<HEAD>52 Students Arrested After Takeover Of University of Massachusetts
Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fifty-two students were arrested Tuesday evening after occupying a University of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> building overnight to protest Defense Department-funded research. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, thousands of <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> students got an unscheduled holiday after demonstrators occupied the campus administration building to protest possible tuition increases, prompting officials to suspend classes. About 60 police in riot gear arrived at the University of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> around 5 p.m.. About two hours later, a bus drove away with 29 students who had camped inside Memorial Hall Those students were charged with trespassing, and another 23 students were arrested for lying in front of the bus to prevent it from leaving, police said. About 300 students stood outside the building chanting and looking on as the students inside the hall were arrested. About 35 students had occupied Memorial Hall since 1 p.m. Monday. They declined an offer to meet with administrators in the provost's office Tuesday morning, and instead presented a list of demands that included a halt to all <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> research at the 25,000-student campus. About 40 students left the building Tuesday morning after several university administrators told them they would be arrested after 5 p.m., said university spokeswoman <PERSON> Jeanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>. The takeover was the second at the western <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> campus in a week. Seven protesters were arrested April 19 on charges of disorderly conduct and trespassing after also demonstrating against military-funded research on campus, particularly research into anthrax. All research at the university is non-classified and researchers must make their work public under university rules. About $ 11.6 million, or 22 percent of grant money received at the university, came from the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in 1988, according to the school. Chancellor <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Duffey </PERSON> issued a statement telling the students the research would continue on campus until school administrators decide differently. `` The policy will not be negotiated with students,'' <PERSON> Duffey </PERSON> said. The latest occupation began when students rallying Monday at the Student Union against military research marched toward the administration building. Several then ducked into Memorial Hall en route, and more followed. Members of the local chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Friends </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> have contended that the research is dangerous to the town, promotes militarism and should be banned. The university has argued the purpose of the anthrax research is peaceful and the strain of bacteria used is non-virulent and has been under study at the school for 23 years without incident. The <LOCATION> Amherst </LOCATION> health board has scheduled a hearing for Wednesday on the question of the safety of the anthrax research. Tuesday was the first time since 1969 that classes at <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> have been canceled because of student protests, said school spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> DeCiccio </PERSON>. Protesters demanding a face-to-face meeting with Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said they feared tuition at the college _ now $ 1,250 a year _ would be increased and the college staff would be reduced because of state budget cuts. The governor had no immediate comment. Tuition for next year has not been set, <PERSON> DeCiccio </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
