<HEAD>Senators: U.S. Cannot `Wimp Out' on Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can not `` wimp out'' on fraud in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s upcoming presidential vote and still maintain credibility in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, four <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senators said Monday after touring the region. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sens. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCain </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ariz </LOCATION>., <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Robb </PERSON>, D-Va., and <PERSON> Connie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Fla </LOCATION>., hopscotched through <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> over the weekend, visiting with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> The scheduled May 7 election in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, which the senators said is widely expected to be stacked in favor of Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s candidate, is a test of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attitudes toward next year's Nicaraguan elections `` We can not allow to go unchallenged what is obviously a massively fraudulent election in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> McCain </PERSON>. The senators called <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> a test in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sincerity, saying the nation's actions will be used to judge attitudes toward next February's elections in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, which pit a leftist Sandinista government against the U.S.-backed Contra rebels. `` If we wimp out in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, and passively let a fraudulent election go forward ... I think our moral standing within <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and our credibility to the world community will be seriously compromised,'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must immediately focus world attention on <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, persuading as many foreign observers as possible to oversee the vote even though <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> has sought to ban such activities. `` One of the things we have failed to do is to bring international pressure with respect to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said reports that President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had approved aid to the Panamanian opposition were understandable, because the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has legitimate economic and military interests in the nation, especially the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>. But he said he was puzzled by the $ 10 million amount reported. `` I was surpised, because the people with whom we met indicated they were expecting to spend approximately $ 1 million on the oppsoition campaign, and they had already raised a substantial amount of that,'' the senator said. `` I was unclear where the figure $ 10 million came from.'' In <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, the senators said, Sandinista foreign ministry official <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> met with the senators to discuss next year's scheduled election in that country But <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> refused to answer the senators when they asked point-blank if the Sandinistas would peacefully transfer power to the winners of the February 1990 election, <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said. In a visit to the Yamales Contra camp in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said, he found the rebels in high spirits. He said they would prefer to be fighting, but understood their role in pressuring the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> to comply with their commitment to democratize <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
