<HEAD>Government Mandates Use of Seatbelts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Drivers and passengers in this car-mad country will have to buckle up beginning Thursday and keep the bambini in the back seat, the government announced. A communique from Premier <PERSON> Ciriaco </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Mita </PERSON>'s office Monday said that people caught without their seat belts on will be subject to fines ranging from 12,000 lire -LRB- $ 9 -RRB- to 50,000 lire -LRB- $ 37 -RRB-. The regulations do not apply to pregnant women. The new rules also require babies and toddlers to be in car seats and relegate children up to the age of 12 to the back seat. The regulations were drawn up by the ministries of the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>.
