<HEAD>Lucille Ball Improving, Daughter Says Hairdo Utmost Post-Surgery
Worry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Comedian <PERSON> Lucille </PERSON> <PERSON> Ball </PERSON>'s first words to her daughter after last week's emergency heart surgery was about her hairdresser's appointment, actress <PERSON> Lucie </PERSON> <PERSON> Arnaz </PERSON> says. `` I went to mom's bedside where she was all tied to tubes and things and I told her, ` Hello mom, I love you,''' Miss <PERSON> Arnaz </PERSON> told 150 people Monday at the <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hotel </LOCATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> Second Century Award ceremony. `` She mumbled something under the oxygen mask, but I said I could n't hear her. Finally I asked the nurse if I could lift the mask a little to hear what she was saying. So I did, and mom said, ` Would n't you know _ this is the day I was going to get my hair done.''' Miss <PERSON> Ball </PERSON> was honored for her work in helping young people in the entertainment field. Miss <PERSON> Arnaz </PERSON> accepted the award on her mother's behalf. The 77-year-old actress was in serious condition and improving daily, said <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Wise </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Cedars-Sinai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. `` The outlook is very encouraging,'' he said. `` Her doctors have her in the chair for longer periods each day. Her spirits are good and she's cracking jokes.'' She was moved Monday from the cardiac surgical intensive care unit to a step-down unit, `` technically another intensive care unit,'' said Wise. `` She should be in her own room toward the end of the week. At the luncheon, Miss <PERSON> Arnaz </PERSON> said she was glad the award was n't postponed after her mother's heart attack `` because it means very, very much to her at this time. Presenting the award, comedian <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> told of being visited by Miss Ball on the second night of her <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> show, `` Once Upon a Mattress.'' `` She came backstage to visit us all and she spent 30 to 35 minutes in my dressing room answering my questions,'' Miss <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> said. Miss Ball's husband, <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Morton </PERSON>, also attended the luncheon, where guests signed a huge card with the `` I Love Lucy'' heart logo and the words, `` We Love <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> _ Get Well Soon.'' Wise said the mounds of get-well wishes arriving at the hospital represents the biggest outpouring of affection for any celebrity confined to <ORGANIZATION> Cedars-Sinai </ORGANIZATION>, known as the `` hospital to the stars.'' `` We've received a tidal wave of mail with a couple thousand letters coming in today,'' said Wise. `` It's taken four volunteers several hours to sort it. She wants everything sorted so she can see every one of them when she gets home.'' Inside a package addressed to Miss Ball, <PERSON> Wise </PERSON> said, `` You can hear ` Twinkle, Twinkle Little Star' playing on a music box inside.'' The surgery was performed April 18 when doctors replaced her aorta and aortic valve with the donated organ tissue of a 27-year-old man.
