<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0680,0745</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon and State Squabble Over Cleanup, Rough Weather Slows Work</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with more on cleanup, salmon being released
in Prince William Sound, comments by Quayle; CORRECTS that halibut decision
will be Wednesday, sted Tuesday; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s top environmentalist squabbled over the pace of the oil spill cleanup Monday as skimmers in the Gulf of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> sought refuge from rough seas for the second day in a row. Hatchery owners on Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>, meanwhile, announced that 24 million salmon fry have been released into the sound, where they must swim through seas hit by the spill. The salmon had to be released Sunday and Monday in conjunction with the bloom of plankton in the sound to enhance their rate of survival. `` We really have no choice but to release them now,'' said <PERSON> Heather </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarty </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the non-profit <ORGANIZATION> Prince </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> William </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sound </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aquaculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which owns three hatcheries in the sound. It is unclear what will happen to the fry as they migrate to the open sea if they encounter oil, <PERSON> McCarty </PERSON> said. As cleanup work continued in the sound, gale warnings and seas swelling to 18 feet kept aircraft on the ground and skimmers close to shore Monday, said coordinators of the military's role in the cleanup. Exxon, however, called a news conference to announce that the cleanup was ahead of the pace calculated in the oil company's federally approved plan, which figures the cleanup will be done by Sept. 15 K.T. <PERSON> Koonce </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president for exploration and production, said 70 percent of the 10.1 million-gallon spill had evaporated, dissipated or been recovered. The company said 1.8 gallons had been recovered. An estimated 1.2 million gallons remains afloat. The oil spilled March 24 from the <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION>, a fully loaded tanker that ran aground on <LOCATION> Bligh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reef </LOCATION> as it steered from the Valdez terminal through Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelso </PERSON>, commissioner of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s Despartment of <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION>, questioned <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s claim and said the oil company's efforts remain inadequate. `` I would look carefully at the figure and not take it at face value,'' said <PERSON> Kelso </PERSON>, adding that the estimate was based on <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s computer models and could be off by as much as 50 percent `` What I want to see is some results,'' he said after <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s news conference While the rough seas kicked oil onto beaches that had previously been spared, Monday's weather also broke up oil and increased the likelihood that more crude will be carried to the open seas of the Gulf of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. `` We see this -LRB- storm -RRB- as a good thing,'' said <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Gleason </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. Fishermen from Homer and other maritime communities south of <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION> have sewn absorbent material into nets and are picking up oil in much the same way they might be gathering herring this time of year. A cleanup priority has been set for beaches where seals come out with their pups each summer. Thousands of sea birds and hundreds of otters already have been found dead. State officials have canceled or postponed herring, black cod and shrimp harvests in the sound, and closed a portion of the <LOCATION> Kodiak </LOCATION> herring fishing grounds. Fisheries officials in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> were expected to decide Wednesday whether to cancel the May 15-16 halibut season. Heavy oil has been reported around the <LOCATION> Barren </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> at the mouth of <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Inlet </LOCATION> where many large boats congregate for the 24-hour open season. In <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, meanwhile, Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> warned oil companies not to use the nation's worst oil spill as an excuse to raise gasoline prices. `` If they are, it is going to be a very difficult situation for them,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, who plans a firsthand look at the cleanup next month, said in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. Allegations have been made that a temporary shortage of oil caused by the spill was used a pretext for gas price hikes. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> made his comments after meeting with former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> as he left on a trip to <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. He is scheduled to visit Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> on his way back May 4. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said he would tour the area, and collect information for President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>.
