<HEAD>Expanding AP Service Offers New Products, Faster Delivery Within
A Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Associated Press will introduce three new services for readers this year to help meet the changing needs of the news industry, <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> President and General Manager <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boccardi </PERSON> said. `` I want to reaffirm something that I think you know is true, at least I hope you know is true,'' <PERSON> Boccardi </PERSON> told news executives at the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> annual meeting Monday. `` That is that I want quality service and responsiveness to be the twin themes of everything the AP does.'' Earlier Monday, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> both addressed the annual meeting and luncheon, highlighting the start of the 103rd annual convention of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, reporting on his first 100 days in office, listed among his accomplishments savings and loan legislation, ethics proposals, the beginning of a war on drugs and agreements with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on the federal budget and Contra aid. `` In three short months we've made a good start coming to grips with issues demanding urgent attention and decisive action,'' he said. At the same time, defense and foreign policy reviews, environmental legislation and a program to deal with homelessness `` are all on the near horizon,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> added. He also suggested his relationship with the media had matured after a sometimes-rocky presidential campaign. `` Both of us, government and the news media, need one another and we owe each other a measure of respect, honesty and integrity equal to the work we're engaged in,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. The president also pledged continued administration efforts to win the release of <PERSON> Terry </PER