<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia-Vietnam     04-25 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia-Vietnam,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>Withdrawal Could Improve International Climate For Vietnam ^Eds:
Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When it withdraws from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> will be at peace for the first time since its war for independence began half a century ago against the French, Japanese and eventually the Americans. Reformers now in control hope ending nearly 11 years of occupation will bring better relations with the outside world, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. They believe <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> risks economic disaster without expanded trade and assistance from abroad. Orders for <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s invasion of neighboring <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in December 1978 came from founders of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> made inflexible by the long struggle. Several have resigned or died since, and the reformers pledge to withdraw the remaining occupation forces by Sept. 30. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> says 50,000 of its soldiers remain in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, but foreign intelligence estimates put the number as high as 70,000. A new and bloodier round of civil war between the Hanoi-sponsored Cambodian government and the three-party guerrilla groups opposing it may begin after the withdrawal, but the departure will be a boon to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. Its occupation, aided by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, angered nations on which Vietnamese trade and economic development depend, such as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations: <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brunei </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s invasion overthrew the brutal <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> regime, which was allied with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, and the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> army made a punitive strike into <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> early in 1979. Because of sanctions and its isolation, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> soon found itself in worse shape economically than the devastated country it had occupied. <PERSON> Ngo </PERSON> <PERSON> Dien </PERSON>, Vietnamese ambassador to <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, says relations with <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have improved and trade along the <LOCATION> China-Vietnam </LOCATION> frontier has resumed. `` After the withdrawal, we will see even more changes,'' he added. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> says it will not consider aid or diplomatic relations until Vietnamese military forces leave <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, but <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>'s pledge and its efforts to account for Americans still missing from the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> war have caused more <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> congressmen to recommend quicker reconciliation. <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> talks of turning <LOCATION> Indochina </LOCATION>'s `` battlefields into markets.'' As a condition for a return to normal relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has demanded that <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> force <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> to leave <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, leaders of the two countries, are to meet next month in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> for the Chinese-Soviet summit in 30 years. Asked whether <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> made its decision under Soviet pressure, <PERSON> Ngo </PERSON> <PERSON> Dien </PERSON> said: `` Mr. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> of course welcomed the withdrawal because he has something in his hands for the summit.'' `` Some people may call it pressure. Some people may call it good coordination between close friends who have the same aim.'' Improving relations with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> might enable the non-communist world to wean it from dependence on the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and encourage the limited steps <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> has taken toward a more open, freer society. For three centuries, <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> has found itself shrinking with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s steady territorial expansion. Communist-led Vietnamese guerrillas used Cambodian and Laotian territory as sanctuaries and supply routes for the war against the French and the Americans, and helped communist movements to victory in the two countries. Since economic reformer <PERSON> Nguyen </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Linh </PERSON> became party chief in late 1986, however, <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> has taken steps to get out of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and has withdrawn troops from <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION>. A Soviet diplomat based in <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> said privately that some Vietnamese `` saw themselves as the rulers of this country, but luckily the others got the upper hand.'' <PERSON> Uch </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiman </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s political department in the government installed by <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, suggested greater independence for <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> will accompany the end of occupation. `` For the moment, I think we have to stick together because of the political configuration in the region, but I think in the future we do n't want to wall ourselves in,'' he said. `` We certainly want to expand our relations to all neighboring countries, especially the <ORGANIZATION> ASEAN </ORGANIZATION> countries.'' According to the Soviet diplomat, `` <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s influence will remain'' after withdrawal, `` but it will not be monopolistic.'' <ORGANIZATION> Ngo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dien </ORGANIZATION> suggested <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> would stop using military means to resolve problems and would fix its attention on economic development.
