<HEAD>Midway Plane Returns To Airport As Flames Shoot From Engine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A DC-9 jet carrying 55 passengers was forced to turn around minutes after takeoff when the pilot discovered flames shooting from an engine. The <ORGANIZATION> Midway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> twin-engine jet landed safely at <LOCATION> Midway </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> on the city's southwest side with no injuries, said <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the airline. The plane had departed for <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> at 8 p.m. and returned to Midway eight minutes later. Ms. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said a compressor, which mixes air and fuel, failed and the fuel ignited as it was discharged out of the rear of the engine. She compared it to a car backfiring _ `` a big backfire from a big engine.'' `` I'm sure the passengers heard a loud bang and the pilot noticed a loss of power in the engine,'' Ms. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said Emergency vehicles were summoned as the plane returned using only one engine. Ms. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said the passengers were assigned to other flights to <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>.
