<HEAD>Chairman Wants to Eliminate New York's Board of Estimate, Expand
Council</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of a commission appointed to rework the city's unconstitutional government proposed eliminating the powerful <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estimate </ORGANIZATION> on Monday and expanding the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to 50 members. The mayor would take control of contracts _ a lightning rod in view of the city corruption scandals surrounding Board of Estimate-awarded contracts that have resulted in criminal convictions. However, various bodies would have oversight responsibilities. Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> and City Comptroller <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldin </PERSON> were generally pleased by the proposals made by <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> A.O </PERSON>. <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Charter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revision </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. The five borough presidents who sit on the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estimate </ORGANIZATION> opposed them, however, with <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Golden </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> saying <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON> `` is telling the boroughs to drop dead.'' At a public hearing, <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON> also put forth the idea of a bicameral legislature, but not as a formal proposal. He said a new, 19-member house would be the equal of the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, but that it would only work if it gave greater representation to blacks and Hispanics. The commission was created by the mayor to look into ways city government could restructure itself as court challenges to the Board of Estimate made their way through the legal system. In March, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled that the board was unconstitutional because it violated the one-person, one-vote doctrine by giving each borough equal weight even though they varied widely in population. The commission, which had been on hold pending the court's ruling, then went into high gear with a self-imposed mandate to get its proposals on the November ballot The chairman's proposals are the first formal agenda around which the 15-member commission can debate. <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON> presented part of the proposals Monday for discussion with the rest to be reviewed by the commission Tuesday. His proposals are not final. Under his proposals, the powers of the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estimate </ORGANIZATION>, made up of the borough presidents, the mayor, the city council president and the comptroller, would be dispersed. The comptroller no longer would be involved in policy and would be limited to fiscal matters and oversight and audit functions on contracts. `` I think it is a useful focus for reconstituting the city government,'' Comptroller <PERSON> Goldin </PERSON> said. `` The comptroller's role has always been overwhelmingly fiscal. This recognizes that reality.'' The <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> would expand from 35 to 50 members, with the districts to correspond as closely as possible to community board districts. The city council president would continue as an ombudsman.
