<HEAD>Police To Investigate Palestinian Press Cards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police Minister <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bar-Lev </PERSON> says he has ordered an investigation into press cards Palestinians are issuing foreign journalists for the occupied lands, where <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> police have posed as reporters. Many foreign reporters have acquired such cards since a scandal last month involving two police officers who were filmed using a `` Press'' sign on their vehicle during a raid against Arab rioters in east <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>. Police later imposed limitations on the practice, but did not rule it out altogether, saying it was a legitimate decoy method in dealing with the 16-month Palestinian uprising. In addition, Jewish settlers living in the occupied lands have sometimes used `` Press'' signs to pass unharmed through Palestinian roadblocks where stone-throwers hurl rocks at cars with the yellow Israeli license plates. Palestinians have alleged that <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> secret service agents were also presenting themselves as journalists. Masked Palestinian activists have often stopped reporters to check their credentials. <PERSON> Bar-Lev </PERSON> said on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio Monday that police would look into the Palestinian-issued press cards. `` Those issuing these cards are an organization in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` We will check if it's against the law, and what law, and what steps can we take against people issuing these cards.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Slater </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said foreign journalists had to use the Palestinian cards because <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> security officials had posed as journalists. `` After police were posing as journalists, the Palestinians saw the Israeli press cards as identifying either a real journalist or a police agent,'' he said on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio. `` I can understand that the Palestinians want to make our work easier and give us their cards.'' `` It gives them some possibility to check if the man is really a reporter and we accept it, it makes it easier for us,'' said <PERSON> Slater </PERSON>, whose organization represents 200 to 300 foreign journalists posted in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` If a reporter has to get a card from some element, it's not a violation of some norm but a natural thing in every conflict in the world ... in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' he added. But <PERSON> Yoram </PERSON> <PERSON> Ettinger </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, said that `` the very acceptance of a Palestinian card in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, I think, is a challenge to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s sovereignty.'' `` As far as I know the card has a map of <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION> from the <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> river to the sea which means the elimination of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>,'' he said on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio. Neither <PERSON> Slater </PERSON> nor <PERSON> Ettinger </PERSON> identified the organization that produces the press cards. The Israeli news agency <ORGANIZATION> Itim </ORGANIZATION> said it was a Jerusalem-based organization called `` Palestinian Press Office.'' <PERSON> Radwan </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayyash </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journalists </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> based in east <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, said his office has been issuing cards for foreign journalists for the last two years. There is no map on these cards. `` The cards are not a challenge to anybody and have no political significance whatsoever,'' <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayyash </PERSON> said. `` It has nothing to do with the uprising or an independent Palestinian state. Moreover, our association has a license from the Israeli <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>.'' He said the cards were issued upon request by foreign reporters who `` told us, we are harmed by your people, would you do something to help us and we did.''
