<TEXT>
 Police in the southern city of <LOCATION> Changsha </LOCATION> arrested 98 people, just six of them students, for looting that occurred during a student demonstration last weekend, an official newspaper reported today. The People's Daily said those arrested were caught looting 28 shops and a shopping arcade Saturday in what the official press described as the worst rioting in 40 years of Communist rule. Rioting also broke out Saturday in the ancient capital of <LOCATION> Xian </LOCATION>, with crowds throwing rocks and setting fire to buildings and vehicles. The daily said that of the 98 detained in <LOCATION> Changsha </LOCATION>, 32 were workers, 28 were unemployed, 26 were peasants, six were self-employed and six were students. It said 52 were waiting trial. The outbreaks of violence occurred as university students in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and other cities took to the streets to mourn former <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON>, a reformist who died April 15, and call for democratic reforms. In <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> on Saturday, 150,000 students congregated on Tiananmen Square in the center of the city for a peaceful demonstration. Student leaders in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> have made efforts to keep unemployed youth and other potential troublemakers out of their ranks. Most of the other demonstrations have also been peaceful, although foreign sources said students at the <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hefei </LOCATION>, eastern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, last week smashed windows and furniture in a campus cafeteria.
