<HEAD>Safety Board Looking At California Air Traffic Control Operation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>EDS: NTSB meeting at 9:30 a.m. EDT, air traffic control later on
agenda; lead likely about noon. ^By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> staff report recommends several changes in air traffic control operations over southern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> as a result of incidents of airplanes flying too close together, a board source says. The board was taking up the report at its public meeting today after its investigation into the `` loss of standard separation'' between a <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> jumbo jet and an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jetliner on Feb. 13 over <LOCATION> Westminster </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The report recommends increases in staff and training at the Coast Terminal Radar Approach Control Facility in <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, some improvements and expansion of the facility itself and several technical changes, the source said, speaking on condition of anonymity. The investigation of the British Airways-American incident was expanded to cover seven other operational errors over the past year at the facility just south of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. The traffic control operation handles about half a million flights a year in the skies between <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, which is one of the busiest flight areas in the country outside major airport control zones. The board meeting on <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> air traffic control problems comes two days after two reports of airliners nearly colliding in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> area. A <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> jumbo jet coming in from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and a commuter plane flew about 100 feet apart as they approached <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION> on Sunday, and 45 minutes later a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 en route from <LOCATION> LaGuardia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> reported coming within 400 yards of a small <ORGANIZATION> Cessna </ORGANIZATION> plane near <LOCATION> Westchester </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. The two jetliners in the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> incident flew within 1.9 miles of each other, both at 9,000 feet, and <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> officials at the time said the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> pilot had to make a hasty turn to avoid a collision. Although the planes were not close enough for the incident to be considered a `` near miss,'' <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> rules say they should have been at least three miles apart horizontally and 1,000 feet vertically. The British <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 was carrying 286 people from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> plane, a British Aerospace 146 with 70 people aboard, was landing at <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> after being diverted from <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> airport, whose runway had been closed due to a power failure. The board inquiry is its first major investigation into an air traffic control operation since the board began recommending upgrading at <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s O ` Hare International Airport after operational errors increased in 1986. O'Hare had more than 30 flight-handling errors in 1988, and the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> has ordered several changes, including the hiring of additional controllers.
