<HEAD>St Paddy's Surprise: Three Mile Island Siren Jolted Residents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> wants to know why a warning siren blared for 50 minutes near the <LOCATION> Three </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> nuclear plant on St. Patrick's Day, frightening residents enough that some began to pack their belongings. The siren was heard by residents of <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, late in the evening of March 17 _ 11 days before the 10th anniversary of the nation's worst commercial accident at the plant. During the accident, pregnant women and preschoolers had been advised to evacuate within five miles of the two reactors. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON> said he, his wife and two children thought it was an `` odd time for a test'' when they were awakened by the siren last month at 11:20 p.m. It lasted until 12:10 a.m., and the couple said they could get no information from neighbors, television and radio stations, or the police on the reason why. `` Unless you were involved, you can not realize the anxiety and concern for the health of your family while the siren was sounding, nor can you share my anger at not being able to find out what was happening,'' <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON> said in a March 23 letter to the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Reactor Safeguards. `` Those 50 minutes seemed like hours to me, my family and our neighbors,'' he said. `` Some of the neighbors began to pack up and leave the area. Even after the siren stopped, we had no idea if there was a problem.'' The advisory panel said it considered <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON>'s letter serious enough to warrant an investigation by the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> staff and GPU Nuclear, the plant operator. `` Events of the type described in Mr. <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON>'s lett