</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MACON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Privacy was hard to come by in their parking lot home, but a brown killdeer successfully hatched a family in front of a group of birdwatchers. Decoy tactics by her mate drew little attention as those who had marveled at the nest witnessed the hatching of four eggs Friday. Last month, the killdeer and her mate spent about 10 days digging out their nest in the mobile home parking lot. Oversized trucks and mobile homes moved within feet of the nest, but the mother did not abandon her duty unless the male took over. Although both parents shooed away curious humans, the first two plum-sized baby birds sneaked out and, on wobbly legs, scampered inches toward an onlooker. `` Last week she took off and he sat on the eggs awhile,'' said <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Karr </PERSON>, a bird-watcher and employee at <ORGANIZATION> Sonshine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homes </ORGANIZATION>, where the birds hatched. Co-worker <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Weekley </PERSON> added: `` She'll be glad when the baby birds are gone. I'll bet she'll never come here again.'' After the chicks hatched, the killdeer family escaped to the edge of the parking lot, <PERSON> Karr </PERSON> said Monday. He said he has seen the parents, but the babies `` are nowhere to be found.'' The brown killdeer has orange markings and typically is a shore bird. About 10 inches long, it runs on long, spindly legs and often nests in gravel.
