<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> took office as prime minister, skeptics doubted that the man known for his cautious, back-room political style would be able to create a commanding role for <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> on the international stage. Ironically, he proved successful at his diplomatic efforts, but it was his main strength _ fund-raising for the governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> _ that brought him down after only 18 months on the job. In announcing today that he intended to resign as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s 46th prime minister, <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> took responsibility for a scandal that made the country's <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s least popular prime minister since World War II, according to polls. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>, 65, took over as prime minister from the charismatic <PERSON> Yasuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON> in November 1987. Within two months of taking office he had visited the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and established a first-name relationship with former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. He traveled frequently to other countries. Under <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s leadership, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> surpassed the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as the world's biggest foreign aid donor to developing countries. It also earned new respect as a contributor to diplomatic efforts. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> also played busy host to dignitaries from 164 nations in February at the state funeral for Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>, an unprecedented gathering of world leaders. But his popularity sagged among the Japanese with increasing revelations that he and members of his <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> had accepted bargain-priced stocks and other donations from the <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, an information conglomerate that allegedly attempted to buy government influence. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> acknowledged receiving more than $ 1 million from Recruit. He also confirmed that he borrowed about $ 381,700 from the company in 1987 and repaid the money a few months later. Recruit was a major donor to <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s fund-raising parties. Party tickets are an important tool in raising the money needed to gain and maintain office in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> was partly motivated to resign out of fear his term would be remembered for nothing but the Recruit scandal, said <PERSON> Yotaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Konaka </PERSON>, a political analyst. <PERSON> Konaka </PERSON> said the prime minister did not want to see the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> lose its 35-year hold on the nation's parliament in summer elections, or watch his newly implemented _ and highly unpopular _ tax reform program be canceled. `` Other than the emperor's funeral, he must have realized that the tax reform was his only domestic achievement,'' <PERSON> Konaka </PERSON> said. `` If the tax reform is erased, it will make him a prime minister with no achievement whatsoever.'' The eldest son of a rice-wine brewing family, <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> was born Feb. 26, 1924, in a village in western <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. After serving as a pilot trainee at the end of World War II, he completed his university studies, taught English and social studies for several years, and then turned to politics. He was elected to his local state assembly at 27, and then won a seat in the powerful lower house of the <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> in 1958 at age 34. His political skills gained him key posts. He became finance minister in 1979 under Prime Minister <PERSON> Masayoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Ohira </PERSON> and continued to hold that high post under <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON>'s administration.
