<HEAD>American Citizen Disappears In Israeli Military Custody</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To CORRECT uprising death figure to 444, SUB penultimate graf.
^An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUFR MALIK, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two Palestinians who are American citizens have become entangled in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s military justice system and one disappeared after answering a summons to an army headuarters. Relatives of <PERSON> Jafer </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamayel </PERSON>, 25, said he complied with the army summons on April 13 and they have since been unable to locate him. The other American, 16-year-old <PERSON> Mansour </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdallah </PERSON>, was accused of throwing stones and has been held for three months without bail and without appearing in court, his lawyer said. Human rights activists say <PERSON> Hamayel </PERSON> and <PERSON> Abdallah </PERSON> are among thousands of Palestinians who are being denied basic legal rights under military justice in effect in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. Army officials deny the allegations, saying the military has set up a special office to help lawyers find clients and that bail has been granted in hundreds of cases. `` We believe we have a liberal judicial system in the territories, but we should not be judged in the same context as Western countries that are not in a state of war,'' an army official said earlier this year. In the cases of <PERSON> Hamayel </PERSON> and <PERSON> Abdallah </PERSON>, both of whom had lived in <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, the army was unable to locate either one even after being given details three days earlier by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. An army official, who could not be identified under military regulations, said he could not locate them because he did not have Israeli-issued identification numbers for them. Palestinian lawyer <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuttab </PERSON> said <PERSON> Abdallah </PERSON> has only a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> passport and not an Israeli identity card. <PERSON> Hamayel </PERSON>'s relatives said he had his Israeli card with him when he disappeared and they did not know the number. <PERSON> Hamayel </PERSON> was born in <PERSON> Kufr </PERSON> <PERSON> Malik </PERSON>, a mountain village known for its resistance to <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> occupation. On a visit Monday to the village 15 miles north of <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> slogans, <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> flags and a poster of <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> adorned the main square. <PERSON> Hamayel </PERSON> left <PERSON> Kufr </PERSON> <PERSON> Malik </PERSON> in 1983 after being imprisoned for three months on charges of violating <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> law by raising <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> flags, said his uncle, <PERSON> Ata </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamayel </PERSON>, 39. He said <PERSON> Jafer </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamayel </PERSON> then lived for six years in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, joining his parents who went to the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> island in 1966 and now own a clothing store. The uncle said the young man had studied accounting at <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> InterAmerican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Ata </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamayel </PERSON> gave this account of his nephew's disappearance: Several months ago <PERSON> Jafer </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamayel </PERSON> became a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen. On April 4, he returned to <PERSON> Kufr </PERSON> <PERSON> Malik </PERSON> to renew his Israeli-issued identity card. Without the card he would lose the right to live in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>. Shortly after his arrival he was given a summons to appear at the military headquarters in <LOCATION> Ramallah </LOCATION> and went there April 13. Later that day, a <LOCATION> Ramallah </LOCATION> man saw <PERSON> Jafer </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamayel </PERSON> being held in a tent jail at the headquarters but the family has not seen him since and has not been notified by the army of his fate. Ata <PERSON> Hamayel </PERSON> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consular officials were refused permission to see his nephew at the <LOCATION> Ramallah </LOCATION> headquarters. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consulate </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Good </PERSON> said efforts were made to find <PERSON> Jafer </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamayel </PERSON> but `` we have n't been able to make contact with him yet.'' Good refused to discuss details of the case. <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Sayyad </PERSON>, <PERSON> Abdallah </PERSON>'s lawyer, said the youth was arrested Jan. 23 in his native <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> village of <LOCATION> Surda </LOCATION> on charges of throwing stones and setting up road barricades. <PERSON> Sayyad </PERSON> said military officials failed to present <PERSON> Abdallah </PERSON> at court hearings March 19 and March 30 and have not responded to a request that the youth be released on bail. The lawyer said another court hearing is scheduled for Sunday. Good said consular officials visited <PERSON> Abdallah </PERSON> on March 24 and are trying to get him released on bail. He said <PERSON> Abdallah </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hamayel </PERSON> are the only two Palestinian-Americans being held under military detention. Good said he did know how many American citizens have been arrested since the Palestinian uprising began in December 1987 in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> but added: `` We never had more than three or four at a time.'' About 7,000 Palestinians with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> passports live in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and Israeli-annexed Arab east <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, according to Good. He said only a few live in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. Army officials say at least 20,000 Palestinians have been arrested during the uprising, which has claimed the lives of 444 Palestinians and 18 Israelis. Army figures showed 6,650 Palestinians were being detained as of early April with 3,627 awaiting trial, 1,187 held under emergency laws that require no charges or trial, 974 awaiting sentencing and 862 serving sentences.
