<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> put a hand on an old family bible, looked into the eyes of an old family friend and took the oath of mayor, a job his late father held for 21 years. But in Orchestra Hall, surrounded by many state and local officials whose careers started with the blessing of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> boss <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, the new mayor said his administration would not resemble his father's vaunted army of loyal foot soldiers. `` Business as usual is a prescription for failure,'' he said Monday after he took the oath on his 47th birthday, noting that his father instilled him with values, but policies will be his own. `` The old ways of doing business simply are n't adequate to cope with the new challenges we face,'' <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> said City Hall will be open to all _ a pledge that produced optimism among his black election opponents and their supporters. <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> is the largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> city to replace a black mayor with a white. `` He appears to be using a reconciling approach as opposed to a polarizing approach, and that is good,'' said <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who supported two blacks and had warned during the campaign that <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> would return to the machine politics that marked the elder <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s reign. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> was sworn in by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> <PERSON> Marovitz </PERSON>, a family friend who presided at the elder <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s six inaugurations. `` This is a sentimental journey for me,'' said the 83-year-old judge. The new mayor delivered an upbeat speech, mentioning few specific goals but acknowledging that the city's school system, labeled the worst in the nation by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Education Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, needs an overhaul. `` Today our foundation is crumbling and nothing but genuine school reform will repair it,'' <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> said. The former <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> prosecutor was elected April 4 to complete the last two years of the second term of the late <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s first black mayor. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> succeeds <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, who had been acting mayor since <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s death 17 months ago. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> defeated <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, who is black, in the Democratic primary Feb. 28 and then defeated black <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON> <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> and Republican <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Vrdolyak </PERSON> in the general election. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s first election in 1983 led to a few years of bitter debate in <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, with a white majority blocking his programs. <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> predicted that black aldermen would not act as obstructionists during <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s term. `` Wherever he -LRB- <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> -RRB- is correct, we're going to move right along with him,'' <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said, but if aldermen disagree with the mayor they will `` protect the gains of this community.''
