<TEXT>
 A pudgy super-hacker who agreed to plead guilty and spend a year in prison for computer fraud must stand trial after all because a judge thinks the proposed sentence is n't harsh enough <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Mariana </PERSON> <PERSON> Pfaelzer </PERSON> surprised <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON>, his defense attorney and a prosecutor by rejecting their plea agreement on Monday and ordering <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON> to trial. `` You have been engaged in this activity for far too long and no one has adequately punished you,'' the judge told the defendant, citing two previous convictions for computer fraud in 1981 and 1987. `` This is the last time you are going to do this.'' The judge suggested the 25-year-old <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON> remains a danger and rejected a prosecutor's belated claim that <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON> did n't destroy anything of value. <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON>, clad in a blue prison uniform, appeared stunned by the rejection. Outside court, defense lawyer <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> expressed disappointment and said the judge's action took him by surprise. `` She obviously considers him a far greater menace than I do or the government does,'' he said. <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> said it was unlikely <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON> would agree to any new bargain involving a longer sentence. When the case began last December, prosecutors portrayed <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON> as a brilliant youth obsessed with junk food and computers who used the code name `` Condor'' to infiltrate computer systems in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. They suggested he might have gained access to top secret <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> computers, but such charges were never brought. Last month, they agreed to a plea bargain. Under his plea, <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON> had admitted he infiltrated <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s computer system and stole one of its programs. He also admitted stealing 16 <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> telephone codes and using them to make long-distance calls for free. The prosecution had agreed to dismiss two additional charges, one of which alleged <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON> infiltrated the computer system of <ORGANIZATION> Leeds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. If <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON> stands trial, those charges would be reinstated. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> told the judge he had `` thought long and hard'' before entering the agreement and concluded that <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON>'s actions were n't seriously destructive. `` This is not a case where Mr. <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON> destroyed anyone's computer or inserted viruses in a computer,'' he told the judge He also noted that the government would have to grant immunity to an alleged co-conspirator, <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> DiCicco </PERSON>, to obtain his testimony against <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Pfaelzer </PERSON> was unmoved. `` I do n't think a year is long enough. And I'm not going to honor the agreement,'' she said. A pretrial report recommended a higher sentence, she noted.
