<HEAD>Proposals to Revamp Government Get Mixed Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A plan to make the city's government constitutional by expanding the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and setting up a new commission drew good reviews from the mayor but was panned by presidents of the five boroughs. <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> A.O </PERSON>. <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Charter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revision </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, outlined proposals Monday that would give the mayor more direct control over awarding contracts, previously the domain of the powerful Board of Estimate. The mayor would be required to submit his plans to communities for review, though. The proposals also would increase the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to 50 members from 35 and create a new commission to oversee city-owned land, rule on zoning changes and award city franchises, also currently the board's province. The mayor would appoint four of the 11 commission members. The plan comes one month after the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled that the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estimate </ORGANIZATION> was unconstitutional because it violated the one-person, one-vote doctrine. <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON> said he hoped his plan would provide fair representation for all New Yorkers. <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, the city's smallest borough with about 400,000 residents, has the same presence on the board as the other four boroughs, including <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> with 2.2 million residents. <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Borough </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamberti </PERSON> said the proposals `` are a disaster for <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and all local communities. It makes the authority of the mayor almost czar-like.'' <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Borough </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Golden </PERSON> said <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON> `` is telling the boroughs to drop dead.'' But <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON> said the plan would give borough leaders more say over land use, budget formulation and budget oversight. Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> and City Comptroller <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldin </PERSON> were generally pleased by the proposals. `` The principles that the chairman lays out in his report would seem to be quite positive,'' said mayoral spokesman <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> <PERSON> Chanin </PERSON>. Under the plan, the comptroller no longer would be involved in policy and would be limited to fiscal matters and oversight and audit functions on contracts. `` The comptroller's role has always been overwhelmingly fiscal,'' <PERSON> Goldin </PERSON> said. `` This recognizes that reality.'' The Charter Revision Commission, which was created by the mayor, has set a goal of getting a proposal for governmental change on the November ballot. The chairman's proposals are the first formal agenda on which the 15-member commission can debate. They are n't final.
