<HEAD>North Korean Woman Sentenced To Death For Plane Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A confessed North Korean agent wept today as a court sentenced her to death for the 1987 bombing of a South Korean airliner in which 115 people were killed. Officials said they expect 27-year-old <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyon </PERSON> <PERSON> Hui </PERSON> to be pardoned. Ms. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> shook with grief as Judge <PERSON> Chung </PERSON> <PERSON> Sang-hwak </PERSON> pronounced her guilty of violating national security and aviation laws and sentenced her to die by hanging. She said nothing before being whisked away by security agents. Relatives of the victims sat quietly as <PERSON> Chung </PERSON> said there was no doubt that Ms. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> was guilty of planting a bomb aboard a <ORGANIZATION> Korea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 707 that disappeared on Nov. 29, 1987 over the <LOCATION> Andaman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> as it approached the Burmese coast. The plane was en route to <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> confessed on South Korean television in January 1988 that she planted the bomb as part of a plot by senior leaders of communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to disrupt the Olympic Games, held successfully in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> last summer. She said at a hearing on April 4 that she wanted to die to atone for the deaths. She has a week to appeal the sentence, but defense lawyers said no decision had been made on the matter. South Korean officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Ms. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> was expected to be pardoned on grounds she was duped by communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and has repented. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has denied it had anything to do with the plane bombing and has claimed it was engineered by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to embarrass the north. The two Koreas have been bitter rivals since the division of the peninsula at the end of World War II. Judge <PERSON> Chung </PERSON>, who headed the three-judge panel hearing the case, said the destruction of the plane underlined the threat the north poses to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s freedom and survival. `` We have an enemy which always tries to our destroy liberal democratic system. We must face that reality with resolute determination,'' he said in a 13-minute statement. The sentencing came after three hearings during which Ms. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> often sobbed into a hankerchief as she listened to testimony that the plane exploded in less than a second, killing all aboard instantly. The bodies were never recovered. Ms. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> arrived at the courthouse today under heavy security and hundreds of police surrounded the building to prevent protests by angry relatives or a possible threat from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> agents. Relatives of the victims disrupted the earlier proceedings and often yelled `` Kill her!'' They were silent today as <PERSON> Chung </PERSON> read the verdict and gathered in small groups outside afterward. Some relatives expressed satisfaction with the death sentence, but others urged mercy. Ms. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> said she and another intelligence agent pretending to be Japanese tourists planted the bomb disguised as a radio and a liquor bottle when they flew from <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Abu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dhabi </LOCATION>, where they got off. The pair were arrested a short time later in <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION> and attempted to take cyanide hidden in cigarettes. The other agent, an elderly man, died, but <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> recovered and was extradited to <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>.
