shelling details. DELETES 7th to trim. Picks up 8th, ``On Monday ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Christian army units and Syrian gunners poured rocket and artillery fire on <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> in an escalation of violence today, the eve of an Arab League meeting aimed at ending the fighting. Police said at least two people were killed and 16 wounded in the bombardment, which began at midnight and raged until 6 a.m., then dwindled to sporadic exchanges. The deaths raised to 272 killed and 991 wounded the toll since the latest round of fighting broke out March 8 in the 14-year-old civil war that pits Christians against Moslems. The city shook as army troops under Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> fired 155mm and 130mm howitzer and mortar shells into Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. The only sound other than the blasts of shells was the occasional siren of a Civil Defense ambulance. Civilians scurried to basements and underground shelters. The Syrians opened up on east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, the heart of the besieged 310-square-mile Christian enclave, with 240mm mortars and BM-21 launchers, which fire 40 122mm rockets in 20 seconds. Four shells crashed in the garden of east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s Comfort Hotel, which houses offices of <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeepers and the U.N. Relief and <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, police said. Windows were shattered and windshields of five <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> cars were blown out, the hotel and a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> official said. Shells destroyed the facade of the three-story <ORGANIZATION> Goethe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a West German cultural center in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. Police said west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Sahel </LOCATION> hospital on the main airport highway took several direct hits that damaged equipment but hurt no patients. On Monday, Moslem forces fired rockets at a <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> tanker as it delivered fuel to restart power stations, police reported. Much of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, including <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, has been without electricity since fuel for power stations' generators ran out nine days ago. Police said four rockets crashed into the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> about 700 yards from the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> navy tanker, the Penhors, as it unloaded 4,000 tons of fuel in the Christian town of <LOCATION> Zouk </LOCATION> north of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. The salvo was fired despite what <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> officers called `` solid guarantees'' given to French Ambassador <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Blanc </PERSON> by <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> and Syrian commanders that there would be no shooting while the tanker unloaded. The delivery of the fuel oil caused an interruption in the stream of refugees fleeing <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> from the Christian-controlled port of <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION> north of the city. An aide to <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> said he ordered two Cypriot-flag ferries to stop picking up Christians while the Penhors unloaded. Foreign ministers of the 22-member Arab League are to meet in an emergency session in <LOCATION> Tunis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION>, on Wednesday to find ways to end the violence. Three cease-fires arranged by the league have collapsed. An Arab League committee will recommend that the group send an observer force of people from all <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states to monitor a cease-fire, said <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s foreign minister, <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Ahmed </PERSON>. The current fighting erupted after <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> government vying for legitimacy with a rival Moslem cabinet, clamped a blockade on illegal ports run by Moslem militias south of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> in a bid to restore long-eroded state authority. The <ORGANIZATION> Druse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> retaliated by shelling the Christian enclave. They soon were joined by the Syrians, who maintain 40,000 troops in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate. `` The observer force will not be a deterrent one, but rather a symbolic force assigned to oversee a cease-fire,'' <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. The truce would be an interim step aimed at stabilizing the situation in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> until a political solution is worked out, with provisions for arranging presidential elections and the formation of a a coalition government. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> has said it will attend the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> meeting.
