<FIRST>r i PM-India-ColdFusion     04-25 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Cold Fusion,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Scientsts Duplicate Cold Fusion Experiment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BHAGWAN SINGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KALPAKKAM, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists at an Indian laboratory have achieved nuclear fusion in an electrolytic cell, a process first reported by two <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> researchers in March, an Indian researcher said. The experiment at the <ORGANIZATION> Indira </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gandhi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> in this city on the <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bengal </LOCATION> 40 miles south of <LOCATION> Madras </LOCATION> differs slightly from the <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> work. <PERSON> Cherian </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mathews </PERSON> said in an interview that he and two associates achieved the `` cold fusion'' April 16 after three days of experiments. He said the team used titanium cathode and platinum anode dipped in so-called heavy water, which contains a form of hydrogen called deuterium that has a neutron in its nucleus. The <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> researchers had used a cathode made of a palladium, a highly expensive element, to achieve cold fusion. Cold fusion aims at getting the deuterium atoms to fuse, forming helium and releasing energy. The reaction occurs at room temperature and hence is called cold fusion. Previously fusion had been achieved under extremely high temperature and pressure, as seen in the core of the sun. <PERSON> Mathews </PERSON> said his team experimented with ordinary water and heavy water. He said there was a significant increase in temperature -LRB- heat -RRB- during the experiment with heavy water, as compared to ordinary water. That suggests that the reaction involved nuclear processes, such as fusion, rather than chemical processes. Heavy water and ordinary water are chemically identical. The team did not measure the energy output. But <PERSON> Mathews </PERSON> said they had rough estimates of energy during the different experiments. He did not give details. The team also noticed an increase in the number of neutrons emitted but these could not be reproduced at will, he said. <PERSON> Mathews </PERSON>, 50, said he had worked with <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> after receiving a doctorate from <ORGANIZATION> McMaster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hamilton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>.
