<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Lotteries,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Tosses Out Dispute Over Lotteries in Minnesota Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, by a 6-3 vote, today tossed out a dispute over the federal government's power to ban newspapers from publishing lists of winners in privately run lotteries. The justices ruled that a controversy from <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> has become moot because the government no longer intends to enforce the ban. `` We conclude that there is no longer any live controversy on the issue of whether the -LRB- challenged -RRB- statute is constitutional as it applies to prize lists, and that this appeal is moot,'' the court said in an unsigned opinion. Justices <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> cast dissenting votes but did not explain why. Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, in a brief dissenting opinion, said the court should have reversed _ not merely set aside _ a federal judge's ruling that had upheld the publishing ban. The <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> originally challenged a postal law that bars newspapers from carrying advertisements and prize lists. Postal laws currently prohibit use of the mails to disseminate information about any lottery not run by a state. Since nearly all newspapers rely on the mail for at least a portion of their distribution, the postal laws apply to them. But after the justices agreed last October to study the case, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> enacted a new law, to take effect in May 1990, dropping the ban on advertising for private lotteries. The newspaper association and the government agreed to drop that part of the case. Government lawyers then told the justices that the existing ban on publishing prize winners will not be enforced. The dispute had focused on lotteries and other gaming, such as bingo and raffles, sponsored by non-profit, charitable organizations and others. Lawyers for the <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> newspapers said, `` The revenue generated by charitable gaming is very substantial. In <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> alone it appears to exceed $ 200 million per year.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Magnuson </PERSON> upheld the ban on lottery advertising even though he acknowledged that the ads are a constitutionally protected form of commercial speech. The newspaper association appealed. The judge, however, ruled that newspapers can not be barred from running lists of private lottery winners unless such lists are found in advertisements. The government had appealed that part of his ruling. The case is <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, 87-1956.
