<HEAD>Court Upholds law Imposing User Fees on Transporting of Hazardous
Liquids</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A unanimous <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today upheld a 1986 federal law imposing `` safety user fees'' on pipeline companies that transport natural gas and hazardous liquids. The court reversed the ruling of a federal magistrate in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> that the law, that allows the secretary of transportation to impose user fees to pay for pipeline safety programs, unconstitutionally gives the executive branch too much of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' power to impose taxes Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> wrote for the court that the law clearly is not an `` unconstitutional delegation of the taxing power by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to the executive branch.'' The user-fee system is being used to pay for pipeline safety programs costing about $ 8.5 million to $ 9.3 million a year. The law had been challenged by <ORGANIZATION> Mid-America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipeline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a transporter of hazardous liquids. It has been assessed a $ 53,000 fee in 1986 by the secretary of transportation. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Magistrate <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, ruled in 1987 that the assessments are taxes, and therefore the law improperly gives the transportation secretary the power to set tax rates. In her opinion today, however, <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said, `` We need not concern ourselves ... whether the pipeline safety user fees'' are really taxes. Assuming they are, she said, `` We hold that the delegation of discretionary authority under <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' taxing power is subject to no constitutional scrutiny greater than that we have applied to other non-delegation challenges.'' Had the court upheld the magistrate's ruling, its decision could have affected a broad range of federal fees and taxes. As examples, government lawyers cited congressional authorization for the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to assess nuclear power plant operators for licensing and inspection, and for the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to impose fees to pay the cost of its various programs. The assessments may be based on the amount of pipeline miles a company operates, the quantity of natural gas or liquid and how far it is shipped, or the gross revenue of the company. The case is <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Mid-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipeline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 87-2098.
