<HEAD>Gonzalez Offers S&amp;L Bill with Stricter Capital Requirements</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS lead and DELETES 8th graf pvs, In one, to CORRECT by removing
statement that Gonzalez proposing to include subordinated debt in core
capital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> is considering a proposal from its chairman that would force savings and loan owners to back their lending with more of their own capital. According to a draft document circulated among committee members and obtained Monday by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, is offering a plan with moderately stricter capital requirements than the bill passed earlier this month by the subcommittee on financial institutions, chaired by Rep. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON>, D-Ill. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>' committee is scheduled to hold its first public session on the bill Wednesday, after a private meeting of committee Democrats today Both <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>' plan and the subcommittee's bill include a risk-based formula for capital that offers a break to S & amp; Ls making low-risk loans such as home mortgages. But the <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> proposal would require most S & amp; Ls to maintain a somewhat higher base of `` tangible'' or `` real money'' capital, which includes cash and assets readily convertible to cash. The subcommittee's bill provides for a base of tangible capital of $ 1.50 for every $ 100 in loans, while another $ 1.50 could consist of `` goodwill,'' an intangible asset representing the value of an institution's customer loyalty and name recognition. Together, they amount to `` core'' capital of 3 percent. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>' plan also provides for core capital of 3 percent, but it's tougher on goodwill, allowing it make up only one fourth, rather than one half, of the core. Both the <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> and subcommittee legislation represent advances over current rules, which do not require owners to put up any real money if they have enough goodwill and subordinated debt _ money <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls borrow _ on their books. As of the end of 1988, goodwill was the biggest loophole, accounting for a third of the industry's $ 60 billion in capital. Subordinated debt amounts to about $ 4 billion. S & amp; L industry critics are targeting goodwill because it can not be sold when an institution closes. The subcommittee bill would allow <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls to maintain goodwill on their books, in some cases for as long as 40 years. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> would eliminate it in 20 years. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration had wanted to get rid of it in 10 years. The <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>' plan is also stricter with risky activities conducted in S & amp; L subsidiaries, such as investment in commercial real estate and junk bonds. It gives S & amp; Ls five years to come up with extra capital to back the subsidiaries, while the subcommittee plan does n't require extra capital. In another change, <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> would move back the deadline for complying with the new capital rules, from the June 1, 1990, target in the subcommittee bill to the June 1, 1991, originally proposed by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Leach </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, one of the top-ranking Republicans on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, is pressing for even stricter capital requirements, calling the 1.5 percent tangible rule `` absolutely utterly insane.'' `` We have made a prescription for repetition of the problem and I think the country ought to be alarmed,'' <PERSON> Leach </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> forum. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 91-8 to approve its version of <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L legislation last week. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, praising the vote in a speech in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> to the annual meeting of The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` I urge the House to act promptly, and pass this S & amp; L reform bill with its central provisions intact.''
