<FIRST>r a PM-TransplantTherapy     04-25 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Transplant Therapy,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treatment Could Revolutionize Organ Transplants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A treatment that could revolutionize organ transplants by overcoming the rejection of foreign tissue and improving the quality of patients' lives is showing promising results, researchers say. The treatment, which could eliminate the lifelong need for highly toxic drugs to fight organ rejection by the body's immune system, may be ready for human studies within three years, said Dr. <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrison </PERSON> <PERSON> Fathman </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor of medicine. The approach uses three doses of tailor-made, laboratory-grown monoclonal antibodies before the transplant to temporarily `` blind'' the immune system and keep it from recognizing the new organ as foreign tissue and attacking it. Rats given the treatment before receiving transplanted hearts have survived for more than 200 days without signs of rejection and without any anti-rejection drugs. Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Flavin </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> department of cardiovascular surgery, was scheduled to present the findings today at the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transplantation </ORGANIZATION> meeting in <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Meanwhile, the first full year of mandatory reporting of organ transplants by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hospitals shows 12,798 of the procedures were performed around the country in 1988, according to the national transplant network. The statistics, released Monday, were compiled by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sharing </ORGANIZATION>. Medical centers have been required since Oct. 1, 1987, by federal law to report transplants to the Virginia-based network. There were 9,123 kidney transplants, according to the network data. There also were 1,680 liver transplants, 1,647 heart transplants, 243 pancreas transplants, 74 heart-lung transplants and 31 lung transplants. Twenty-one of the lung transplants involved a full set of lungs and 10 involved single lungs. The monoclonal antibody treatment effectively paralyzed the rat immune system by killing certain cells while surgeons implanted hearts from donor rats into the abdomens of other rats with mismatched tissue type, leaving the recipients' original hearts intact. The drugs a patient must take to prevent the immune system from attacking a transplanted organ also prevent the immune system from attacking other harmful diseases. Patients then are susceptible to infections and may suffer other problems related to the drugs' toxicity The antibody treatment takes a new approach to the problem by creating a `` transient window of immunosuppression,'' said co-research, Dr. <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Shizuru </PERSON>. The antibody wipes out the specific type of white blood cells, called CD4 T lymphocytes, that lead the attack on the foreign organ, she said. But only mature cells are killed. Immature T cells are protected inside the thymus gland and begin repopulating in the body a few weeks after the transplant. `` We're sort of fooling the immune system for awhile,'' <PERSON> Fathman </PERSON> said. `` We're wiping the blackboard clean by removing the -LRB- mature -RRB- T cells that have not yet come into contact with the foreign antigen, in this instance the transplant,'' he said. By transplanting the new organ at a time when those cells are absent, the T cells repopulating from the immature cells in the thymus apparently do not recognize the transplant as anything except `` self,'' he said. When the T cells grew back, the immune system appeared to be `` blind'' to the foreign transplanted organ. But the T cells maintained their `` memory'' and attacked other foreign tissue. `` If the same thing holds in man, and we can prove that immunologic memory is not impaired by this type of immune paralysis, then we would be very hopeful that this technique could be readily applied to man,'' <PERSON> Fathman </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
