<HEAD>Impeachment of Imprisoned Mississippi Judge Urged by Lawmakers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel called today for the impeachment of imprisoned <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, who has collected $ 286,000 in pay since his 1986 perjury trial and is planning to return to the bench within months. `` His pattern of lies and deceit led ... to the inevitable conclusion that he has to be impeached,'' Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, D-Calif., said as the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> approved three articles of impeachment, 34-0 Floor action by the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on the move to impeach the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> jurist could come as early as Wednesday. <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> stands accused of lying to a federal grand jury and <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> investigators and bringing the judiciary into disrepute. The case centers on an oil and gas investment arranged for <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> by a wealthy businessman, <PERSON> Wylie </PERSON> <PERSON> Fairchild </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s alleged intervention in marijuana smuggling charges against Fairchild's son. <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> was sentenced in 1986 to two concurrent five-year sentences for perjury after denying involvement in the marijuana case. Since then, he has collected $ 286,000 in judicial salary, authorities say. They say he will be released within a matter of months and plans to don his black robes again and resume his seat on the bench. `` I believe that Judge <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> should have had the good grace to resign after his appeals were exhausted,'' Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sensenbrenner </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Wis </LOCATION>., told the <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Defense attorney <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> had said that some of the statements cited as instances of perjury were factual, and that in any case <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> has done nothing serious enough to warrant impeachment. He said <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> was `` subjected to a sensationalized investigation and an unfair trial.'' In such cases, the House first votes on a bill of impeachment. If it approves the bill, the judge is impeached and must stand trial in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is currently preparing for a trial of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Alcee </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, who was impeached last year.
