<DATELINE>CALCUTTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A woman suspected of being a witch was dragged from her hut, tied to a tree and then axed to death by her neighbors in an eastern <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> village, police said Tuesday. <PERSON> Sonamoni </PERSON> <PERSON> Kisku </PERSON> was killed Sunday by <PERSON> Ganesh </PERSON> <PERSON> Soren </PERSON> and his brother, <PERSON> Meghraj </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Goaljoi </LOCATION>, about 155 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Calcutta </LOCATION>, police said. <PERSON> Ganesh </PERSON> <PERSON> Soren </PERSON> was arrested but his brother was at large, according to Police Chief Satyan Pal. It was the latest in several killings of women suspected of being witches in the predominantly tribal region of the state. The Santhal tribes believe many women, especially widows, have the power to heal the sick and cast evil spells. But Mrs. <PERSON> Kisku </PERSON>, 50, was married and had two sons, Pal said. He said <PERSON> Ganesh </PERSON> <PERSON> Soren </PERSON> believed Mrs. <PERSON> Kisku </PERSON> had cast an evil spell on his 6-year-old daughter, who had been ill since January. State Chief Minister <PERSON> Jyoti </PERSON> <PERSON> Basu </PERSON> said at least 20 women were killed in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bengal </LOCATION> in 1987 on suspicion of practicing witchcraft.
