n. The Soviet delegation came to <PERSON> Little </PERSON> <PERSON> Diomede </PERSON> to sign the protocol, which urged the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet governments to approve a border commission to handle visits by Eskimos between <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>. Eskimos would not need visas to make the trip. Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> was supposed to take part in the ceremony along with his counterpart from the <PERSON> Magadan </PERSON> region of <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>. Fog and blowing snow prevented <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> from reaching the island, and the ceremony was conducted by telephone. The ceremony was held in conjunction with the <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION> Expedition, a skiing and sled dog journey from <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. The expedition consists of six Soviets and six Americans. Two of the Soviets and two of the Americans are Eskimos. Many Eskimo families were separated when the Soviets closed the border in the <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> at the onset of the Cold War in the late 1940s. The Soviet island of Big Diomede, three miles from <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diomede </LOCATION>, is a military installation. Eskimos who once lived there were relocated to the Siberian mainland in the 1950s.
