<HEAD>U.S. Writers Honor Jailed Vietnamese Poet, African Woman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY CHENAULT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From prisons and re-education camps in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Nguyen </PERSON> <PERSON> Chi </PERSON> <PERSON> Thien </PERSON> wrote of despair, of loved ones and of dreams of freedom. Through poetry, he found a way to let his thoughts escape from `` the swamplands'' where he spent nearly half his life. Human rights groups have conflicting reports on <PERSON> Thien </PERSON>'s fate, with some sources saying he died in jail and others suggesting he remains imprisoned. His plight has drawn attention of writers around the world, and now his works are part of an effort to highlight the risks writers take to express themselves. On Wednesday, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> chapter of the PEN organization, a leading voice of international literary freedom, will honor <PERSON> Thien </PERSON> with one of two Freedom-to-Write awards. The other writer to be honored at the <ORGANIZATION> PEN </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Montblanc </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Literary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gala </ORGANIZATION> is identified only as `` an anonymous African woman.'' `` The very thought that that person is unable to be identified says so much about the importance of focusing attention on these writers,'' said author <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>, a member of <ORGANIZATION> PEN </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. `` We ca n't even say which country in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> she is from because of the dangers she faces. That underlines the need for us to turn to these heroic people as symbols in the fight against the harsh treatment of writers in countries where people are a lot less free to write.'' In addition to $ 3,000 that the <ORGANIZATION> PEN </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> will send to a friend or relative of each recipient, the group hopes to pressure <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> with a written request for <PERSON> Thien </PERSON>'s release and pleas from prominent writers. <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> said freedom of expression is not just important to writers: `` In a world where we have writers who are not free, who are imprisoned and tortured for writing, what happens to the readers in these societies?'' He said promoting freedom of expression is especially important this year because of the controversy over <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>'s novel, `` The Satanic Verses.'' The book, considered blasphemous by many Moslems, ignited an international furor and led to calls for censorship and for <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>'s death. For <PERSON> Thien </PERSON>, imprisoned for 26 of his 55 years after opposing the Communist government, pushing for literary freedoms and writing articles critical of communism, poetry became a creative diversion to help him survive prison hardships and the emotional torment of captivity. According to reports from human rights groups, <PERSON> Thien </PERSON> burst into the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> in April 1979. He gave a staff member a collection of poems and a letter asking that they be published. Vietnamese guards arrested him. His poems have been translated into French and English, set to music and compiled in a book titled `` Flowers From Hell,'' which won the prestigious <LOCATION> Rotterdam </LOCATION> International Poetry Prize in 1985. `` When successful, it sounds like the depth of feelings from a man who has endured much pain but continued to dream and to hope for freedom,'' said <PERSON> Huynh </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanh </PERSON> <PERSON> Thong </PERSON>, who translated the poems into English. Thong is director of Vietnamese Studies Projects at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, where the book was published. The London-based human rights group <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> received reports that <PERSON> Thien </PERSON> had died in 1986. But sources in <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> have told <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> since then that he is alive. There also have been reports that he is suffering from depression and is partially paralyzed.
