<HEAD>Probe Of 747 Accident Begins Without Key Piece Of Evidence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATES with hearing beginning, statement
from Dickinson. Picks up 6th graf, `Investigators are...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal officials today opened a hearing aimed at explaining how a cargo door was torn off a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jumbo jet in February, killing nine passengers. <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> began the four-day hearing with a statement that the testimony gathered would assist the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> in `` determining the probable cause and in making any recommendations to prevent similar accidents.'' But he said any conclusions would await a report issued later in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747's 800-pound, 9-foot-square forward lower cargo hatch was left at the bottom of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> after <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> Flight 811 lost part of its fuselage shortly after takeoff from <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>. The door was located 85 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> and under nearly 17,000 feet of water. <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> has said efforts may be made to raise the door, which several experts say is the best chance of finding definitive answers for the cause of the accident. Investigators are debating whether a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> salvage mission this summer would be essential and worth the high cost. Officials for <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, and unions representing airline pilots and mechanics were expected to testify during the hearing. `` The board's full report will not be issued for several months, but recommendations to prevent any recurrence could come at any time,'' <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> said in a news release. The plane was bound for <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, with 337 passengers and a crew of 18 on Feb. 24. At about 23,000 feet, the airplane experienced an explosive decompression following the loss of the cargo door. Nine people were sucked out, along with seats and luggage, when the door and part of the aircraft fuselage were swept away. Though two engines conked out, pilot <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON> managed to land at <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> with no further loss of life. The 747-100 was one of the first jumbo jets built by Seattle-based <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>. The 13 people testifying were expected to discuss maintenance, inspection procedures and practices, human factors and details of a 1987 incident in which the cargo door on a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> 747 opened slightly during a flight from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. There has been speculation the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> cargo door may have broken free in an explosive decompression when the latching mechanism failed. Airline records indicated there had been recent problems with the door before the accident, including a faulty door seal and electrical problems requiring the door to be closed manually rather than electrically on several occasions. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> on March 3 issued an emergency order requiring all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines to reinforce within 30 days the relatively lightweight aluminum latch mechanisms with steel, so the doors would be less vulnerable to damage caused by improper closing. The cargo bay door is hinged at the top so it closes downward, with eight latching mechanisms along the bottom attached to the plane's frame. It also has a latching mechanism and a hook pin on each side. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> 747 remains at <ORGANIZATION> Hickam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> and will be returned to service after repairs are completed.
