<HEAD>Fighting Escalates on Eve of Arab League Peace Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BEI1, ROM2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Syrian gunners firing giant mortars battled Christian forces in an ill-matched duel Tuesday that each accused the other of starting in an effort to sabotage a new Arab peace initiative. Police reported two people were killed and 16 wounded as artillery and rockets pounded the <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> capital for six hours. The fighting shadowed a peacemaking effort by foreign ministers of the 22-state <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, who are to meet Wednesday in <LOCATION> Tunis </LOCATION>. Christian leader Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> was reported to have accepted a league proposal for 200 Arab observers to enforce and monitor a cease-fire. But the plan was jolted when Justice Minister <PERSON> Nabih </PERSON> <PERSON> Berri </PERSON> rejected having more foreign troops in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, where his staunch ally, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, has 40,000 troops under a 1976 league peacekeeping mandate. `` We do n't need more armies,'' <PERSON> Berri </PERSON> said Tuesday. His remarks are seen as a rejection by proxy of the Arab plan from <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s main power broker. <PERSON> Berri </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> militia so far has taken no part in the fighting between <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s mainly Christian troops and an alliance of Syrian troops and Moslem Druse militiamen that outgun and outnumber the Christians. <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s foreign minister and architect of the Arab plan, left Tuesday for <LOCATION> Tunis </LOCATION> declaring: `` We hope our <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> brothers will discern the interests of their people and country and stop fighting so that dialogue and wisdom replace shells and cannons.'' In <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> announced a plan to send its own forces to quell the fighting, but the plan is not expected to win much support. `` Observers say who is wrong and who is right. But to stop the killing of the people, we need real forces,'' said <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Abderrahman </PERSON>. Earlier Arab attempts to halt the carnage have failed, as has a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> appeal Monday for an end to the battles that erupted March 8. Since then, at least 272 people have been killed and 991 wounded. Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> repeated his calls for peace Tuesday at a Mass in the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>, where he invited Lebanese clerics and families. The London-based <ORGANIZATION> Mideast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> newsletter quoted <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> as saying he will accept an Arab observer force `` as a first step'' toward a political solution `` so long as it does n't include any of the participants of the fighting.'' `` The ultimate objective ... remains ending the Syrian and <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> occupation of Lebanese territory,'' it quoted <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> as saying. Some Arab states support Christian demands that <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> withdraw because it has violated its mandate by shelling them. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> says it will not withdraw. Tuesday's random bombardment raged from midnight to daybreak, forcing tens of thousands of residents to shelter in underground bunkers. It later slackened into sporadic shelling. The Syrians hammered the east of the city, heart of the besieged 310-square-mile Christian enclave, with 240mm mortars and B-21 launchers that fire 40 122mm rockets in 20 seconds. <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> shook as <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s forces lobbed 155mm and 130mm howitzer and mortar shells into west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. Ambulances with wailing sirens sped through rubble-strewn streets. Four shells crashed into the garden of east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s Comfort Hotel, shattering windows and windshields of five cars of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> monitoring force in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> official said. In west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, the facade of the West German cultural <ORGANIZATION> Goethe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> was destroyed. Police said west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Sahel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> was hit, but no patients were hurt. The <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> proposes an interim truce to stabilize the situation until a political solution is worked out providing for presidential elections and the formation of a coalition government.
