<HEAD>Trappings Go Back In The Closet, Horseshoes Come Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In his first 100 days, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> put the imperial trappings of the White House in storage. The place now rings with the squeal of grandchildren and the clang of horseshoes. Born to wealth and privilege, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> brought to the Executive Mansion the down-to-earth tastes and attitudes of a common person: hot dogs and baseball games, barbecues and country music, guided tours of the grounds, side trips to tourist attractions. Yet for all the bustle of the White House these days, the nation's 41st president often rides about town in a silent motorcade, politely stopping at red lights to avoid tying up traffic. Historians and political analysts may differ over the president's accomplishments in these first 100 days, but few will deny he's been enjoying every one of them. `` <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is sort of a <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> figure,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Newt </PERSON> <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> whip, recalling the mix of aw-shucks naivete and stubbornness in the actor's characterization in the movie classic, `` Mr. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> Goes to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` The president's personal style is nice and warm and collegial. It's just the way he is. He's also a very tough man,'' <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> said, adding, `` <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was a star. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is more of a senior player-coach type.'' Riding the crest of 60 percent-plus approval ratings in public opinion polls, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is settling with obvious relish and comfort into the job that he long coveted. At the same time, he has eschewed efforts to compare him with his predecessor, who also scored high in the polls. `` I certainly know something about following a class act,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told a recent audience. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> himself can joke that his first 100 days are `` about the same as <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Buren </PERSON>'s'' _ who was forced in his first 100 days to deal with one of the nation's worst financial panics and the long depression that followed _ and whose name the president enjoys invoking. But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s constant-motion style gives aides and reporters a difficult time keeping up with him. Beginning work each day at 7 a.m., <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> routinely puts in 11-hour workdays in the Oval Office, although he also has been known to slip away in the middle of the afternoon to play tennis, jog, throw horseshoes or play racquetball in a congressional gymnasium. While he seldom held news conferences during his presidential campaign, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has met roughly once a week with reporters since taking office, in forums ranging from regular news conferences to small-group chats in the Oval Office. He's traveled to four foreign counties and 17 states in his first three months in office. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> set a populist tone on his first full day in office, opening the White House and its grounds to the public. And he's had a stream of visitors in ever since, among them Democratic leaders who got little such attention from <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. `` I've been here more ... since <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has been president than I was in eight years under his predecessor,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>. Congressional leaders who have met frequently with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> say he is a good listener at high-level meetings, but a tough negotiator. `` I am amazed at how much at peace with himself he is, and really knows where he wants to go, how he wants to do it,'' said his chief of staff, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has no trouble making quick decisions, even though the president himself jokes that `` People say I'm indecisive I do n't know about that.'' Aides and associates say he gives careful attention to detail, even checking travel manifests to make sure there are n't too many staff members on trips, while always keeping up to speed on the issues of the day. In addition to daily intelligence and national security briefings, he reads `` about five papers as far as I can see'' each morning, said his wife, <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON>. Participants at Cabinet meetings say the president often stays on the sidelines and lets others do most of the talking, while other times jumping in and vigorously leading the discussions. `` He enjoys the give and take,'' said Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>. `` He enjoys having ideas put forward. ... He enjoys the competition of ideas and discussion of policy and where we ought to be going.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who as vice president had lunch once a week with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, has carried the custom forward. He eats a private lunch each Thursday with <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, who said he has complete access to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and can go into his office any time he wants. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is `` a much more open, gregarious, outgoing president than we've had in a long time,'' said <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Ornstein </PERSON>, a political analyst with the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. `` His early reputation is that this is a president who makes things happen. Once you establish that reputation, you are going to carry it to your advantage for a long time.'' Still, others have trouble focusing on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s true political and policy identity in all the swirl of activity. `` The non-image is the image he has created for himself,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Griscom </PERSON>, who was <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s communications director. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, after all, is the president who begins speeches on education with the phrase, `` you know;'' who talks about `` things'' and `` stuff;'' who frequently stumbles over his own lines. `` It's been said that sometimes I do n't speak in very good English and that I have a hard time being understood,'' he told a White House audience the other day. `` I'll admit it, it's true. And all I can say is that I'm in pretty good company, though. Look at <LOCATION> Yogi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berra </LOCATION>.'' `` I love to quote Yogi,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, captain of <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>'s 1948 baseball team, told another audience. `` He once said at a state dinner right here in this building, ` How could you get a conversation started in there? Everybody was talking too much.''' And if <PERSON> Berra </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION> catcher who turned the language on its ear, is the baseball great that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> quotes the most, the one he admires the most is another <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION>, the low-keyed <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Gehrig </PERSON>, whom <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> calls his personal hero. `` He played in 2,130 straight games _ a record which still stands,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` But more than that, he was a good and decent man about whom a teammate said, ` Every day, any day, he just went out and did his job.'''
