<HEAD>Study Group Says OPM Appointees Often Hostile to Civil Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Presidents <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> `` made bureaucrat-bashing the norm'' and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s political appointees at the Office of Personnel Management were often hostile to the civil service, a congressional panel was told Tuesday. The congressional <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> received reports from task forces of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, a private organization that has recommended pay increases and other steps to make federal service more attractive. The commission's task force on recruitment and retention said in its report that the personnel management office, created by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1978, `` has not met early expectations and remains, in many ways, an agency in search of an identity.'' `` Although <ORGANIZATION> OPM </ORGANIZATION> operated for a brief time at the end of the <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration, it was President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> who really shaped the early character of <ORGANIZATION> OPM </ORGANIZATION>,'' the task force said. It said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s first appointee to head <ORGANIZATION> OPM </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Devine </PERSON>, `` took a political approach to both the position and the agency'' and more than quadrupled the number of political appointees, increasing them from eight to more than 32. `` Equally troubling is the fact that the political appointees to <ORGANIZATION> OPM </ORGANIZATION> were often actively hostile to the career civil service,'' the task force said. It charged that `` the organization's effectiveness was severely diminished'' by low morale among the remaining career employees. Rep. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dicks </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Wash </LOCATION>., a co-chairman of the congressional task force, said, `` Clearly, the public's perception of the federal civil service has been influenced by negative messages from some elected officials in recent years, too many of whom have been willing to blame civil servants for the country's problems `` The previous two presidents made bureaucrat-bashing the norm,'' <PERSON> Dicks </PERSON> said. The commission task force said the appointment of <PERSON> Constance </PERSON> <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> as director of <ORGANIZATION> OPM </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 `` signaled a new direction'' for the agency, which in 1987 and 1988 `` paid serious attention to promoting the public service.'' `` There is consensus that <ORGANIZATION> OPM </ORGANIZATION> stands at the crossroads,'' the task force said. One of the commission's recommendations is a sharp decrease in the ratio of political to career appointees in the federal government. Rep. <PERSON> Steny </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyer </PERSON>, D-Md., also a co-chairman of the congressional task force, said that `` career executives have been driven off the leadership team in recent years, displaced by deepening layers of political appointees. `` This is a dangerous trend for the federal government,'' <PERSON> Hoyer </PERSON> said. `` Career executives help assure continuity as political appointees change.'' <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON>, former <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> chairman and chairman of the privately financed study group, said President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` speaks clearly and spontaneously about the value of public service'' and `` I think that is an indication and a hopeful sign that attitudes in this area may be in the process of changing.'' The commission's recommendations, calling among other things for a 50 percent increase over two years in pay for senior federal officials, judges and members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, were submitted to the president March 29. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has recommended pay raises for judges, but has withheld recommendations on other increases.
