<HEAD>Condemned Aircraft Bomber Probably Will be Pardoned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A woman condemned to death for bombing a South Korean airliner probably will be pardoned even if the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upholds her sentence, government officials said Tuesday. Confessed communist agent <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyon </PERSON> <PERSON> Hui </PERSON> was convicted Tuesday and sentenced to death by a three-judge panel headed by senior Judge <PERSON> Chung </PERSON> <PERSON> Sang-hwak </PERSON>, who said her crime underlined <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s unchanging policy of destroying <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s freedom <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION> has denied <PERSON> Kim </PERSON>'s assertions that North Korean leaders ordered her to bomb the Korean Air passenger plane in 1987. All 115 people aboard died when the plane disappeared over the <LOCATION> Andaman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> near the coast of <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>. `` We have an enemy which always tries to destroy our liberal democratic system. We must face that reality with resolute determination,'' <PERSON> Chung </PERSON> said in the verdict of the three-judge panel. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON>, 27, wept and her shoulders heaved as he pronounced her guilty of violating national security and aviation laws and sentenced her to death. South Korean law gives <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> one week to appeal. <PERSON> Ahn </PERSON> <PERSON> Dong-il </PERSON>, her lawyer, said they have not yet decided whether to do so. Relatives of those killed sat quietly in the court, watching <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> as she stood before the judge with downcast eyes. She said nothing before being led away. `` She deserves death because she killed 115 people,'' <PERSON> Park </PERSON> <PERSON> Son-jin </PERSON>, 60, whose son was on the plane, said after the hearing. Hundreds of security agents and police surrounded the courthouse to prevent more angry protests by relatives, or a possible threat from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. The judge said there is no doubt <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> planted the bomb aboard the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 707 that disappeared Nov. 29, 1987, on a flight from <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> has said she blew up the plane on orders from <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Jong </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON>, son and heir of North Korean President <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON>, to disrupt the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> Olympics. She has said she wants to die to atone for her sin. But South Korean officials said privately they expect she will be reprieved on grounds she was duped by <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and has repented. Court officials said if <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> is pardoned, she will be free on a stay of the sentence. Similar arrangements have freed other North Korean agents pardoned under a special amnesty after they switched loyalty. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> denies involvement in the bombing and claims it was engineered by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to embarrass the <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION> government. The two nations have been bitter rivals since their land was divided in 1945. Testimony given by <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> corroborated the findings of bomb experts who said the plane exploded in less than a second. No bodies were found. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> has said she and another agent pretended to be Japanese tourists and planted the bomb, which was disguised as a radio and a liquor bottle. The two were arrested a few days later and tried to take cyanide hidden in cigarettes. The other agent, an elderly man, died.
