<HEAD>Sales of Existing Homes Down for Third Straight Month</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales of existing homes dropped 4.3 percent in March, the third straight monthly decline, as rising mortgage interest rates made more inroads into the housing market, a real estate trade group said Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> said sales of existing single-family homes dropped to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.33 million units in March, the slowest pace since February 1988. Sales had dropped 2 percent in February and 9.4 percent in January. The March figures were the latest in a series of reports that indicate rising interest rates are slowing the economy and taking a toll on home sales and residential construction. Last week, the government reported that construction of new homes and apartments declined 5.4 percent in March, the second straight monthly decline. Because housing usually slows down in advance of other sectors of the economy, the weak performance has heightened fears that a recession could come later this year or in early 1990. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> for a year has been pushing up interest rates as part of a campaign to slow the economy and keep inflation in check. `` This is another piece of evidence that things are softening and that high interest rates do make a difference,'' <PERSON> Maury </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said of the latest housing report. Fixed-rate home mortgages averaged between 10.86 percent and 11.22 percent in March, up a full percentage point from a year earlier, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Ira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gribin </PERSON>, president of the Realtors, said the higher rates are having their biggest impact on first-time home buyers He said they are `` the first to leave the market and the last who are able to get back in.'' With fewer sales last month to first-time buyers, the median price of existing homes sold rose $ 1,200 to $ 93,100, meaning half the homes sold for more and half for less. `` What we are seeing is definitely a trade-up market,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuccillo </PERSON>, chief economist for the Realtors. `` People still in the market are those with the incomes to withstand higher monthly mortgage payments resulting from higher interest rates.'' Economist <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramley </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said that while further declines lie ahead for the housing industry, `` this is not a collapse of the housing market.'' `` Monetary policy used to clobber the housing market,'' <PERSON> Gramley </PERSON> said. `` Now it's nibbling gently on the fringes.'' <PERSON> Gramley </PERSON> said slower growth is `` just what the doctor ordered'' to dampen inflationary pressures and keep the economic expansion alive. By region, the sharpest decline in home sales last month was in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>, where the resale pace was down 10 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 540,000 units. Sales in the <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> had declined 15.5 percent during February. Sales last month were down 7.6 percent in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> to an annual rate of 850,000 units and fell 3.1 percent in the South to a rate of 1.27 million units. The only increase was recorded in the West, where sales rose 4.7 percent to an annual rate of 670,000 units.
