<HEAD>Strong Earthquake Shakes Mexico City</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to update with report of death, injuries.
Picks up 3rd graf pvs ``The National Earthquake...'' </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A strong earthquake shook <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and other parts of southern <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> this morning, cracking buildings and sending thousands of panicked people into the streets. At least one death was reported. Ambulances raced around the capital, sirens blaring, after the 8:29 a.m. -LRB- 10:29 a.m. EDT -RRB- tremor. The government news agency <ORGANIZATION> Notimex </ORGANIZATION> reported one man was electrocuted and died and that two women were seriously injured when they jumped from the second story of a swaying building during the tremor. The death and injuries occurred in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, the agency said. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Earthquake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Golden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, said preliminary readings indicated the quake registered 6.8 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale. The epicenter was 40 miles east of <LOCATION> Acapulco </LOCATION>, about 200 miles south of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, seismologist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Minsch </PERSON> said. The tremor was felt strongly in <LOCATION> Acapulco </LOCATION>, causing brief power failures and panic, said <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Guerra </PERSON>, advertising director of the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Novedades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acapulco </ORGANIZATION>. `` I've never felt a tremor so strong in the city and I've lived here for 30 years. I thought the building would collapse,'' he said. <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON>, spokesman for the <LOCATION> Guerrero </LOCATION> state government, said `` there are no reports of loss of life or major damage throughout the state,'' including heavily populated <LOCATION> P