<HEAD>Pickled Spotted Owl Eggs, Spotted Owl Dinners Signs of Frustration</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-7, `But the...' with 1 graf to UPDATE with U.S.
Fish and Wildlife Service confirming it will tell a federal judge in Seattle
that owl should be listed as a threatened species.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EUGENE, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At a tavern in <LOCATION> Coburg </LOCATION>, there's `` pickled spotted owl egg'' and `` fried or broasted spotted owl'' on the menu. An Oakridge tavern held a spotted owl dinner two weeks ago, and attracted a big crowd. A <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> man plans to market `` spotted owl jerky.'' The food is n't really owl meat, but the spoofs are signs of how high emotions are running in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s timber country over the northern spotted owl and its habitat in old-growth forest coveted by loggers. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Allison </PERSON>, publisher of High Lead magazine in <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON>, said he's sold more than 600 T-shirts that feature a hairy logger carrying an owl on a tray with the caption `` save a logger, eat an owl.'' Despite the protestations, the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said today in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, it will tell a federal court in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> next week that protection of the spotted owl as a threatened species is warranted. Listing a species as `` threatened'' is slightly less restrictive than listing a species as `` endangered,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON>, associate chief of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. However, it still could lock loggers out of much of the old-growth forest west of the <ORGANIZATION> Cascade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Range </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> earlier decided against listing the owl as endangered, but a reassessment was ordered by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Zilly </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Zilly </PERSON> found the earlier decision was not supported by evidence compiled by Fish and Wildlife. Under the Endangered Species Act, a species is considered endangered if it is `` in danger of extinction throughout all or a significant part of its range.'' A species is considered threatened if it is `` likely to become an endangered species in the foreseeable future throughout all or a significant portion of its range.'' <PERSON> Rolla </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, who works at the <ORGANIZATION> Bohemia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> plywood plant in <LOCATION> Vaughn </LOCATION>, has written a poem about the owl. In it, he tells of a man seeing a spotted owl contentedly sitting on a limb in a stand of old-growth trees. `` Even tho I soon may lose my job And stand to lose my home I ca n't explain the peace I felt Like none I've never known. Standing there in that quiet place Far from the sound of cars I looked around, took careful aim Then blew his brains to Mars.'' Environmentalists who say the owl is faced with extinction because of logging, and timber industry representatives who say the trees are needed to keep the industry alive in the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, agree that the spotted owl dinners, T-shirts and poems are signs of frustration and fear. <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> of the environmental group <ORGANIZATION> Earth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> said anti-owl sentiment has been caused by the timber industry. `` They find it convenient to turn their workers' heads around and say, ` Look, it's that owl that's taking your job,' when they're sending logs overseas,'' she said `` It's just a fear thing and I hope workers can look beyond the fear to see what's happenning.'' <PERSON> Allison </PERSON> said he's received only one complaint about his T-shirts. That came from a timber industry official who said the shirts are inappropriate and thought it would be better to show an owl or other wildlife living in harmony with good forest practices. <PERSON> Allison </PERSON> accuses both sides of `` tunnel vision.'' `` The spotted owl is a means to an end,'' he said. `` If it was n't that, it would be the pig-tailed titmouse. The -LRB- environmentalists' -RRB- goal is to save old growth.'' As for the timber industry, he said, `` How can people like <ORGANIZATION> Weyerhaeuser </ORGANIZATION> send -LRB- logs -RRB- to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, then go bid on federal timber? That's not fair.'' <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said he really does n't advocate shooting spotted owls, but he lost his job in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> when <LOCATION> Redwood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> was established. `` I just kind of got a new start and I'd hate to see it go down the tubes here,'' he said. `` I'm not so dumb that I think the owl is the only problem,'' he said. `` They're shipping logs -LRB- overseas -RRB-, I realize that. There might be a poem coming on that one of these days.'' `` The owl gets focused on,'' he said, `` because it's kind of a symbol.''
