<HEAD>U.S. Criticizes Suggestion New Zealand May Pull Out Of Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on Tuesday disputed a suggestion by Prime Minister <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lange </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> that his country may pull out of a security alliance with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> because of his nation's anti-nuclear policies. `` That is <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>'s prerogative,'' said <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON>. But, she added, `` we take exception to the prime minister's assertions that such action is justified by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' refusal to consult with <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>'' in accordance with terms of the ANZUS pact. <LOCATION> ANZUS </LOCATION>, created in 1951 as a defense alliance among the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, has been crippled since the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> suspended guarantees for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>'s defense in 1986 over the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> nation's ban of ships carrying nuclear weapons. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy is neither to confirm nor deny the existence of nuclear weapons on its vessels. Even if <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> does pull out, `` <ORGANIZATION> ANZUS </ORGANIZATION> would continue to exist as the foundation of our important and active security relationship with <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>,'' said a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> statement. `` We continue to hope that <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> wil