<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government said Tuesday that a severe gas shortage has closed some stations and caused long lines at the pumps, forcing <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> to look to the West for extra gas supplies. The government blamed a 20 percent jump in gasoline consumption on the end of gas rationing Jan. 1, a mild winter that allowed more cars on the road and the government's refusal to allow prices to rise high enough to discourage demand. `` If we were persistent in introducing the market economy, prices would surely regulate the problem of lines,'' said deputy government spokesman <PERSON> Zbyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Rykowski </PERSON>. Concern about gas shortages and price increases began spreading across <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> by word of mouth last week. Confirmation came Tuesday in official newspaper reports the government would tap hard currency supplies to buy about 163 million gallons of gasoline from <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Gas imports planned for the first half of this year from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s largest supplier, arrived early and were used up ahead of schedule, the <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wieczorny </ORGANIZATION> newspaper reported Tuesday. It will be several weeks before the new gas reaches <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and eases the supply problems, said <PERSON> Krzysztof </PERSON> <PERSON> Pilich </PERSON>, deputy manager of the state oil department. But <PERSON> Pilich </PERSON> said rationing would not be introduced again. When rationing ended, the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> warned that prices would increase if sales of gasoline outstripped supplies. The price at the time was 190 zlotys a liter, or $ 1.46 per gallon. The price has been raised to 250 zlotys a liter. The average monthly salary is about $ 127 to $ 175. Disgruntled drivers waiting Tuesday at a <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> gas station had differing opinions about the cause of the shortage, which is being widely discussed in the informal network that keeps residents up to date on supplies of goods. `` I think it is a matter of bad distribution,'' said one man. Another who had waited for four hours without success the night before said he thought the government had created the shortage to keep people from `` moving around the country'' during upcoming elections, the first since 1947. `` I think it is done on purpose and a lot of people share this view,'' he said. <PERSON> Rykowski </PERSON> said there could be some distribution problems but poor planning did not cause the shortage. Instead, he said it stemmed from a failure `` for justifiable, social reasons'' to use higher prices to suppress demand in the style of a market-based economy. `` I am saying this with certain terror because I know that these sorts of moralizing speeches are met with rejection,'' he said at the news conference. `` I do n't intend to continue this sermonizing and point out that in countries with a market-oriented economy, when someone drives to work he calculates how much that costs,'' he said.
