<SECOND>AM-Child Pornography,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publishing and Library Groups Attack Age-Documentation Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new law requiring publishers and distributors to document the ages of nude models in photographs `` will have a truly devastating effect'' on free expression and will not stem the flow of child pornography, a judge was told Tuesday. The law poses near-impossible record-keeping burdens on legitimate businesses and would impose a `` corporate death penalty'' on distributors because all assets could be seized if they violate the law with even one publication, said an attorney for a coalition of publishing and library groups. The coalition claims the law would force librarians to remove from their shelves any medical, sex education and sociological texts showing full frontal nudity and stop magazines and TV shows from using adult sexual material that is protected by the First Amendment. `` It will have a truly devastating effect on entirely lawful, protected speech of adults,'' said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Ennis </PERSON>, an attorney representing the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in a lawsuit against the statute. The law requires that anyone who produces material with images of sexual activity or `` lascivious exhibition of the genitals'' keep records showing the models depicted are at least 18 years old. The law covers the reissue of any materials produced after Feb. 5, 1978 _ the date when a major federal child pornography law took effect. <PERSON> Ennis </PERSON> said the word lascivious is too imprecise, the text of the statute is too broad and the child porno industry is entirely underground and would not be affected by the law. `` The government is concerned about an underground problem, but they impose a solution on a legitimate above-ground industry,'' <PERSON> Ennis </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stearns </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> attorney, told <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Revercomb </PERSON> that publishers' First Amendment arguments were `` overwrought'' and that they would be little affected by the law. He said if mainstream companies were n't distributing child pornography it must mean they already have adopted ways to prevent such occurrences. <PERSON> Stearns </PERSON> said the government has the right to try to stop the production of `` vast'' amounts of child pornography in this country and the importation of child pornography. The new law would punish criminals, not suppress free expression, he told the judge. Then-President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed the Child Protection and Obscenity Enforcement Act last November, and the record-keeping requirements were scheduled to start May 17, not Aug. 17 as published incorrectly in the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Register </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Stearns </PERSON> said. The act increases penalties for anyone facilitating use of a child for producing sexually explicit materials, creates a new federal offense for engaging in the business of distributing obscene materials and provides mandatory forfeiture of the profits of those convicted of being engaged in the adult obscenity business. House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, has said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> intended to target only major dealers or producers of obscene materials who were `` knowingly engaged for a long period of time.'' He said the measure was not aimed at the bookstore owner who may have a single volume judged to be obscene. <PERSON> Stearns </PERSON> said the problem in prosecuting child pornography was the difficulty in determining the ages of models. He agreed with <PERSON> Revercomb </PERSON> that the issue involved those aged 14 to 17 who can pass for 19 and 20, such as actress Tracy Lords who made 75 porno films starting when she was 14. <PERSON> Stearns </PERSON> said the law clearly defines illegal sexual acts and `` does n't apply to all frank depictions of the human form.'' Medical texts, art books and news photos would not be in jeopardy, he said. <PERSON> Revercomb </PERSON> took under advisement the coalition's request for a preliminary injunction against the record-keeping and forfeiture provisions. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sought dismissal of the suit. The challengers include the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Booksellers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Read </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Magazine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magazine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Photographers </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magazine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Editors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Periodical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Distributors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Periodical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Distributors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Satellite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Video </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Software </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> also filed court papers arguing against the law.
