<TEXT>
 Gangs of angry Mauritanians armed with sticks and clubs harassed Senegalese citizens and sacked their shops Tuesday, forcing the government to impose a dusk-to-dawn curfew. In the Senegalese capital of <LOCATION> Dakar </LOCATION>, 375 miles to the south, anti-Mauritanian violence was not quelled until 4 a.m. Tuesday after the army was called out and police resorted to tear gas. Both countries reinforced their troops along the <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> border, as tensions mounted over a land dispute. Government officials in the two <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> nations tried to calm passions sparked by the April 9 killing of two Senegalese farmers, allegedly shot by <LOCATION> Mauritanian </LOCATION> soldiers in <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Diawara </PERSON> border village Two people have died in violence in <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION> since then. Sporadic outbursts against Mauritanian shopkeepers in <LOCATION> Dakar </LOCATION> and Senegalese in <LOCATION> Nouakchott </LOCATION> grew into widespread violence Sunday. `` Our compatriots must imperatively, no matter what pain they have suffered, chase from their hearts the cowardly sentiment of vengeance,'' Interior Minister <PERSON> Gibril </PERSON> <PERSON> Ould </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdallahy </PERSON> said in a statement broadcast Tuesday on Mauritanian radio and television. He announced an 8 p.m. to 6 a.m. curfew in <LOCATION> Nouakchott </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nouadihbou </LOCATION>, the principal port. A government source denied reports three people died in <LOCATION> Nouakchott </LOCATION> violence, although he added officials do not have complete casualty lists. Truckloads of police, some with riot helmets and shields, rushed through the streets of this sand-blown capital of 500,000 people. Violence has been concentrated in poor quarters and shantytowns. Angry crowds formed in dirt back streets, occasionally surging onto a main artery to attack Senegalese and sometimes wreck or burn a shop. Police broke up the crowds with tear gas and clubs. Knots of Mauritanians demanded to see ID cards and roughed up those who did not prove they were Mauritanian. <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION> straddles <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> north and black <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Two-thirds of its 2 million people are Moors of Arab-Berber extraction. The rest are black, mostly from the southern river region. <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION>'s 7 million people almost all are black. In <LOCATION> Dakar </LOCATION>, many women and children sought refuge in the <ORGANIZATION> Mauritanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, Ambassador <PERSON> Mokhtar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ould </PERSON> <PERSON> Zamel </PERSON> said. They were escorted to the central mosque. Many have asked to be repatriated. Senegalese authorities said they arrested large numbers of vandals, but did not confirm reports that hundreds have been detained. This violence was sparked over the right of Senegalese to farm on a <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> island. Even before the colonial period, the black Toucouleur people farmed both sides of the <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. After both countries became independent from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in 1960, Senegalese Toucouleur continued to farm the Mauritanian side they had considered their own for generations. Moors to the north, traditionally nomadic herders, did not farm. But the recent completion of two dams on the river has opened up new farmland and spurred Mauritanian interest in agriculture. All along the border, Senegalese are being forced off the land.
