<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An international group of bishops and educators urged the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> on Tuesday to safeguard academic independence in Roman Catholic universities. The appeal came at the conclusion of a weeklong meeting to assess a draft of a major <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION> document on Catholic higher education. The draft has drawn sharp criticism from college officials who charge it could undermine academic freedom. Delegates from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which has the world's largest <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> college system, said at a news conference Tuesday they are optimistic the <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION> will heed the representatives' wishes. But the final document must be approved by Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>. In a closing address to the conference, the pope called for a `` more strict and faithful collaboration'' between the universities and the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> hierarchy. The representatives, in a near-unanimous vote, said the document should contain non-binding guidelines that are general and inspirational, rather than specific. `` My impression is that the Congregation will do a major rewrite,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitz </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dayton </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, referring to the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>'s Congregation for <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>. The first draft of the education document, issued in 1985, assigned church authorities some power over <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> colleges and universities to ensure that teachers adhered to church doctrine and `` uprightness of life.'' Those teachers judged not doing so would be subject to dismissal. The document, circulated to