<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sworn statements about a dog that understood Estonian and trysts between a defense attorney and courtroom marshal are some of the odd turns a long trial of three leftist militants has taken. Tuesday was day 37 of testimony and arguments in the federal trial of two men and a woman accused of plotting to overthrow the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> government by force. The charge also known as seditious conspiracy rarely has been used since it was invoked during the Civil War to prosecute Confederate loyalists. Despite the historical weight of the proceeding, which involves some of the major violent radicals of the 1970s, the dozen or so marshals guarding the courtroom usually far outnumber the few spectators. The 17-member jury yawned and fidgeted through Monday's skirmish between defendant <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Luc </PERSON> <PERSON> Levasseur </PERSON>, dressed in blue jeans, and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, a gray-suited <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> lawyer who was friends with some associates of the defendants when she studied at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> a decade ago. <PERSON> Levasseur </PERSON>, who is serving as his own lawyer, has accused <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> and others of informing on the radicals, who sometimes called themselves the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> and are accused of bombing buildings and robbing banks around the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> from 1975 to 1981. `` I would like you to cooperate, although not as much as you did with the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Levasseur </PERSON> said, in the kind of bitter aside that jurors have come to expect of him. <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> was the 91st witness on the stand, and prosecutors are only a quarter of the way into their witness list. <PERSON> Levasseur </PERSON>, 42, faces a maximum of 60 years in prison if convicted on three charges of seditious conspiracy, racketeering and racketeering conspiracy. On trial on the same charges are his wife, <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Gros </PERSON> <PERSON> Levasseur </PERSON>, 40, and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, 41. There were seven defendants at the time of the initial jury selection in March 1988. Prosecutors dropped charges against <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Manning </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Laaman </PERSON>, already serving lengthy sentences on other charges. <PERSON> Manning </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Manning </PERSON>, pleaded guilty to sedition and other charges, and a separate trial was ordered for <PERSON> Laaman </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Curzi-Laaman </PERSON>. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Loucks </PERSON> questioned <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> on April 13 about a dog she said former co-defendant <PERSON> Jaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Laaman </PERSON> had taught commands in Estonian. `` Did you ever hear him talk to the dog?'' Young asked her. She replied: `` A couple of commands, like sort of ` sit' and ` stop.''' Young later struck the comments, saying, `` I ca n't for the life of me see how that would be a statement made in furtherance of the conspiracy.'' Ms. <PERSON> Curzi-Laaman </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, and a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> marshal assigned to guard the courthouse during the trial were the subject of an April 7 hearing for their love affair during jury selection. A judge found that the pair had not discussed court business during the liaison.
