<SECOND>AM-Quake-Tourists,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hotels Swayed Like Flagpoles in Quake, Some Tourists Leave</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mexico-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tourists said the capital's luxury hotels swayed like flagpoles in Tuesday's earthquake and it felt like a rollercoaster ride, frightening some so badly they cut short their vacations and headed for more stable ground. `` We were in bed and she thought I was shaking the bed and I thought the people next door were shaking the walls,'' said <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Giddings </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> as he and his wife, <PERSON> Maria </PERSON>, checked out of the Hotel Krystal in the Zona Rosa tourist area. They were a day and a half into their honeymoon when the quake hit at 8:26 a.m. `` Once it really got going you could hear a rumble. It felt like a good rollercoaster ride,'' said <PERSON> Giddings </PERSON>. Two hairline cracks ran down the walls, one in the bedroom, one in the bathroom, popping chips of paint off the walls. Running down the stairs from their 10th floor room after the motion stopped, they saw chunks of plaster scattered about. They had planned to go to the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> coast resort of <LOCATION> Acapulco </LOCATION> but changed their minds when they heard the quake was centered near there. `` We're going anywhere in the States,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Giddings </PERSON> said, `` It's a terrifying experience.'' She said <LOCATION> Disneyworld </LOCATION> was one possibility. Tourists at other hotels said they saw other people checking out, cutting vacations short because of the quake, which measured 6.8 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale. Across the street, in the Century Hotel, Cobe Eekels-Bakker of <LOCATION> Amstelveen </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, at first thought she was ill, then noticed that everything was moving back and forth. `` I could see through my window stones and dirt coming down,'' she said. Although slowed by an already existing hip injury, she grabbed her purse and cane to run down the steps from her eighth-floor room. `` Everybody was going past me. Then somebody took me and brought me downstairs quickly,'' she said. `` I have cried,'' she said, sitting in the lobby more than an hour later, still shaken. The quake sloshed water from the hotel's rooftop pool, over the walls onto cars parked on the street 23 floors below. Three hours later, <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> and <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Westport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, who had been staying in the <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Isabel </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheraton </PERSON>, said they decided to continue their vacation and go on to <LOCATION> Acapulco </LOCATION>. `` I'm still actually dizzy from it,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> said. `` I do n't feel I have my legs under me yet.'' She remembered sitting in their sixth-floor room, waking up with a cup of coffee just before the quake. `` There was a Do Not Disturb sign on the inside of the door wiggling. I was sitting there, trying to wake up, wondering what was making the sign move.'' About five minutes later, the whole building began shaking. `` I felt like I was going to pass out. I was really frightened, it was a sort of panic attack,'' she said. But her husband, everyone agreed, stayed calm throughout. `` It was like being on the top of a flagpole,'' he said. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Cummings </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Selden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, recovering from a two-day bout of illness, tried to get out of bed when he heard the bathroom door bang and felt the building sway. `` It was strong enough to make me fall back down on my bed when I got up,'' he said. `` That's when I realized what was happening.'' <PERSON> Lauren </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Henley-on-Thames </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, had been in an earthquake in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> but said it was `` not as bad as this.'' She called her husband <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> from the bathroom of their 15th-floor room. `` We sat on the bed and held each other,'' she said. `` We could just see our building moving relative to the other buildings,'' he said. While it seemed like a lot, it looked like about a foot, he said.
