<HEAD>Gingrich Denies Helping Book Investors With Their Government Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 House Republican Whip <PERSON> Newt </PERSON> <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> said Tuesday that none of the 22 investors in a partnership created to promote a book he co-authored ever received `` unusual or extraordinary personal help'' from him in their dealings with the federal government. But <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>, during a stormy news conference which his wife left in anger, acknowledged that some of the investors had a direct interest in legislation and that he had handled routine requests from some of them. While House rules prohibit members from accepting gifts worth more than $ 100 from people with direct interest in legislation, <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> said the partnership did not violate <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rules because the $ 5,000 that each investor put into the deal did not constitute a gift. Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>, D-Ark., has filed a formal complaint with the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> ethics committee alleging that the partnership involved 10 apparent violations of <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rules The committee has not indicated whether it will launch a preliminary investigation of the complaint. <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>, who initiated the investigation that led to <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s being charged with 69 violations of <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rules last week, said he was satisfied that each investor in the partnership `` thought there was a reasonable chance that it might make money.'' In exchange for their investments, the 19 individuals and three corporations that formed the <ORGANIZATION> COS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Limited </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partnership </ORGANIZATION> in 1984 were promised half of the publisher's profits from the book, `` Window of Opportunity,'' written by <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>; his wife, <PERSON> Marianne </PERSON> <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>, and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Drake </PERSON>. According to hundreds of pages of financial documents and tax returns released Tuesday by <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>, the partnership spent $ 51,571 to promote and advertise the book from 1984 through 1986, but the publisher still had a net loss of $ 6,259 on the book by the end of 1987. Because the partnership received no profits from book sales, the $ 104,185 loss it generated from 1984 to 1988 was distributed among the partners, providing them with tax writeoffs. Mrs. <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>, as general partner of the partnership, received a $ 10,000 payment in 1984 for setting up the organization, and later received a 2 percent interest in the partnership and a $ 1,500 payment, according to the documents. She did not invest any of her own money in the partnership. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>'s complaint alleges in part that the payments and ownership interest in the partnership that Mrs. <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> received were gifts that violated House rules limiting gifts members may receive. The complaint parallels the ethics committee's allegation that the salary and benefits <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Betty </PERSON>, received from an investment corporation were actually gifts because there was no evidence that Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> did any work for the corporation. Mrs. <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> said Tuesday that she kept all the records for the partnership, interviewed potential investors to ensure they were qualified and handled the filings necessary to comply with various state securities laws. She left the news conference abruptly after telling reporters she was upset that no one seemed interested in going through the 350 pages of tax returns, financial records and incorporation papers that she had put together in response to questions about the book deal. <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> defended his wife, telling reporters that unlike Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, `` she actually did the work for the money she got.'' He said the 350 pages of documents `` represent her work product.'' <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> said he was willing to concede that the book partnership was `` unusual.'' But he said there was nothing `` unethical'' in the deal, which he described as markedly different from the financial arrangements for <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s book, `` Reflections of a Public Man.'' `` We wrote a real book, working with a real publisher distributed to real bookstores and sold to real people for a realistic, standard royalty,'' he said. `` <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> did none of those things.'' Part of the ethics committee's charges against <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> allege that he violated <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rules on outside income limits though bulk sales of his book, on which he received a 55 percent royalty.
