<HEAD>Future Of Longtime Governing Party Uncertain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Japan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The absence of strong, untainted leaders in the governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> was a big reason Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> held on so long through a personally painful and damaging scandal. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>, 65, was in power only 18 months and had to deal from his first days in office with the multimillion dollar scandal involving the Recruit information conglomerate. He announced Tuesday he will resign. That had been expected, but it still left the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which has been in control since 1948, foundering. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> was <ORGANIZATION> LDP </ORGANIZATION> president, and that assured him of becoming prime minister in November 1987 when Prime Minister <PERSON> Yasuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakosone </PERSON> retired. And although the new <ORGANIZATION> LDP </ORGANIZATION> president could expect to become prime minister, the party is riddled with factions. `` Many of the leaders of factions inside the <ORGANIZATION> LDP </ORGANIZATION> are themselves involved in the Recruit scandal, so it would be difficult to find someone to take <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s place,'' said <PERSON> Seisaburo </PERSON> <PERSON> Sato </PERSON>, a political science professor at <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Unlike questions of personal finances in the 1970s that led to the resignation of Prime Minister <PERSON> Kakuei </PERSON> <PERSON> Tanaka </PERSON>, the Recruit scandal has scarred virtually all the <ORGANIZATION> LDP </ORGANIZATION> factions. Political analaysts said the plunge of <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s popularity in public opinion polls to less than 4 percent reflected broad opposition to the political system, often characterized by back-room dealings. `` I feel deeply responsible for having fostered such distrust,'' <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> said in his resignation announcment. He said he would leave office after parliament approves the budget for fiscal 1989. The Recruit scandal created a stalemate in Parliament with a boycott of the budget debate by opposition members demanding former Prime Minister <PERSON> Yasuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON> be called for questioning about payments and stock deals by Recruit to politicians and the <ORGANIZATION> LDP </ORGANIZATION>. For many people the scandal revealed the extent of unreported money flowing between business and government. Analysts, noting the years the <ORGANIZATION> LDP </ORGANIZATION> has governed, suggested a system of `` structural corruption'' had been created. Some <ORGANIZATION> LDP </ORGANIZATION> members, including reform leader <PERSON> Masayoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Takemura </PERSON>, have said the party may not be able to end its dependence on large sums of money from the business world and maintain its dominance. `` Sometimes I think we may have to dissolve the party and start again from zero,'' <PERSON> Takemura </PERSON> said last week. <PERSON> Takako </PERSON> <PERSON> Doi </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, told other opposition leaders at a strategy session this month that the scandal offered a rare opportunity to wrest power from the <ORGANIZATION> LDP </ORGANIZATION>. `` This is a time of unprecedented importance,'' she said. <PERSON> Fuyuko </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamisaka </PERSON>, a prominent writer on women's and consumer issues, suggested in a television interview that an independent panel be appointed to supervise political reforms. `` I hope that someone not directly linked to the political world can lead a fundamental reform of politics that will eliminate the flow of ` strange' money,'' she said.
