<HEAD>Resignation Held Likely to Delay FSX Project</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Japan, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 2 grafs White House comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Japanese Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s resignation likely will further delay action on the controversial FSX fighter project, official sources said Tuesday Some high-level sources suggested the end result could be a weaker deal for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, or a complete unraveling of the plan to jointly build a new fighter based on the American F-16. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s announcement that he would step down as a result of an influence-peddling scandal brings new uncertainty to the already-troubled FSX plan, said administration and congressional officials, all of whom declined to be identified. The sources suggested it is now unlikely there will be any movement in stalled negotiations on the project until a successor to <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> takes office. `` It's not on the verge of being resolved now anyway,'' said one administration soucre. `` We're continuing to try to clarify the conditions'' on the project set down a month ago by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiators. `` It's proven to be a very difficult process.'' Although President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> signaled general support for the joint venture in mid-March, Japanese officials balked at some of the conditions he stipulated _ including a guarantee that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies have a 40 percent share in the production of the new jet. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> also wants assurances that any new technology developed from the project would be available to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, along with protection for U.S.-developed computer codes that help fly and control the plane. The agreement to co-develop the FSX, which stands for Fighter Support Experimental, was negotiated late last year between <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s government and the outgoing <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> adminstration. Under the agreement, <ORGANI