is will give them a chance to get their act together and play trade hardball.'' Any effort by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to demand further concessions from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could jeopardize a project that already has thin support in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, possibly torpedoing the plan entirely, said both administration and congressional sources. Traveling with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, presidential spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> was asked what impact <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s resignation might have on the FSX project. `` We do n't really know how it might affect that deal,'' he said. Asked if the White House still favored moving ahead with the agreement, with the new qualifications, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said, `` Our position is the same, we still hope so.''
