<HEAD>Surinamese Rebels Shatter Lull With Village Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARAMARIBO, Suriname (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Jungle rebels broke a six-month lull in their uprising by attacking a village, where they killed one man, kidnapped two others, and set fire to homes, the state news agency reported Tuesday. Witnesses said about 40 insurgents of a group known as the Jungle Commando attacked <LOCATION> Pokigron </LOCATION>, about 100 miles south of this capital city, early Sunday despite resistance by villagers armed with shotguns. The attackers beat, stabbed, and then shot a man they suspected to be an army spy, according to the state-run <ORGANIZATION> Suriname </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. The victim later died in the hospital. The rebels also burned some homes and kidnapped the village chief and a second man, the news agency said. The rebels doused the chief with gasoline and threatened to burn him alive but halted when villagers begged them to stop, the agency said. About 100 villagers fled to <LOCATION> Paramaribo </LOCATION> after the assault, the news agency said. The insurgents reportedly escaped. The attack was the most serious in this former Dutch colony on the northeastern coast of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> since cease-fire talks with the government of President <PERSON> Ramsewak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shankar </PERSON> stalled in October 1988. Witnesses said Sunday's attackers were led by <PERSON> Ronny </PERSON> <PERSON> Brunswijk </PERSON>, a one-time army private who began the uprising in 1986. More than 400 people, mostly civilians, have been killed in the rebellion. The insurgents have not publicly stated their grievances.
