<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A prominent Iranian newspaper on Tuesday backed <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> to head a leadership council that would eventually succeed the 88-year-old <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>. The state-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Ettelaat </ORGANIZATION> daily said in an editorial that no single possible substitute for <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> existed `` when it comes to knowledge and jurisprudence especially in the area of government... or when such other factors as record of struggle or political intuition is concerned. It suggested a leadership council made up of present state administrators and leading religious authorities in which one member `` would be capable of saying the last word on matters of dispute and able to adopt decisions on his own responsibility.'' `` If we were to make a decision on the basis of a grade point average of a candidate it seems ... <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> has the necessary qualifications for heading the leadership council,'' <ORGANIZATION> Etelaat </ORGANIZATION> said. `` In all countries and with every leadership council there is one member entitled to veto the vote of the rest.'' It was the first public backing for a <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> successor since <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> forced <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Hossein </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Montazeri </PERSON> to step down last month as his officially designated successor. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> is a leading candidate for president in elections scheduled to be held this year to choose a successor to <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON>, who is not permitted by the constitution to run for a third four-year term. But under <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s present system, the president divides power with the prime minister and <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, all of them subject to the authority of <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>. The revolutionary patriarch's separate status as spiritual leader is unmatched and unlikely to be filled after he dies, Iranian political experts say. <ORGANIZATION> Ettelaat </ORGANIZATION>'s endorsement significantly boosts <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>'s status in current political infighting. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> kept a low profile in a recent purge of moderates and in the international outcry over <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s death sentence decree for British author <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> is considered a pragmatist able to maneuver between hard-line theologians and others who wanted to soften the harsh Islamic revolution and end <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s international isolation. On Friday, he announced the discovery of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> spy network including senior Iranian naval officers, a move apparently aimed at gaining points with the hardliners. On Saturday, <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, 54, who also holds the post of acting commander in chief of the armed forces, received backing for his presidential campaign from an influential party of hardliners, the Assembly of Combatant Theologians. And on Monday, <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> included <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> in a 20-man committee given two months to `` rectify defects'' in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s 1980 revolutionary constitution. One task, <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> said, was to consider the leadership question. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> has been campaigning for a constitutional change giving the president more power and abolishing the prime ministry. Prime Minister <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Musavi </PERSON> meanwhile said Tuesday that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> spy network which <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> reported uncovered recently had direct contact with <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> offices in neighboring countries. Some agents communicated with the Americans through West German embassies in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, he said. <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio, monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, quoted <PERSON> Musavi </PERSON> as saying in an interview with the state-owned <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> that the West Germans `` should know their embassies are at the service of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> spy network.'' He said some agents were in `` sensitive positions'' with access to top secret information which they passed on to the Americans, the radio reported. <PERSON> Musavi </PERSON> said the purported <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> actions violated the <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION> agreement, which stipulates non-interference by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in each other's domestic affairs. He was apparently referring to a 1980 accord under which <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> released 52 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomats held hostage in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> for 444 days. <PERSON> Musavi </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> would lodge a complaint against <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> at the Hague.
