<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel's Chairman Asks Members to Resist Lobbyists' Pressure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, on the eve of public sessions to write savings and loan bailout legislation, privately appealed to fellow Democrats Tuesday to resist pressure from industry lobbyists or face the anger of taxpayers. Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, at a closed-door caucus of the panel's Democrats, urged support for requiring S & amp; L owners to back their lending with more of their own money, calling it `` the litmus test on whether anything has changed'' and `` the guts of this whole issue.'' Capital investment from S & amp; L stockholders acts as a cushion, absorbing losses that would otherwise have to be paid by government deposit insurance. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> is attempting to persuade his 51-member committee to toughen the standards passed earlier this month by the panel's 47-member subcommittee on financial institutions, chaired by Rep. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON>, D-Ill. More than 100 amendments are pending before the committee, which in sessions scheduled Wednesday and Thursday is expected to re-hash many of the battles fought during during 32 hours of subcommittee deliberations <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, who is joined by Rep. <PERSON> Chalmers </PERSON> <PERSON> Wylie </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, the panel's senior <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION>, would require institutions to hold $ 2.25 in `` tangible'' or `` real money'' capital for every $ 100 in loans, compared with $ 1.50 in versions of the legislation passed by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee and the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. `` Inadequate capital standards simply mean that we let the industry, once again, roll the dice with the taxpayers' money,'' he said in a statement prepared for delivery at the caucus. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> is trying to raise the visibility of the complex capital issue, which is at the heart of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s savings and loan proposal. In the past, industry lobbyists have heavily influenced congressional decisions on banking laws because most voters do n't follow the issues. With taxpayers picking up the bulk of the 10-year, $ 157 billion <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L bailout, however, <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> told his colleagues that ` the decisions will be tough _ and they will be watched.'' `` The choice may be difficult, but, as Democrats, we had better be able to say, ` When the choice was presented, we sided with the taxpayers,''' he said. Rep. <PERSON> Barney </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, D-Mass., predicted, `` The capital standards are going to look pretty kosher to the president by the time we're through `` There's intense lobbying by people in the industry, but I also think ... there's a view that if the committee votes $ 100 billion without a tough bill, sooner or later the public will react,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, who is supporting <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>' capital amendment. However, Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> LaFalce </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, argued that <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> was trying to precipitously impose `` lily white, absolutely pure'' standards on S & amp; Ls. He warned that if S & amp; Ls were not permitted to gradually improve their condition, the government's list of troubled institutions will swell. `` I honestly believe that if we prescribe this medicine for our troubled financial system, the medicine will be so strong that it will, if not kill the system, at least exacerbate the problem multifold,'' he said. In addition to raising the tangible capital requirement, <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> is also trying to tighten two other standards: one affecting an accounting item known as `` goodwill,''' the other the treatment of S & amp; L subsidiaries. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, more than one-third of the S & amp; L industry's $ 60 billion in capital consists of `` goodwill,'' an intangible asset representing the value of an institution's customer loyalty and name recognition. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is seeking to eliminate `` goodwill'' value over 10 years, arguing that it is `` phantom capital'' and has no worth when an institution is shut down. The bill passed by <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON>'s subcommittee would permit goodwill, in some cases, to remain on institutions' books for as long as 40 years. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> is proposing it be phased out over 20 years. The <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> plan gives S & amp; Ls five years to come up with extra capital to back subsidiaries investing in risky areas such as commercial real estate and junk bonds. The subcommittee bill did not require the extra capital. The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, based on a staff document, reported Monday that <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> would permit subordinated debt _ money <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls borrow _ to count for up to one-half of an institution's core capital. Aides explained Tuesday, however, that while subordinated debt will be permitted in capital, it will not be counted toward meeting the very minimum, or core, requirement.
