<HEAD>Agency Will Tell Court Owl Worthy Of Protection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it has dediced after all that the spotted owl is worthy of protection as a threatened species. Environmentalists hope the decision will save the ancient forests of the Northwest. The timber industry says the move could lock up vast areas of the region to logging. A federal judge in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> had given the agency until Monday to review its decision of more than a year ago not to list the owl under the Endangered Species Act. `` We will present a finding to the court that listing of the owl as a threatened species is warranted and begin steps to officially propose it for listing,'' said <PERSON> Meg </PERSON> <PERSON> Durham </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Once the owl is proposed for listing as a threatened species, a year-long review will begin during which management plans for protection of the bird could be developed and public comment sought. Ms. <PERSON> Durham </PERSON> offered no indication when the agency would actually propose the listing, but said the `` best scientific evidence'' available confirms the owl was worthy of protection. The Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in December 1987 refused to list the owl and environmental groups filed suit. District Court Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Zilly </PERSON> ruled the initial decision not to list the owl was `` arbitrary and capricious'' and gave the agency until May 1 to review its decision. The bird, which is thought to nest only in the old-growth forests of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, has become the focal point of a raging dispute between environmentalists and the timber industry. Environmentalists have sought to have the owl protected as part of their campaign to halt logging in the old-growth forests of the <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> while the industry has claimed such protection would close vast areas of the region to logging forcing dozens of mills to close and the layoff of thousands of workers. Court orders in related cases have already put a halt to more than 140 timber sales in the region's national forests. <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> officals have said those injunctions would interupt half of the harvest planned in the national forests this year and during the long-term the harvest could drop by one-third. <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> chief, has said under a `` worst case scenario'' more than 31,000 workers could loose their jobs and his agency's timber receipts from the region could be cut in half. `` They should have done it a year ago, but better late than never,'' said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Wilderness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, adding his his group believes listing the owl as an endangered species will require an end to logging in most of the remaining old-growth forests of the Northwest. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Pissot </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Audubon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> said the decision gives the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> an `` opportunity to focus on some of the real threats to the timber industry rather than using the spotted owl as a scapegoat.'' <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Salem </LO