<HEAD>Weekly Publishes 8-Page Cover Story On Late Cardinal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A weekly published what was believed to be the first detailed report on the late Cardinal <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Mindszenty </PERSON> and his show trial for treason, incarceration and seclusion in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomatic mission. In its latest issue, Idea carried a front-page photo showing the cardinal praying in front of an altar. Idea was formerly the publication of the <ORGANIZATION> Hungarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, which is now defunct. It now refers to itself as `` a political weekly.'' Displaying a degree of press freedom unthinkable only months ago, Idea carried an eight-page report that included an account of <PERSON> Mindszenty </PERSON>'s trial. It also made frequent references to his memoirs and printed a speech <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s Roman Catholic prelate made on Nov. 3, 1956, a day before Soviet tanks quashed a popular uprising against Soviet rule. In the speech, the cardinal said the main aim of the Hungarians should be the `` revitalization of the nation'' and demanded `` an all-out effort of the entire country for progress.'' <PERSON> Mindszenty </PERSON> also said, `` <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s fate will be decided by what the Russian Empire decides to do. We did n't attack <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>, and we hope that Russian troops will be withdrawn from <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>.'' However, it took almost 33 years for the Soviets to begin a withdrawal. A first batch of Soviet tanks were pulled out Tuesday, starting a partial pullout of 10,000 Red Army soldiers. <PERSON> Mindszenty </PERSON> was arrested in 1948 as an enemy of communism and, following a humiliating trial, was sentenced to life in prison on trumped-up charges of high treason. In 1956, he was freed from prison by Hungarian revolutionaries. After the Soviets crushed the uprising, <PERSON> Mindszenty </PERSON> found shelter in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mission in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> until 1971, when he left under an agreement worked out between the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. After a short stay in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mindszenty </PERSON> settled in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, where he died in 1975 at age 83. <PERSON> Konrad </PERSON> <PERSON> Szanto </PERSON>, a Franciscan and historian, was quoted by the magazine as saying there were increasing signs of a broad demand for the rehabilitation of <LOCATION> Mindszenty </LOCATION> along with others, who were imprisoned on similar phony charges. Last month, <PERSON> Imre </PERSON> <PERSON> Pozsgay </PERSON>, a Politburo member and leading party reformer, said <PERSON> Mindszenty </PERSON>'s trial would be reviewed as part of the re-examination of all political trials in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> between 1945 and 1962.
