<NOTE>End embargoed material</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 After the Hispanic reception in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> flew by helicopter to <LOCATION> Anaheim </LOCATION> to watch a baseball game between the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orioles </ORGANIZATION>. He was to remain in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> overnight and meet Wednesday with former president <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. At his first stop of the day, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said the best investment for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s future would be to cut the huge federal budget deficit, warning that `` tough talks still lie ahead'' to achieve that goal. He said the nation must be more competitive to sustain the economic recovery that has produced nearly 20 million jobs over the last seven years. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spoke to workers at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION>'s space systems division in <LOCATION> Palo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION>. The facility, which employs 2,000 people, produces communications satellites, tactical weapons systems, space systems and other high-tech products. After touring the aerospace facility, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told the audience that `` the best investment in the future is to slash the federal deficit. Every dollar the government does not borrow means more capital available for investment.'' He noted that he recently concluded a sketchy agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to cut the deficit to $ 99.4 billion in the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1. The blueprint does not provide much detail about how the reduction will be achieved. `` Now this plan's an agreed outline,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` Tough talks still lie ahead.'' He said: `` Think of deficit reduction as an exercise, like walking the dog every day. Believe me, I know, exercise keeps you at the top of your game.'' While challenging the nation to become more competitive in technological innovation, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did not offer any new initiatives. He made a new pitch to reduce the capital gains tax rate to 15 percent from its current level of 28 percent. `` Lower capital gains taxes will create jobs for those who do n't have jobs and help build a better <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' He laced his speech with television sound-bite lines such as `` I want to give the high-five symbol to high tech. And I want to do it by investing in competitiveness.'' Ticking off some of his proposals, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> noted he has proposed a permanent extension of tax credits for research and experimentation, and has asked <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for an increase of $ 2.4 billion for <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>. `` Let us use our own technological prowess to expand free and fair trade,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` I'm talking about excellence in such fields as microcomputers, superconductivity and, yes, aerospace.'' Before an audience of white-collar workers, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also extolled his proposal for a child-care tax credit for low-income parents. His plan would provide a credit of up to $ 1,000 for each child under age 4 in poor families. `` Our proposal urges a nex tax credit to make child care more affordable,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` And it puts money in the hands of the low-income parents, limits federal intervention and increases options. `` A church can help or grandparents or professional nursery,'' he said. `` When it comes to child care, we say, let the parents decide. Keep the family strong and we must do that.''
