<TEXT>
 Three years after <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> starred in an award-winning television special about schizophrenia, the actors have reunited for a production that can best be described as sobering. `` My Name Is Bill W.,'' which airs Sunday on <ORGANIZATION> ABC-TV </ORGANIZATION>, tells the story of <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, the late co-founder of Alcoholics Anonymous. `` This is a very unsentimental version of <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s life,'' said <PERSON> Woods </PERSON>, 42, who plays <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>. `` There are scenes in this picture that I think are literally hair-raising. There was no sentimental restraint placed on us. `` They allowed us to show the true story ... and it's a devastating story and it's not an easy story to watch,'' he added. The story focuses on the struggles of a stockbroker whose health and success are destroyed by twin calamities _ the stock market crash of 1929 and his own alcoholism. It details the days when <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> was unable to stop drinking despite the efforts of a devoted wife, <PERSON> Lois </PERSON> -LRB- played by <PERSON> JoBeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> -RRB-. Strapped to a hospital bed, he realizes he is helpless to defeat alcoholism alone. Most of the two-hour movie shows the horrors <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> faced before he met Dr. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, surgeon and drunk played by <PERSON> Garner </PERSON>. A church arranged for the two men to meet after <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, only sober for a short time and struggling to rebuild his life, arrived in <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION>. He was lonely, uptight and tempted by other drinkers. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, thinking <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> came to lecture him to stop drinking, was suspicious. `` Just what do you think a man like you can do for me?'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> asks. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> cries out: `` I did n't come here to help you. I came here to help me.'' <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> calls <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> `` two of the greatest men of this century, two drunks who got together to help each other and ended up helping millions of others.'' Filmed in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, the Hallmark Hall of Fame presentation was written by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Borchert </PERSON>, who read his script to the 97-year-old Mrs. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> on the back porch of her <LOCATION> Bedford </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, home last fall. `` When I got finished she reached for my hand, put her arms around me and we shed tears together. She said, ` I'm very happy this story will finally be told to the world.' Twenty one days later she passed away,'' he said. The production was the idea of <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Duchow </PERSON>, co-producer with <PERSON> Garner </PERSON>. <PERSON> Duchow </PERSON> met <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> in the 1950s and was convinced by 1953 the story should be told. But he could not pursue it for 30 years. <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Duchow </PERSON> discussed the project in 1983 but five scripts were rejected. `` Because there is a tendency to beatify <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, most writers really are influenced by the size of the membership and what all of that means,'' he said. `` Our feeling was always let's personalize by simply telling the story of <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, which was very difficult to get on paper. <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> had worked together more than once. As a fledgling actor, <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> played the villain in the first episode of <PERSON> Garner </PERSON>'s `` The Rockford Files.'' And in `` Promise,'' another Hallmark special broadcast in 1986, <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> played a carefree man forced to care for his schizophrenic brother, played by <PERSON> Woods </PERSON>, after the death of their mother. It lost in the ratings to a <PERSON> Dolly </PERSON> <PERSON> Parton </PERSON> television movie, but won five Emmy awards. <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> recalled hearing Duchow and <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> `` mumbling about their next project'' in a coffee shop at the end of filming for `` Promise.'' `` I kind of cocked an ear and thought there could be a job in this. I said, ` Heh. I'm Bill W. I could be <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON>' I did n't quite realize what I was about to embark on,'' he said. `` I have friends and people I love very dearly who in the course of work are alcoholics. Most of them have found Alcoholics Anonymous and a few have not and some are dead,'' he said. `` I just hope the few who are n't members will find their way in.'' Even before the production aired, it had an impact. After <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> appeared on television talk shows to promote the movie, <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> was stopped by a woman outside his hotel in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>; she said the actors had convinced her brother to join AA. A day earlier, <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> had told a luncheon gathering, `` If we can save one life, then we will go greatly beyond what we hoped to do, which was great entertainment, some information. If there's a life or two along the way that we can save, then we will indeed be blessed.''
