<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv28   04-25 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 28,0749</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, April 28, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>People Rate Religion News Important But Lean To Reading Sports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans think it's more important for newspapers to cover religion than sports, a new national study finds. But people are a bit more likely to read sports stories. Indications also turned up that increasing religious coverage likely wo n't do much to boost circulation, since religion-interested readers already make up the bulk of readership. `` The religious and religion-interested readers are already there,'' says the project director, <PERSON> Steward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. `` Religiosity and newspaper readership are statistically associated.'' Preliminary findings of the study, described as the first comprehensive research on press coverage of religion and interest in it, were presented recently to the Religious Public Relations Council convention in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Concerning the relative news importance of nine special fields, religion was found to rank about in the middle, below education, health and business, but above sports, food, personal advice, entertainment and art. When people were asked to rate their likelihood of actually reading about the topics, religion also ranked in the middle, but below sports. Ahead of sports again were health, education and business. The study, sponsored by <ORGANIZATION> Religious </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> under a grant from the <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endowment </ORGANIZATION>, included two national Gallup polls of 1,100 samples each, plus in-depth interviews in a variety of local congregations. Contrary to assumptions that people are primarily interested in local religion stories, `` we discovered great expressions of interest in national and international religion stories,'' said <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Weidman </PERSON>, RNS editor-director. In ranking the importance of types of religion news, the polls gave first place to `` social and ethical positions and pronouncements by major faith groups,'' such as on abortion, nuclear policy and the economy. While `` local church news and announcements'' ranked second, all the other highly-rated categories `` were national and international in scope, rather than locally or individualistically oriented,'' <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON> said. These included, in this order, `` ethical and social issues,'' the `` role of religion in foreign or international politics,'' the `` role of religion in American politics,'' and `` national religious issues and controversies.'' <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON> said the findings undermined `` tried-and true assumptions'' that readers want `` stories of faith and inspiration'' or opinion commentary about religion. These rated low in appeal. `` The findings confirmed what we have been hearing in our local-congregational interviews,'' <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON> said. `` People think of religion in national and even global terms. They know it is a dimension of other news. They clearly want that dimension to be covered well.'' Seventy-one percent of those polled called themselves `` daily readers'' and 81 percent said religion is important in their lives. Of these considering religion important, a higher proportion _ 80 percent are daily readers. More than half of the total sample _ 52.2 percent _ said it was important for newspapers to cover religion as well as other kinds of news. Asked how well the press covers the various specialties, sports got the most `` excellent'' scores, followed by business, food and entertainment. But a rather poor job is seen in religious coverage. It ranked seventh. `` The sad truth is that many of this country's almost 1,700 daily newspapers either ignore the religion story or amuptate it at the county line,'' Ms. <PERSON> Weidman </PERSON> said. A still incomplete part of the study involves interviews with eight newspapers regarded as covering religion well. Three already have been visited, the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Times, The Tennessean in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION> -RRB- Times. `` What these newspaper executive believe in common is that the religion story is central to interpreting life in their communities and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> culture in general,'' Ms. <PERSON> Weidman </PERSON> said. Debunking an old claim that a news professional needs to be religious to give a fair shake to religion, she quotes <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Wasson </PERSON>, city editor of the Tennessean as saying: `` I'm an atheist myself, but I have great respect for religion as a motivational force in people's lives ... Religion is simply not important to many reporters or editors personally, and thus they do n't understand how personally important it is to readers ... `` I think they do n't understand the richness of coverage available in religion. It's not just socials and churchy things. Religion is very rich turf in news value, and many editors do n't know that.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, April 28</NOTE>
