<SECOND>BC-Continent in Crisis-Slums, Adv 07,1208</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 7, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>CONTINENT IN CRISIS: Venezuelan Ranchos _ Where Riots Begin</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Teeming shantytowns sprawl across the hills surrounding <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and more and more, as economic conditions worsen, they are becoming breeding grounds for social unrest. An <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> correspondent visited one recently and filed this report, one of a series on the economic, social and political turbulence that has turned <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> into a continent in crisis.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By HAROLD OLMOS</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Zurbaran </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruiz </PERSON>, her commom-law husband and their eight children live in a tin-roofed, three-room shack called a rancho on the slope of a hill overlooking <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>. They consider themselves fortunate. He has a job making bricks 10 to 12 hours a day 100 miles away in <LOCATION> Valencia </LOCATION> for roughly the equivalent of $ 25 a week. The good life for her is being able to feed her the children corn bread and coffee, sometimes with milk, for breakfast; black beans and spaghetti for lunch and again for dinner; and meat on Saturdays, when her husband, <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Zambrano </PERSON>, is home. But <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Zurbaran </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruiz </PERSON>, who is 48 years old, said things wo n't be that way much longer She was talking about the recent turn of events in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> _ price increases that set off rioting down on the streets of <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> Feb. 27-March 2, leaving 276 people dead and about 1,000 injured. `` There are several bad years ahead,'' she said. `` Nothing will be easy anymore.'' Some of those who went down into the streets to protest, loot and burn were from <PERSON> Maria </PERSON>'s slum, <LOCATION> Rancholandia </LOCATION>. It is the kind of place in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> where riots, and sometimes revolutions, are born. <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> said she tells her children to prepare themselves for hard times. She has 14 in all _ 7 to 33 years old _ but just eight still live with her. `` I was blessed with 20 children,'' she said, `` but my triplets and another three died in the 60s from disentery.'' Millions like <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> and her family live in ranchos on the hills around Venezuelan cities. <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> and <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> are n't as poor as most of them nor as better off as some of them. She stays at home while he goes off to work Mondays through Thursdays in <LOCATION> Valencia </LOCATION>. Before leaving <LOCATION> Valencia </LOCATION> for home on weekends, he stops at a slaughterhouse and with part of his pay buys a kilo of meat _ 2.2 pounds. `` With <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> at home for the weekend, Saturday is the feast day,'' <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> said. `` Everyone gets a piece of meat mixed with a lot of boiled potatos so that everybody is full for the rest of the day. Maybe it wo n't be every Saturday anymore.'' She was thinking again about the price increases and the riots. The price increases were part of a government austerity program intended to halt the downward economic spiral <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> has been in since the collapse of oil prices a few years ago. The program called for the lifting of subsidies that kept prices low for the poor. At the same time, the bolivar, the local currency, was allowed to float for the first time in decades and prices for unsubsidized goods and services also rose. The government of President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> said it had no alternative, but it did not expect people to pour out of the ranchos as they did. They came by the thousands. In <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>, at least 50 percent of the population of 4 million lives in ranchos. Sociologists and politicians analyzed the sudden swarm of protest as the revenge of the have-nots against the rich. <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> said she had no part of it. `` Here we are all honest people. The ` malandros' -LRB- criminals -RRB- came from up the hill,'' she said, gesturing with her left thumb. There was n't much hill left before the top and it was hard to determine where the `` malandros'' could have come from. All that can be seen from <PERSON> Maria </PERSON>'s rancho are myriads of other ranchos crammed over the hills like a waving ocean of corrugated metal. Full employment is rare in the ranchos; many people are completely jobless, others are underemployed and still others make a living as street vendors. <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> considers herself lucky because <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> has the brick-making job in <LOCATION> Valencia </LOCATION>, where he stays with his mother during the work week to save bus fare back and forth every day. <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> adds about 400 bolivars -LRB- $ 13 -RRB- to the weekly budget by sewing pants on a neighbor's machine and sweeping a nearby school twice a week. But electricity is free in <LOCATION> Rancholandia </LOCATION> _ people simply hook into the power lines _ and water comes from a public line not far from <PERSON> Maria </PERSON>'s rancho. <PERSON> Ranchos </PERSON> began sprouting in Venezuelan cities only during the last 30 years, while the nation was establishing itself one of the most stable democracies in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Before that, the dictatorial governments that ruled most of the time since independence from <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> in 1811 barred the poor from building shacks in the cities. They were kept in rural areas and the few who made it into <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> were constantly harassed by authorities. But after the dictatorship of <PERSON> Marco </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON> collapsed in 1958, the poor were allowed in from the countryside and as the nation's oil economy burgeoned they flocked to the cities for jobs. <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> and other cities soon were overwhelmed by a new socialwing decade when <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> began to swell with oil money the couple built a sturdier one of adobe and concrete blocks a bit further down the hill. `` Now we do have space,'' she said pointing to the narrow, partly walled space where she cooks and does the laundry. At midday, it is the only cool place in her rancho. Heat in the rest of the shack soars over 100 degrees. `` This is the best we could get,'' she said. `` But I think my children will get something even better.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 7</NOTE>
