<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 30 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Studio Theme Park is Centerpiece of Building Boom at Florida Resort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A $ 400 million blend of big-league film making and <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> stargazing is making its debut as <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s top entertainment resort opens its newest attraction _ the Disney-MGM Studios theme park. The 135-acre complex at <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> combines working movie-TV sound studios with backstage tours for the public, a mixed-media ride-through show and special effects adventures. It's all `` themed'' to the flamboyant ambience of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>'s Golden Age in the 1930s and'40s, when a small group of moguls ran the studios with a firm hand Art deco and `` <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Crazy'' dominated the architectural styles. The park has its own entrance admission and more than enough activities to fill a visitor's entire day, <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> officials say. Visitors will walk through re-creations of palm-lined <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Boulevard </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Grumman </ORGANIZATION>'s Chinese Theater, peek at movies under production, take a role in an ongoing television show, make their own music videos, get a screen test and rub elbows with the stars at the <LOCATION> Brown </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Derby </LOCATION> restaurant. Movie and television production began last summer with the `` Superboy'' syndicated TV series and parts of several large-screen films, while construction continued on the tourist portion. Workers were still putting finishing touches on it prior to the opening on May 1. Chairman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisner </PERSON> describes it as one of the <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s most exciting projects `` It is a theatrical environment that is very close to the original conception by <PERSON> Walt </PERSON> <PERSON> Disney </PERSON>,'' he said in a recent interview. `` It's been on the shelf since the 1940s and is the culmination of a company dream. This attraction is unlike anything else we have.'' The grand opening to the public is preceded by a weekend of glitzy celebrity parties and previews that include a special on <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- April 30 -RRB-, and `` live'' tapings of the TV special and the new `` <ORGANIZATION> Mickey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>'' television series. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunis </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Attractions </ORGANIZATION>, believes bringing a bit of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> will lure new fans and encourage former visitors to return. `` We talked of doing a studio tour when <PERSON> Walt </PERSON> was alive,'' said <PERSON> Nunis </PERSON>. `` We've wanted to do this for a long, long time. It's a dream come true.'' Disney will get a full year's jump on its formidable competition, <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION>, which wo n't complete the tour portion of its $ 500 million complex until May 1990. Situated just a few miles down the road, Universal is billed as the nation's largest working studio outside of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>. Movie and TV production is already under way at the facility owned by <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Rank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. It is built on a 440-acre site. Universal will feature what it calls a `` total experience'' of Hollywood-style filmmaking to the public, making the visitor a participant in the action. It expects to attract up to 6 million visitors a year. Disney officials do not project attendance. Despite their well-publicized rivalry, <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> officials downplay the situation, insisting the competition is good for each other as well as <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. `` We've always had competition _ from <ORGANIZATION> Sea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Busch </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gardens </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boardwalk </LOCATION> and Baseball and many others,'' <PERSON> Eisner </PERSON> said. `` We welcome competition. It's good for <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Disney does things in its own way, and we feel comfortable that we will have our niche in the community.'' The Disney-MGM theme park is the centerpiece of a $ 1 billion-plus renaissance of the 27,400-acre resort situated in the pine woods and citrus groves of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Kissimmee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION>. Not that a rebirth is needed. After earning a record $ 3.4 billion in revenues and $ 522 million in profits in fiscal 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has on tap a number of `` openings'' at its <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> resort this year in addition to the studios. On schedule to open this fall is part of what it calls the largest convention-hotel complex in the Southeast. Making their debut this summer will be Typhoon Lagoon -LRB- `` the world's largest water park'' -RRB- and the <LOCATION> Pleasure </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> nighttime entertainment district. Built for the teen-age crowd, <PERSON> Nunis </PERSON> says Typhoon Lagoon will make all other water attractions as obsolete as <ORGANIZATION> Disneyland </ORGANIZATION> made amusement parks in 1955. `` We're finally going to be able to make wav