 `` Eight Men Out'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Video </ORGANIZATION>. VHS-Beta, $ 89.98. Rated PG -RRB- Who's on first. What's on second. I do n't know is on third. <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON> and <PERSON> Costello </PERSON> made the skit a classic in 1945, and viewers of `` Eight Men Out'' might just revive it. The movie, as earnest as it may be in trying to present the whole tangled scandal of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sox </ORGANIZATION> throwing the 1919 World Series, has enough faces and characters in it to pack a locker room. And it would take extra innings to comprehend who's doing what to whom `` Eight Men Out'' begins just as the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sox </ORGANIZATION> are about to meet the <ORGANIZATION> Cincinnati </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reds </ORGANIZATION> in the World Series. The team is owned by a penny-pinching, manipulative <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Comiskey </PERSON>, who has driven morale into the ground with his cheap wages. Enter scheming, sleazy gamblers to capitalize on the discontent. The ball players are approached by a cast of underworld types, and the deal is hatched for the team to allow the <ORGANIZATION> Reds </ORGANIZATION> to win the series. During the conspiracy, director <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sayles </PERSON> introduces the eight crooked players, their wives and sundry girlfriends, at least two gambling kingpins and their assistants, the team's manager and somebody's father. It takes a score card to keep track of the rest. The White-Sox-turned-Black-Sox yarn is a good one, but this movie has too many loose threads.
