 Symphony in B-flat; Psalm 23; <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Zemlinsky </PERSON>; <PERSON> Riccardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Chailly </PERSON> conducting the <LOCATION> Radio-Symphonie-Orchester </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> and Kammerchor -LRB- <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> -RRB- It's always a pleasure to come across an unfamiliar performer giving a familiar work a superlative reading. It's even better to discover exciting, lesser-known music, particularly when the performance is as excellent as that of <PERSON> Chailly </PERSON> and the RSO on this disc. <PERSON> Zemlinsky </PERSON> -LRB- 1871-1942 -RRB- was a prominent teacher, composer and international conductor whose musicial life centered in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>. He moved to <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> in 1938, escaped during the war to this country and died, oddly, in <LOCATION> Larchmont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, a suburb of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Schoenberg </PERSON> was his brother-in-law and pupil, and <PERSON> Webern </PERSON> also studied with him. <PERSON> Mahler </PERSON> was a friend and supporter, and <PERSON> Brahms </PERSON> recommended <PERSON> Zemlinsky </PERSON> to his own publisher. No lack of favor from the musical community here. He wrote a quartet of string quartets, a half-dozen works for orchestra and chorus, seven operas and three symphonies, including the B-flat in 1897 _ the year of <PERSON> Brahms </PERSON>' death. The work sounds at times like a cross of the better halves of <PERSON> Brahms </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mahler </PERSON>, though without their depth. But <PERSON> Zemlinsky </PERSON> has his own world of orchestral sound. <PERSON> Chailly </PERSON> understands that. He also seems to understand exactly what to do with each phrase, even more so at times than <PERSON> Zemlinsky </PERSON>, whose style can seem fragmented. Psalm 23 sounds more Mahler-esque, maybe because of the chorus. The recorded sound of the orchestra is crystal clear and nigh perfect. Instruments blend but stand out when need be, never out of balance. The RSO musicians play difficult music with panache. Buy this disc not because no collection is complete without <PERSON> Zemlinksy </PERSON>, but because no listener is complete without a desire to hear the new and unfamiliar. And buy it because <PERSON> Chailly </PERSON> and the RSO deliver a great performance. _ By <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Wakin </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
