<TEXT>
 `` Blast Off'' -LRB- EMI <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION> -RRB- _ Stray Cats Now this is the way to do a rock' n' roll reunion. Invite a couple of buddies over, turn the speakers up real loud and _ to steal a phrase _ blast off. The Stray Cats, pinup boys and rockabilly revivalists in the long ago days of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s first term, drifted apart when the hits stopped coming. Now they're back with `` Blast Off,'' an unexpectedly delightful reunion LP that kicks, snarls, scratches and bites. Unlike most ponderous reunions where middle aged rockers check their lawyers at the door, `` Blast Off'' sounds like that jam session with old friends where someone left a tape recorder on. Sure, it's more complicated than that. But it does n't sound that way, and that's the key. Age has n't diminished the Cats' skill and spirit. It may even have helped; singer <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Setzer </PERSON>'s voice has deepened into an effective growl with none of the precocity of his youth. And producer <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Edmunds </PERSON>, the ultimate kindred spirit, was a perfect choice to guide this project. His voice brightens the catchy singalong, `` Bring It Back Again.'' Do n't look for particularly deep statements. The Stray Cats must set a record for most songs on one 10-song album with the word `` rock'' in the title -LRB- 4 -RRB-. `` Everybody Needs Rock' n' Roll,'' `` Rockabilly Rules,'' `` Rockabilly Worlds'' and `` Rockin' All Over the Place'' are all high octane. For what it aspires to _ the soundtrack for a terrific party _ `` Blast Off'' is a howling success. _ By <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauder </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
