<HEAD>Star Watch: Doubts in the Tall Lane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> <PERSON> McGillis </PERSON> seems so strong-willed and controlled both on the screen and off that you wonder if she ever had doubts in her waitress days that she would reach the top of the acting world. `` Oh yeah, all the time,'' she admits. `` But there's also that part of you _ the driven side _ that says, ` I will,' and has that kind of confidence. But I think you will always have self-doubt. I still do. I continually wonder if I would ever work again. Maybe that's one of the things that drives me.'' Contributing to her air of confidence is her appearance: stately if not quite regal, with a cool beauty that would have melted the late <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitchcock </PERSON>. Was her height ever a drawback? `` Not to me. Maybe to other people, but no, I do n't think so. I suppose people say, ` How come you always play sort of stronger women, not the vulnerable, victim types?' I can maybe attribute that to my height. It's sort of hard to be a victim when you're 5-feet-10 and you're bigger than a lot of guys you're working with. Significantly, <PERSON> Jodie </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> was the gang-rape victim in `` The Accused'' and <PERSON> McGillis </PERSON> was the prosecutor who sought justice for her. In her new film, `` Winter People,'' <PERSON> McGillis </PERSON> plays both victim and protagonist. She is an unwed mother, ostrasized by her family, who stirs up a smoldering mountain feud and then resolves it with an act of supreme sacrifice. The Columbia release was filmed in the locale of the <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ehle </PERSON> novel, the <LOCATION> Blue </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>, under conditions that duplicated the hardships of living on the land 50 years ago. `` It was pretty rough to be out in the elements for so many hours a day,'' she recalled. `` It was cold and wet and damp. `` The emotional challenges of playing <PERSON> Coley </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> were very demanding, but that's why I did it. I wanted to see if I could hit those emotional peaks and valleys. `` Coley is a bit rebellious, but at the same time she is very traditional. She is very strong and impetuous, but at the same time very weak and feminine. Which are all sort of interesting things to portray in a character, because that's how we are in real life.'' Any resemblance between <PERSON> Coley </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>? `` Mmmm, yeah, I think so,'' she said. `` I think that I'm a bit rebellious, and yet very traditional at the same time. And I think I'm strong and weak at the same time. I'm very single-minded when I get an idea; nothing can stand in my way or change my mind.'' Filmmakers have discovered that about <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> <PERSON> McGillis </PERSON>. While she does n't push her weight around on a set, she does like to contribute to the creative process. And why not? `` I must say I've been very fortunate in not working with that type of -LRB- dictatorial director -RRB-. I've always felt that I could at least bring up an idea, and they can say, ` That's not a good idea,' or, ` I do n't like that.' I do n't take that personally. `` I've never worked with the kind of person who said, ` Just shut up and do it this way.' If I did, I probably would rebel a lot,'' she said. `` After a certain amount of time, an actor or an actress knows their character better than anyone else around. Once you've assimilated and really become this person, you know what you would do in a given situation than anyone else on that set. <PERSON> McGillis </PERSON>, 31, spent her early years in <LOCATION> Thousand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oaks </LOCATION>, halfway between <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ventura </LOCATION>. By a weird coincidence, her father was physician for her `` Winter People'' co-star, <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, then a Disney child star. `` I had a big crush on him when I was 8 years old,'' she said. The <PERSON> McGillis </PERSON> family moved to <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. `` We went on vacation and never came back.'' `` When I was in high school I took theater,'' said <PERSON> McGillis </PERSON>, whose new hair style is close-cropped blond and brown. `` I dropped out of high school to pursue acting, which did n't make my family happy. I studied a few years at the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> Conservatory of the Performing Arts, then I was accepted to <LOCATION> Julliard </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, where I studied for four years.'' During her last year at the <ORGANIZATION> Julliard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, she auditioned for a role with <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Conti </PERSON> in `` Reuben, <PERSON> Reuben </PERSON>.'' She appeared in a few TV movies without much notice. Then director <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Weir </PERSON> saw her in `` Reuben, <PERSON> Reuben </PERSON>'' and wanted her to test for the Amish woman opposite <ORGANIZATION> Harrison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> in `` Witness.'' `` I said, ` Of course, I know all about the Amish,' but I really did n't,'' she said, `` so I had to spend the weekend in the library. `` I had just gotten a job as a waitress in a restaurant where I had wanted to work for a long, long time. When they finally offered me ` Witness' a week later, I felt so bad about quitting the other job. You always want to work in a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> restaurant where there is minimal work and a lot of money.'' Even after the film she applied for another waitress job because she was worried she'd never work again. `` Witness'' and `` Top Gun'' eased her insecurity. Now she can even take a few months off, as she and her boat broker husband, <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Tillman </PERSON>, recently did, ferrying a yacht from the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>.
