<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--ArtDeco Adv5-7   04-25 0809</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Art Deco, Adv 5-7,0830</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, May 5-7 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: A Kaleidoscope of Art Deco Shapes and Forms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An unprecedented show on art deco brings together some of the best decorative works of the 1920s from 12 European nations to redefine the whimsical, elitist style of the rich and powerful. In all, 274 pieces _ from fine jewelry and glassware to massive, bulky dressers _ are on show until the end of May at the Beaux-Arts Palace, itself an art deco gem, to mark its 60th anniversary this year. The `` Art Deco in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'' exhibit aims to shed new light on the much-abused concept of the movement by highlighting work from as far apart as <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. The style is an eclectic ode to superficial prettiness for the rich who failed or refused to face the harsh social realities of the 1920s. The difference between art deco and other styles of its age is often very thin, said exhibit organizer <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Lambrechts </PERSON>, explaining why art deco has often been confused with, and used as, an amalgam of everything from stark modernism to flamboyant rococo. The kaleidoscope of forms and shapes at the Beaux-Arts Palace might still leave many visitors lost for a uniform vision of art deco. But then, <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Deco </PERSON> loved to `` quote'' from foreign and bygone styles, from the Japanese and Chinese cultures from rococo and classicism, much in the same way that postmodernism does today. <PERSON> Lambrechts </PERSON> said only the social idea behind the pieces constituted the art deco style. `` There is no unity of form, no real style,'' he said, only a common attitude of snobbery and elitism among art deco artists and buyers. Through his show, <PERSON> Lambrechts </PERSON> paints a picture of a gilded cage in which a spoiled European elite sought to shield itself from the revolutionary changes that swept society early this century. It did so by cultivating an art that had no meaning other than to please the eye. In contrast, the contemporary modernism of <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Corbusier </PERSON> and <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gropius </PERSON> thrived on the new technologies and social developments art deco shunned. Through its devotion to function and lack of ornament, it gave shape to many of world's modern cities. `` In almost all the capitals of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the high bourgeoisie tried to compensate the threat to its power with a refined culture, while the new rich wanted to create an identity by purely showing off,'' <PERSON> Lambrechts </PERSON> said. In return, <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Deco </PERSON> was dismissed as kitschy and tasteless for many decades. But in recent years it has found a new following as evidenced by the fact that over 2,000 people a day visited Lambrechts' show, which opened March 3 at <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Horta </PERSON>'s Beaux-Arts Palace in the center of <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> have long claimed to be the cradle of art deco. But Lambrechts' show breaks new ground there. It shows strong contributions from across <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, many of them on display for the first time outside their home countries. The exhibit is not as complete as Lambrechts would have liked, as much art deco was destroyed in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> who considered it decadent. Still, culled from 101 museums and private collections from around <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, it shows a lot of `` previously undiscovered beauty among the best arts and crafts this century has produced,'' <PERSON> Lambrechts </PERSON> said. What all the pieces have in common is a sense of luxury, expert finishing and craftmanship. Leaf-gold, silver, gems, <LOCATION> china </LOCATION>, delicate woods _ no costs were spared to produce a unique work of art deco. While modernists employed concrete and steel to allow function to prevail over style, art deco only wanted to impress with its flashy materials and ornaments. And impress they did. Dutchman <PERSON> Hendrik </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Den </PERSON> <PERSON> Eynde </PERSON> was lavish enough in his use of silver. But his 1918 urn flanked by four statuettes, shows some of the restraint other works at the show dearly lack. At the other end of the spectrum, Austrian <PERSON> Anny </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON> outrages with loud, clashing colors and seemingly irrelevant drawings of hunters and exotic deer on her 1919 mask. And nowhere is craftmanship and use of rich materials more evident than in the art deco jewelry of the <PERSON> Maison </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cleef </PERSON> and Arpels. Its 1927 vanity brooch of gold, enamel, christal, emerald, rubies and diamonds wrought by master hands is one of the highlights of the exibit. After spending some decades in relative obscurity, dealers are also quickly re-evaluating art deco. Some small tables have been sold for close to $ 1 million, and prices for all objects are rising constantly. `` Times have changed,'' said <PERSON> Lambrechts </PERSON>. `` Today art deco is even more expensive than French art of the 18th century.''
</TEXT>
