<HEAD>Music Makers: He Loves To Do That Wild Thang</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tone Loc, the raspy-voiced rapper whose bawdy `` Wild Thing'' went to the top of the charts, did n't think the tune about a pickup artist on a streak of amazing luck was hit material. `` The record company -LRB- Delicious Vinyl -RRB- did. I did n't. It's not my style of rap,'' the 22-year-old <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> native said in a recent interview. `` I mean, ` Loc'd After Dark' is really my style of rap _ slow and funky, that's how I like it.'' The song was a No. 1 hit for Loc, whose real name is <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. <PERSON> Loc </PERSON> is short for loco, a gang term for a crazy man who likes to fight. But <PERSON> Loc </PERSON>, who grew up in a two-story house on the affluent west side of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and went to <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Santa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, had to travel by bus to the city's tough south side to get his reputation. He was uncomforable dwelling on gangs during the interview. However, in the past he has said he was involved with a gang during his teens but withdrew because a girlfriend asked him to _ a choice kids locked into the southside scene usually do n't get. But his commuter-gang experience had nothing to do with his interest in rap, he said. `` I found it out on my own, clear out of the blue.'' <PERSON> Loc </PERSON> said a friend from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> came to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> about eight years ago with a tape that he rapped along to. `` I never saw anybody rap live before. It was pretty new, especially out here. I went home and tried to write one of my own, and it sounded pretty cool,'' he said. All the original big rappers, such as <PERSON> Kurtis </PERSON> <PERSON> Blow </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kool </PERSON> <PERSON> Moe </PERSON> <PERSON> Dee </PERSON>, were from the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. Only recently have <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> rappers been taken seriously in the genre. Early 1980s acts such as the <ORGANIZATION> LA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dream </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Team </ORGANIZATION> failing to take hold. <PERSON> Loc </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> rappers now have developed their own laid-back style rather than trying to imitate the uptempo hip-hop from the East. `` We've grown tremendously out here,'' he said. `` We've got a groove that slow. I'm a slower, more mellow type.'' <PERSON> Loc </PERSON>'s own rap experience came during high school, with a group called the Triple A's because all the members first names began with `` A.'' `` There really was n't too much happening with it. I think we were too good for our time,'' he said. Loc was a rap retiree by age 20, but took it up again when the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> rap scene began to heat up. A cousin introduced him to <PERSON> Matt </PERSON> <PERSON> Dike </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, founders of the small Delicious Vinyl label, and two of <PERSON> Loc </PERSON>'s records, `` I Got It Goin' On'' and `` I'm on Fire,'' received play on local station <ORGANIZATION> KDAY </ORGANIZATION> But it was the crossover appeal of `` Wild Thing,'' which got play on new wave station <ORGANIZATION> KROQ </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> last fall, that helped launch Loc, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> rap, and Delicious Vinyl, now distributed by <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION>. As for `` Wild Thing,'' <PERSON> Loc </PERSON> said he pieced the song together pretty much from personal experience. `` You change a little bit here and there, but the idea comes from something that happened to you,'' he said. Does he get any static for the lyrics? `` Nah. All the girls I know love it,'' he laughed. `` Besides, they know it's all true.'' Loc is currently on tour for his album `` Loc'd After Dark,'' which is climbing the Billboard pop and black charts, facing crowds of up to 18,000 in arenas. `` I was playing clubs in January and February,'' he said. `` It's different, but it's the same I really like the hype.'' And the crowds join in on `` Wild Thing.'' `` They rap right along with it,'' <PERSON> Loc </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Loc </PERSON> is casual so far about his own success. When asked, he did n't know exactly where his records were on the charts, except to say `` I know a lot of people are buying them.'' There is also street recognition for the husky 6-foot-1 Loc, who appears in the heavy rotation `` Wild Thing'' video clip, which borrows the expressionless all-woman band from <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON>'s `` I Did n't Mean to Turn You On.'' <PERSON> Loc </PERSON>'s own stock is soaring, and he finds some things more difficult to do, such as shopping in a mall. `` When I'm shopping or eating, I get swarmed. You can hear people saying ` Is that Tone Loc? Yeah, that's him.' But they're always nice to me and stuff, and I love that Plus, I can get into a lot more clubs now,'' he said laughing. `` It's nothing like <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> or anything, but I can definitely tell the difference,'' he said.
