<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: V.S. Naipaul Takes His Turn in the South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENEVA COLLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From `` Gone With the Wind'' to `` A Southern Family,'' writers have addressed the South with much sound and fury. But V.S. <PERSON> Naipaul </PERSON> has used his acute eye to furnish some fresh insights in `` A Turn in the South.'' <PERSON> Naipaul </PERSON>, a Trinidadian of Indian descent who has lived in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> for nearly four decades, spent six months traveling through the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, studying race relations, religion, the romance with the past and its wary concessions to progress. `` A Turn in the South'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Knopf </ORGANIZATION>; $ 18.95 -RRB- takes the reader from <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Naipaul </PERSON> begins his sojourn, through <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Tallahassee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Tuskegee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, Miss.; <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, and back to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Chapel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. He shows us Confederate monuments and catfish ponds, a self-proclaimed redneck and a <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> songwriter, fundamentalist preachers and a futuristic <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> assembly plant. The Oxford-educated <PERSON> Naipaul </PERSON> is the author of 19 other books, eight of them non-fiction works such as this one in which he exhaustively explores a locale; they are much too complex to be considered mere travel books. He is best known for his caustic pictorials of Third World countries, in both his nonfiction -LRB- `` <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>: A Wounded Civilization,'' `` The Loss of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dorado </LOCATION>,'' `` The Middle Passage'' -RRB- and his novels -LRB- `` A Bend in the River,'' `` Guerrillas,'' `` In a Free State'' -RRB-. For example, `` Among the Believers,'' his controversial 1981 account of the Islamic faith in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, probably would elicit a death threat from the <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> if it were issued today. One of the pleasures of reading `` A Turn in the South'' is experiencing the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> through the eyes of a world traveler. `` The land was flat, like the pampas of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> or the llanos of <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Naipaul </PERSON> writes of <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION>. Interviewing <PERSON> Naipaul </PERSON> about the writing of this book is another experience altogether. He detests interviews, submits to them only on the insistence of his publisher and endures them with a pained air and mostly terse responses. Asked in a recent interview, for example, to explain what kind of advance work he does before setting out on a destination, he said curtly: `` I do n't. I do n't do any research.'' When the interviewer points out that in his book he says he has obtained letters of introduction, that this sounds like advance preparation, and asks him how he decides whom to contact, <PERSON> Naipaul </PERSON> responded, `` That is always difficult.'' When pressed to elaborate, he would add only, `` It varies from place to place. It is one of the difficulties of the traveling business.'' Asked if he read any Southern authors beforehand, such as <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Faulkner </PERSON> or <PERSON> Eudora </PERSON> <PERSON> Welty </PERSON> -LRB- whom he interviewed in `` A Turn in the South'' -RRB-, he snapped: `` That's fatal. I always refuse to read in advance.'' After a pause he added, `` I always try to see what I've found. I'm a fairly well-educated, well-read person, and I've spent all my life writing, and I have a rough idea of the history of places. I like to go and see what I find and move from there. I do n't want to be reacting against other people's views.'' In `` A Turn in the South'' <PERSON> Naipaul </PERSON> writes that this will be his last travel theme book. Why abandon a format that has served him so well? `` I felt it at the time. I felt I was getting on,'' said <PERSON> Naipaul </PERSON>, who is 56. `` But what happened was I was so energized by it -LRB- researching the book -RRB-, so excited, so delighted _ I was so delighted by the method I had stumbled on in my middle 50s. I found it so true and interesting, and I so marveled that I had n't alighted on it before I found that at the end of it quite a bit of energy remaining _ or generated _ and I thought I should do a little more before my chest absolutely packs up on me.'' -LRB- <PERSON> Naipaul </PERSON> suffers from asthma. -RRB- The methodology to which he referred is to interview a wide range of people and to let them do the talking, rather than his old habit of spending a long period in a given place, quietly observing and analyzing, which he now says gives a more prejudiced account. <PERSON> Naipaul </PERSON> seems unaware that the `` new'' method he has stumbled upon is that used daily by journalists. <PERSON> Naipaul </PERSON>'s next trip will be to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, where he has traveled extensively, but he did n't know if a book would come of it. He said that because of his poor health he views every book as his last.
</TEXT>
