<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Roy Clark A Country Music Ambassador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Country music performer <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, the longtime star of the `` Hee Haw'' TV show, thinks the cornpone program would be received well in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> has made two concert tours of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, most recently giving 12 performances last November. He previously made 18 concert appearances in 1976. `` I'm sure they would be bewildered by the corny jokes, but the overall image of ` Hee Haw' would be compatible with their entertainment,'' <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said in an interview. `` They are interested in the history of the American West such as the cowboys. `` You see audiences in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in fringe and cowboy hats and the Soviets are the same way. They would identify with that image of ` <PERSON> Hee </PERSON> <PERSON> Haw </PERSON>.''' The 56-year-old <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, who has been host of the show since it first aired 21 years ago, foresees an entire wave of new viewers. `` There's a generation of young people who get together on Saturday nights and use it as an excuse to have a party in the -LRB- college -RRB- dorm,'' he said. `` It's gone around and made a complete cycle. We may become another fad. I have a feeling it will outlast me.'' The program, which is seen on more than 200 stations, is taped every June and October. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> says the fact that it's not a months-long process has contributed to the show's longevity. `` This keeps it fresh,'' he said by telephone from his office in <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION> `` We're not around each other enough to get on each other's nerves. It's a natural high energy for us to perform because it's like starting over twice a year.'' When <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> first appeared on the show, he already had been performing on prime-time network TV variety shows. But he said `` Hee Haw'' capped his career. `` This was the icing on the cake,'' he said. `` This put my face and name together.'' His recent appearances in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> have embellished his role as one of country music's major ambassadors. After his first tour there 13 years ago, which was made with the <ORGANIZATION> Oak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ridge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boys </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Country </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Music </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> gave him the title `` international friendship ambassador.'' He also performed in <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> last year where his concert was broadcast live and seen by more than 500 million people in socialist countries. `` There's a special feeling when you play in a foreign country,'' <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said. `` It's not just another concert. There is a lot of responsibility on your shoulders. `` You are representing your country first of all. Also you must represent your music well. The opinions of your performance reflects back on all the other country music performers. If the people do n't like it, they will think that's what all of country music is like. `` Your adrenalin definitely flows a little faster.'' His appearances were taped for television broadcast throughout Eastern Bloc countries. Soviet officials told him his concerts would be seen by 700 million people by the time they are broadcast and rebroadcast several times. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nashville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> on cable TV is carrying two one-hour specials about <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>'s Soviet shows. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said such a huge audience is a bit intimidating. `` The first thing you think about is how many mistakes you made,'' he said, chuckling. `` You wonder how many flat notes you hit and whether you looked tired and were at your best. `` But it was gratifying. There's nothing like recognition.'' He said the Soviet people were especially interested in the banjo. Crowds would gather at the foot of the stage to get a close look at his instruments, especially the banjo. `` You could tune one up and they would love it,'' <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said. `` They know the history of it as an authentic American instrument. They know it speaks of our heritage. And they like that brilliant sound of the banjo.'' <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> Meherrin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, grew up in <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clairsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. His father was a computer programmer for the federal government. He learned to play a homemade ukulele as a youngster and got his first guitar at age 14. He is accomplished on the 12-string guitar, acoustic guitar, banjo and fiddle and also plays five other instruments. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> has dabbled in acting, co-starring in the 1986 movie `` Uphill All the Way'' with <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Tillis </PERSON>. He's also appeared in the TV shows `` The Odd Couple'' and `` The Beverly Hillbillies.'' He is now approaching 30 years as a performer, having celebrated his 25th anniversary in 1985, and his foreign concert tours are not over. He plans to return to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> within two years. `` I'd like to keep the friendship going,'' <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
