<HEAD>Wing Mailer, Little Changed Since 1894, Still Addressing Newspapers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly a century after <PERSON> Chauncey </PERSON> <PERSON> Wing </PERSON> invented a simple device to stick mailing labels onto newspapers, his great-grandson is turning out almost identical Wing Mailers, handcrafted on turn-of-the-century lathes, for modern newspapers. `` Times change, but the Wing <PERSON> Mailer </PERSON> just goes along,'' said <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Wing </PERSON>, the latest in the long line of <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION> tinkerers and inventors to preside over the little brick mill in this northwestern <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> town. He estimated that 3,000 to 4,000 of the devices are being used by newspapers ranging from large metropolitan dailies, such as <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Hartford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Courant </ORGANIZATION>, to hometown weeklies. `` Many bigger papers use it to back up their computerized systems. The fancy electronics are only as good as the people who operate and fix them and they still have to get out the papers when the power goes off,'' said Wing. `` And for the smaller papers it can be a lot more economical.'' The device, which feeds a strip of mailing labels through a glue well and then cuts and affixes the labels onto the newspapers with a pull of the thumb, was invented in 1894. The family-owned company still occasionally gets back for repairs mailers made 50 and 60 years ago, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Sevrens </PERSON>, who manages the five-employee factory. The only difference between these older models and the ones made today is that after the 1920s, the mailers were made of aluminum instead of brass. Today the mailers cost about $ 215. Even the cherry-wood handles that <PERSON> Chancey </PERSON> <PERSON> Wing </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON>, editor of the <ORGANIZATION> Greenfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gazette </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Courier </PERSON>, chose for the mailer when <PERSON> Grover </PERSON> <PERSON> Cleveland </PERSON> was in the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> remain, still turned on a foot-driven lathe. `` There would be no purpose to changing,'' said Wing, 45. `` Our customers are familiar with it as it is. And we do n't care about being modern.'' In its one concession to the computer age, the company last year unveiled a new model, without a glue well, to handle pre-glued computer labels. But otherwise the 2 -LCB- - pound machine that has outlasted all its competitors is a hand-held anachronism in the heavily computerized newspaper industry The factory's only pause was during World War II when <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wing </PERSON>, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON>'s father, halted production to mill parts for top-secret radar research. The company's sales, including supplies, totaled $ 250,000 last year, <ORGANIZATION> Wing </ORGANIZATION> said. To step into the plant, near the family home, is to walk into the 19th century. `` Most of the machines were made here and some even predate the mailer,'' said Wing. A turn-of-the-century, five-horsepower electric motor in the basement powers the more than two dozen gear cutters, taps, dies and presses through an intricate arrangement of leather belts and pulleys that whir overhead. `` The electric bill for the whole plant is about $ 20 a month,'' said <PERSON> Sevrens </PERSON>' wife, <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON>, the office manager. It's hard to find people with the skill and inclination to work, often by eye, on the old machines, <PERSON> Sevrens </PERSON> said, but his fascination came early. `` I grew up in the neighborhood and did odd jobs for <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wing </PERSON>,'' said the young machinist. `` He was interested in everything and always working on all sorts of things. Tinkering. I just thought he was kind of a neat guy.'' <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Haskins </PERSON>, 78, who retired and returned twice `` because I do n't have a place where I can have a hobby,'' said he would n't want to work on a modern, computerized milling machine `` There's a nature to man that can be lost,'' he said. `` A machine can make a standard socket, but when you're finished there's nothing of toolmaker in it.''
</TEXT>
