<HEAD>Sales Stagnate In U.S., Akers Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> can revive its stagnant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sales and pull away from competitors by getting closer to its customers, Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> told shareholders at their annual meeting. `` <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> must become a company ... that wo n't rest until every customer is not just satisfied, but delighted, with every association with <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said here Monday. `` Everything else will follow, market share, revenue, profit, returns and stockholder value. `` We intend to accomplish all this ... not by selling them smaller and faster machines to replace more clerical duties, but rather working more closely with them to get an ever deeper understanding of their businesses,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s revenue in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the largest single market for the world's largest computer manufacturer, declined 0.7 percent last year to $ 25.3 billion. Measured in local currencies, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> sales grew 21 percent last year, the most among <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s major geographic markets, <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> said. Revenue in local currencies grew by 14 percent in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, and by 9 percent in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Because of changes in the value of the dollar in terms of various foreign currencies, the dollar value of foreign revenue was different from the value in local currencies. Overall, revenue outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> increased 15.5 percent to $ 34.4 billion when measured in dollars. By the same measure, the greatest revenue growth was 27.7 percent in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, followed by growth of 21 percent to $ 3.9 billion in the <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION>, according to the company's annual report. <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> is battling rapid advances in computer technology, growing needs of customers and thousands of competing companies, from the small and nimble to the big full-line vendors. `` As a result, the industry is under a good deal of stress as evidenced by pressure on profitability and decline in stock prices, including <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s stock price, over the last several months,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Armonk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, remains `` the most profitable company in the world and continues to lead all American companies in market value,'' <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> said. First-quarter profit totaled $ 950 million, or $ 1.61 per share, on revenue of $ 12.7 billion. After adopting a new treatment of deferred taxes, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> restated its 1988 first-quarter profit as $ 1.2 billion, or $ 1.57 per share, on revenue of $ 12 billion. Without the accounting change, the 1989 first quarter would have represented a 1.8 percent increase in profits. While in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> for the annual shareholders meeting Monday, the board increased the regular quarterly dividend 10 percent, from $ 1.10 per share to $ 1.21 per share. Management received overwhelming support for a proposal to expand a program of awarding stock options to executives. The company's Long-Term Peformance Plan will enable the top officers to receive stock as well as cash. Shareholders rejected a proposal to force <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> to discontinue selling computers and services in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, where it no longer owns a subsidiary. The proposal was supported by 14.5 percent of the shares voted. A proposal that would have required management to report to shareholders on any ways in which <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> supports painful laboratory experiments on animals received 7.8 percent of the shares voted. Management opposed both proposals.
