<HEAD>U.S. Judge Ties Up Massive British Takeover Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The clock is running out for South Africa-linked <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S.A. </ORGANIZATION> _ the world's largest gold producer _ to complete its hostile takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fields </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, the No. 2 gold concern. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mukasey </PERSON>, who issued a preliminary injunction barring the takeover bid in October, on Monday rejected another request by <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> to lift or modify his order. <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 4 billion bid expires at 1 p.m. <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> time Wednesday, and unless the Luxembourg-based conglomerate is able to acquire half of <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fields </ORGANIZATION>' shares by the deadline, it would be barred from attempting another takeover for one year under British law. <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> controls 29.6 percent of the stock of Gold Fields. Last month, the 2nd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> upheld <PERSON> Mukasey </PERSON>'s original injunction against further Gold Fields stock acquisition by <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> because it might violate <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> antitrust laws. <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION>, through its various holdings, `` is the largest producer of gold in the non-communist world, accounting for 20.3 percent of all gold production,'' according to court papers. Last fall, <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION>, which is largely controlled by two South African corporations, <ORGANIZATION> Anglo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANI