<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The contours of strike-torn <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> could be markedly changed under management's proposed plan to rebuild as a smaller carrier and sell $ 1.8 billion in assets. The plan presented Monday to <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s major creditors, which must be approved by them and a federal bankruptcy judge, would slash the airline's work force by 43 percent from levels before the strike that started March 4. Eastern's unions as well as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Judge <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> have been pushing for a sale of the entire carrier by its parent, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. If management's plan were approved, Miami-based <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> would cut its fleet size to 157 aircraft from the current 255 and the number of cities served to 77 from a pre-strike 102. Eastern President <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakes </PERSON> would not specify all the cities where <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> would cut service, but told a press briefing the company would sell its <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> shuttle service and <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> hub, along with a total of 117 unspecified airport gates and 28 landing slots, and de-emphasize some foreign routes. While keeping many of the plan's details under wraps, <PERSON> Bakes </PERSON> did say <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> would retain its <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> hub, its routes linking <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> cities with <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and some or all of its <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> service. The <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> hub, which vies with <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>, accounts for 35 percent to 40 percent of <ORG