n </ORGANIZATION> would emerge from Chapter 11 by September, <PERSON> Bakes </PERSON> said _ a target that <PERSON> Neidl </PERSON> called overly optimistic. Fleet size would be reduced by aircraft sales and by leasing planes to other carriers, Bakes said. Employment at the scaled-down Eastern would total about 17,000, down from a pre-strike 30,000, Bakes said. The total would include 1,700 pilots, down from 3,600 before the strike, he said. Eastern would cut its daily scheduled flight hours to 1,473 from 2,076 under the plan. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashby </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said the plan would not work, partly because <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> would not be able to get enough pilots to fly its planes. Bakes said Eastern plans to hire and train new pilots at the rate of 200 a month. Eastern indicated that by yearend under the plan it would have $ 1.8 billion in net cash from asset sales, giving it a net cash balance of $ 774 million after paying creditors and pension obligations. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> has insisted he no longer is interested in selling all of Eastern, following the collapse of a proposed $ 464 million deal with a group led by former Baseball Commissioner <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON>. The federal bankruptcy examiner for <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that further bids to acquire the airline could be made as early as this week by suitors who include hotel executive <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Pritzker </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Carl </PERS