<HEAD>NCNB Drops C&amp;S Takeover Bid That Would Have Been Largest Bank Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rather than wage a bitter battle with <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has withdrawn its $ 2.4 billion takeover attempt, scuttling what would have been the largest merger in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banking history. `` I recommended to our board of directors that we terminate the offer,'' <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> McColl </PERSON> said Monday. `` I did so because, as was evident in our proposal and throughout subsequent communications, we were committed to a friendly merger,'' he said. `` The management and directors of C & amp; S, for reasons satisfactory to themselves, have decided not to accept our offer. I see no benefit in continuing it.'' The announcement was made after the close of trading Monday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> had risen 25 cents a share to $ 36.37 -LCB- and <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Southern had fallen 62 -LCB- cents a share to $ 34. The merger, which consisted of a stock swap, would have created the nation's sixth-largest banking company. But the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> bank refused to discuss the proposal. C & amp; S chairman <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said he `` believed from the beginning that this offer was not in the best interests of our shareholders, customers, employees and communities, and that it would meet significant regulatory difficulties and public policy concern.'' `` Both these fine institutions can now get back to the business of banking and serving their communities,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. One analyst said he was n't surprised by <PERSON> McColl </PERSON>'s decision to drop the bid because <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> needed the merger to be friendly. `` They wanted to retain the management strengths of C & amp; S,'' said the analyst, <ORGANIZATION> Dennis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Just four months ago, <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION>, which has assets of more than $ 50 billion, effectively doubled its size when it was selected by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to acquire the largest bank in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> RepublicBank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. Since 1982, <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> has expanded aggressively into new markets in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>. The First RepublicBank move was the biggest until the C & amp; S offer. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, a bank stock analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Wheat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, agreed that <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> could not go ahead with the takeover bid without the support of C & amp; S's managment. `` I think you have to take them at their word,'' he said. `` They said they wanted a friendly merger. It was important as they approached the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> market that they had the endorsement of the folks at C & amp; S.'' <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> of Wheat First's <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION> office added that <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> needed a friendly merger because `` they have a full plate in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Shea </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> was going after a respected bank with a strong management team that could have offered the <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION> bank considerable help down the road in its expansion into <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. `` If C & amp; S continued to refuse to negotiate, <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> was not going to pull off a friendly merger,'' he said. `` I think <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> realized that it could not negotiate in a vacuum. They could n't just keep upping the price.'' <PERSON> Shea </PERSON> also suggested that <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> may have underestimated C & amp; S's unwillingness to participate in the deal <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> made the offer, which would have created a banking company with assets of $ 76 billion, on March 30, and on April 3, the C & amp; S board rejected the offer. At the time, C & amp; S called the bid `` inadequate,'' and said C & amp; S' present management was better able to serve the bank's customers, shareholders and communities than <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> continued to court C & amp; S, asking for face-to-face meetings, and adding different elements to the proposals, including a plan to move <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION>'s Southeast banking headquarters to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. On April 13, <PERSON> McColl </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and vowed to continue to pursue to the offer, though he did not meet with any C & amp; S officials. Five days later, C & amp; S Chairman <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> urged shareholders to support the <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; S board in its rejection of the <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> offer. `` Let me put it bluntly,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said at the time. `` <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> can not afford C & amp; S.'' Last week, <PERSON> McColl </PERSON> announced that his bank would increase its bid if C & amp; S officials agreed to meet with <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> executives. <PERSON> McColl </PERSON> did not indicate how high the offer would go.
