<HEAD>NWA Board Rejects Davis Offer, Amends Court Complaint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Calling parts of oilman <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>' $ 2.7 billion bid for <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> illegal and unfinanced, <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors unanimously rejected the offer and moved to take further court action to block the efforts. The board on Monday reaffirmed its willingness to negotiate with suitors, including <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, `` in the interest of producing a transaction that is in the best interests of all <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> shareholders.'' But it said it will seek a quick hearing on a motion to enjoin <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>' $ 90-a-share tender offer. The board also said it is working with an undisclosed number of other parties that have indicated an interest in acquiring <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's fourth-largest carrier. <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> stock closed at $ 102.75 Monday, up 25 cents a share in <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> composite trading. In an amended complaint in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> board said <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>' financing plan would exceed federal margin rules aimed at limiting the amount of credit used to buy stock. The board said $ 1.25 billion in preferred stock financing planned for <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>' buyout actually should be considered debt. The motion also claims <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>' tender offer actually was an illegal proxy solicitation that provided insufficient information to shareholders regarding the source and availability of $ 450 million in equity <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said he would provide for the buyout. In addition, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> Commerce Commissioner <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said Monday he found <ORGANIZATION> Davis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acquisition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s registration statement offering to purchase all of <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s outstanding shares deficient. <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> failed to disclose the manner in which he would operate <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> so as to expand its operation and not dispose of `` strategic'' assets of the company or lay off employees. Additionally, the commissioner said, <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> did not disclose plans relating to an Airbus maintenance facility that he said he intended to locate in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> scheduled a hearing on the matter for this evening, and said the registration would be suspended Friday if the deficiencies are not corrected. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Fingeroth </PERSON>, a Davis spokesman, said the acquisition company had no comment on the order. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>' attorneys, meanwhile, were shoring up their efforts in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> is incorporated. His lawyers argued in a <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Del. </LOCATION>, court against a provision in <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION>'s `` poison pill'' takeover defense that is hindering his efforts to put a new <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> board of directors in place. The defense effectively would block a new board of directors from selling <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> for 180 days. The prospect of a long delay would discourage shareholders from supporting <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> in the proxy fight planned at <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION>'s May 15 annual meeting, attorney <PERSON> Gilchrist </PERSON> <PERSON> Sparks </PERSON> told the hearing. <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothmeier </PERSON> has said he prefers to see the airline remain independent or find a `` white knight'' investor to work with current management. In letters to the 5,000 union pilots at <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Rothmeier </PERSON> said last week that `` there are alternatives available to us from friendly investors.'' But, he said, the assistance is contingent upon a contract settlement with the pilots, who have been working under two separate contracts since <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> acquired <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> in 1986. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>' <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> court action altered the course of his fight against the Northwest poison pill. He initially sought to invalidate the entire poison plan, which would more than double the cost of a potential acquisition by a hostile bidder by flooding the market with new <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> shares. But <PERSON> Sparks </PERSON> said Monday that <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> would like to retain the pill for his own use in the event he gained control of the board. <PERSON> Rothmeier </PERSON> has declined to identify any potential friendly investors, but the company has said a group holding 4.9 percent of <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION>'s 29.1 million shares outstanding is interested in a leveraged buyout. In a leveraged buyout, a company is bought with largely borrowed funds. The group includes Los Angeles-based investor <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Checchi </PERSON> and former <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> board member <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, now an executive for <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday that <ORGANIZATION> Kelso </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a small investment bank based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, is considering a bid for the airline. Spokesman for <PERSON> Kelso </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> declined to comment.
