<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar rose in quiet early European trading today. Gold prices also were higher. Foreign currency dealers said they were waiting for the 8:30 a.m. EDT release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> durable goods orders for March. A rise of 1.5 percent or more could send the dollar higher, dealers said. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar fell 0.21 yen to a closing 131.17 following Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s announcement he intends to resign. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 131.35 yen. Dealers in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> said <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s announcement did not affect European exchange rates because the markets had been expecting it for a week. `` It's very quiet today,'' said <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Zapfel </PERSON>, a trader at <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>. `` The dollar is n't doing very much ... We'll have to wait for durable goods to see if something will happen.'' Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday's prices, included: 1.8658 West German marks, up from 1.8575; 1.6460 Swiss francs, up from 1.6395; 6.3165 French francs, up from 6.2975; 2.0001 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0960; 1.1889 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1890 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound cost $ 1.7018, cheaper for buyers than $ 1.7050 late Monday. Markets were closed in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> for a national holiday. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 385.50 a troy ounce, up from $ 384.90 bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 385.85. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 385.50, up from $ 384.65 bid late Monday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose $ 1.51 to close at a bid $ 386.57. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 5.80 a troy ounce, down from Monday's $ 5.81.
