<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Scandal-Glance     04-25 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Scandal-Glance,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Glance At The Government-Toppling Recruit Scandal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Japan-Politics Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a glance at the Recruit scandal, which claimed its biggest victim today when Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> announced his intention to resign: THE ORIGIN: In late 1986 <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> offered bargain-priced shares in a real estate subsidiary to more than 150 leading politicians, bureaucrats, business leaders and media executives. The shares doubled in value after they went on public sale, yielding big profits to the holders who sold. Prosecutors, who have arrested 14 people, allege the transactions were bribes in which Recruit sought special favors from government bureaucrats in a position to influence or regulate Recruit's businesses in job-placement magazines or telecommunications. No politicians have been arrested. <PERSON> TAKESHITA </PERSON>'S LINK: Like most other politicians, <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s name was not on share transactions, but an aide and a relative profited to a total of $ 192,000. The prime minister also acknowledged that he received more than $ 1 million in political donations and contributions to fund-raising parties from Recruit. He told Parliament the donations were legal and sought to put the matter behind him, but over the weekend he also said he received a loan of $ 381,700 from Recruit in 1987 and was embarrassed at having to change his story. ALSO LINKED: Former Prime Minister <PERSON> Yasuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON>, under whose administration the share transactions took place. His aides reportedly received 29,000 shares and were estimated to have profited to the tune of $ 460,000. RESIGNATIONS: Three members of <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> resigned because of money links to Recruit. They were Finance Minister <PERSON> Kiichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON>, Justice Minister <PERSON> Takashi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hasegawa </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Harada </PERSON>, director general of the <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. ARRESTS: Recruit's founder, <PERSON> Hiromasa </PERSON> <PERSON> Ezoe </PERSON>, faces multiple charges of bribery along with several executives of the conglomerate and its subsidiaries. Among others charged with accepting bribes are <PERSON> Hisashi </PERSON> <PERSON> Shinto </PERSON>, former chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s giant telecommunications utility; <PERSON> Kunio </PERSON> <PERSON> Takaishi </PERSON>, former vice minister of education; and <PERSON> Takashi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kato </PERSON>, a former vice minister of labor.
</TEXT>
