<FIRST>r f PM-SellinginPoland 1stLd-Writethru   04-25 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Selling in Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Something New: A Well-Stocked Store of Western Clothing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: To ADD government estimate of amount of U.S. currency circulating
in the country, INSERT one graf after 12th, `Thus, a ... 100,000 zlotys.'
Picks up 13th pvs, `In the ...' ^By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The high-profile Italian retailer <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION> has opened its first store in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, shocking shoppers accustomed to empty shelves with mounds of colorful clothing and prices in their own currency. Sales clerks reported the most common question was `` Dollars or zlotys?'' as a storefront on <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>'s main shopping street, <PERSON> Ulica </PERSON> <PERSON> Marszalkowska </PERSON>, on Monday turned into a glistening <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION> outlet with its crisp, modern look. The Italian retailer is on the leading edge of marketing by Western companies in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> has been trying to attract such businesses to help shore up its ailing economy. Stacks and stacks of knitwear in bright hues of orange, blue, and yellow were folded on open shelves in the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> store on Monday. A bevy of saleswomen in <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION> outfits volunteered assistance. In short, the new store at first looked and sounded very unlike a typically bare Polish store with its clerks' curt replies of `` <PERSON> Nie </PERSON> ma'' _ `` There is none.'' Within hours of opening, however, the store had acquired the customary line. `` The first day probably will be pretty violent, since it is something new,'' said saleswoman <PERSON> Elzbieta </PERSON> <PERSON> Makucz </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION> is the first Western clothing retailer to open an outlet selling for zlotys in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, which increasing has a two-currency economy but is plagued by a shortage of quality consumer goods. Many desirable goods, from cocoa to cars, are bought for dollars in special shops or by private arrangement. Many of <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION>'s first shoppers found the zloty prices astoundingly high. A hot pink sweatshirt was offered for 78,000 zlotys, about the average monthly salary. Last month, Poles became able to legally trade dollars for zlotys at about the same rate _ now 4,000 zlotys per dollar _ as on the black market. Thus, a Pole with $ 25, perhaps sent by a relative abroad, can turn it into 100,000 zlotys. In a 1988 report, the government estimated that $ 5 billion in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency was circulating in the country and another $ 2.8 billion was deposited in bank accounts. Many other hard currencies are, of course, also in circulation. In the joint venture with <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION>, the state-run fashion company <ORGANIZATION> Moda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Polska </ORGANIZATION> is buying merchandise from the Italian retailer in hard currency and translating the prices to zlotys. `` I first of all want to be a businessman,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Moda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Polska </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Marek </PERSON> <PERSON> Zembrzuski </PERSON>. He said <PERSON> Moda </PERSON> <PERSON> Polska </PERSON> spent about $ 400,000 for the first <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION> stock, out of about $ 5 million to be spent on imported goods this year. The hard currency is obtained through exports and auctions of hard currency, he said. For <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION>'s part, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> is one of a series of new markets explored by the company. There are nine <ORGANIZATION> Benettons </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, five in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and seven in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Renata </PERSON> <PERSON> Sponchiado </PERSON>, who represents management in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. However, the other East bloc <ORGANIZATION> Benettons </ORGANIZATION> do not accept local currency, <PERSON> Zembrzuski </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION> designed the store and trained the staff _ there is even a company style for folding clothes _ but <ORGANIZATION> Moda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Polska </ORGANIZATION> operates it. `` Moda Polska and <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION> are two young companies, and this is a good starting point for us,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Eva </PERSON> <PERSON> Villax </PERSON>, who set up the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> store for <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION>. She predicted other company outlets in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. One man, who was among the first shoppers, left Monday with two bulging trademark-green shopping bags and an enthusiastic review: `` It is a great idea. There is a much bigger choice.'' He said the prices seemed about the same as those in stores that accept dollars. However, some women peering at the display window had other ideas. `` The prices shock me,'' said one. `` It is not even worth looking,'' said another.
</TEXT>
