<HEAD>Employment Costs Up 1.2 Percent For First Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 5 grafs after 3rd graf, The index, with analysts' reax;
picks up at pvs 4th graf, The 1.2. This also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The cost of wages, salaries and benefits to the nation's employers rose 1.2 percent in the first quarter of 1989, with increases in benefits costs again outpacing pay gains, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported today. The Employment Cost Index report showed that for the 12 months ended March 31 the cost of wages, salaries and benefits rose 4.8 percent, down slightly from the 5 percent average for calendar 1988 but up significantly from the 1987 jump of 3.6 percent. The index measures changes in an employers' costs for all forms of compensation, principally wages and salaries and employer-paid benefits such as health insurance. It is closely watched as a barometer of inflation, particularly in the past year as analysts have speculated that the tight labor market would drive up compensation costs because of increased competition for workers. Analysts disagreed over whether the figures signaled a faster pace of wage gains and therefore increased inflationary pressure on the economy. `` The numbers are reasonably favorable and there are no signs of wage acceleration,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, president of a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> economic forecasting firm. `` Except for the one sore spot of rising health care costs ... I think the figures show wage gains continue to be stable and no signs of rapid acceleration.'' But economist <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Brinner </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, said the report indicated labor costs are `` creeping up.'' He predicted the annual rate of employer cost increases, which would be 4.5 percent if the first-quarter numbers held throughout the year, would climb to 5 percent and possibly to 5.5 percent over the next year. `` With unemployment down to almost 5 percent, workers feel that they can ask for their normal share _ which is the sum of inflation and productivity,'' <PERSON> Brinner </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. Inflation on U.S.-produced goods is about 4.5 percent and productivity gains have been in the 1 percent to 1.5 percent range. The rate of employer costs could slow, however, if unemployment rises. <PERSON> Brinner </PERSON> predicted that the civilian jobless rate, 5.0 percent last month, would edge up in the next quarter and reach 5.5 percent or slightly higher by year's end. The 1.2 percent increase in the index for the first quarter compared with 1.0 percent in the final quarter of 1988 and 1.4 percent from the first quarter of last year, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported. The increase for the first three months of 1989 was attributed to a 1.1 percent jump in wage and salary costs and a 1.8 percent rise in employers' costs for benefits. Escalating health care costs have been the largest factor in the rising costs of benefits. For the year ended March 31, the government said wages and salaries for workers in private industry rose 4.2 percent while the cost of benefits rose 5.1 percent. Employer costs for workers in service industries rose 1.5 percent in the first quarter, up from 1.2 percent in the final three months of 1988 and the 1.3 percent gain reported in the first quarter of 1988. In the goods-producing industries, employer costs rose 1.0 percent for the quarter, up from 0.8 percent in the final quarter of 1988 but down from the 1.8 percent jump reported for the first quarter of last year.
</TEXT>
