<HEAD>Are Incentives Working Or A Dud? Today's Figures Should Tell</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 15th graf pvs, `Meantime, Ward's ...' with 4 grafs to UPDATE
with GM second-quarter production cuts.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Today brings another critical test for the auto industry _ the first full sales period of the latest round of incentives _ and carmakers are looking for the consumer response that so far has eluded them. `` I'm holding my breath a little on this one,'' auto analyst <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laughlin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. Sales during March were lower than expected, prompting <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to institute new, expensive incentive programs. Partially because of those enticements, car and light truck sales during early April were 28.3 percent higher than the same period last year. But sales during the first 10 days of April last year were among the lowest of the year, distorting comparisons with this year's performance Sales rebounded in mid-April 1988, meaning today's year-to-year comparisons will give a better snapshot of how sales are faring compared to the same time in the second-best sales year in industry history. Automakers had counted on strong March and April sales to shrink inventories and put off the need for large-scale production cutbacks. `` I guess you'd say they -LRB- incentives -RRB- are working but not as well as they used to,'' analyst <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. `` If that's so, mid-April sales were better than the March rate but not as good as early April.'' <PERSON> Laughlin </PERSON> said he was watching interest rates particularly closely. `` If interest rates start to trend down, I think that would alleviate some of the concern -LRB- among automakers -RRB- about the impact of this particular -LRB- incentive -RRB- program, `` he said. `` It would suggest that things will be easier in the next few months. `` If interest rates hang up here, it may be a source of concern for the industry.'' One of the first places any industry concern would be noted is in the companies' production schedules. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> held to ambitious production levels through the first quarter of this year, leading some analysts to speculate that production rates would have to be changed later this year, especially at model-changeover time in the third quarter. Today, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> analyst <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Windecker </PERSON> said the nation's No. 2 automaker was cutting about 2 percent from its second-quarter production schedule as part of `` fine tuning.'' `` Our market share continues to move up, but we will cheerfully admit the industry is a little softer than we thought it would be,'' he said. The cuts, <PERSON> Windecker </PERSON> added, would come in overtime <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> has been running at all but one of its 18 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Canadian assembly plants. The company's <LOCATION> Oakville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, plant, which makes the Ford Tempo and Mercury Topaz, is operating on straight time. <PERSON> Windecker </PERSON> said third-quarter production schedules are due out later. Meantime, <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>'s Automotive Reports, a weekly industry newsletter, said in Monday editions that <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> had cut its production schedule by 60,000 cars for the third quarter of 1989. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Pyden </PERSON> refused to comment on the report, saying final production figures for the July-September period are n't set. However, he confirmed the nation's largest carmaker had cut its second-quarter production schedule by about 3 percent. `` The vast majority of it is elimination of some of our planned overtime,'' he said. `` This does not change our yearlong sales forecast for 1989. We will approach 15 million units.'' <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s original production schedule for mid-1989 was scaled back from first-quarter levels.
