<HEAD>For release at 12:30 p.m. EDT _ set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Renews Plea for Cut in Capital Gains Tax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said today that critics `` could n't be more wrong'' when they call his proposed cut in capital gains taxes `` a tax break for the rich.'' Rather, he said, that proposal and other new investment incentives are needed to help <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> compete in the global economy. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> took note of the criticism of his proposal in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and elsewhere in a speech prepared for managers and employees at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION>'s Space Systems Division here. `` Well, they could n't be more wrong,'' he said. `` Lower capital gains taxes will create jobs for those who do n't have jobs, and help build a better <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' Capital gains taxes are levied on the profits that businesses and individuals make on investments. The president wants to cut the 33 percent maximum tax on capital gains to 15 percent and to exempt entirely the gains accrued by people with incomes under $ 10,000 a year. When fully effective in 1995, the tax break for capital gains would apply to assets held for 36 months or longer. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, and other top congressional Democrats have criticized <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for pushing the capital-gains reduction, which they term `` a tax break for the rich,'' while opposing legislation to increase the minimum wage to $ 4.55 an hour from the current $ 3.35. In his Palo Alto speech, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also put in a fresh plug for his proposed tax credit aimed at making child care more affordable for the poor. This came a day after it was disclosed that he had come out against a reduction in the surtax paid by older Americans for <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> coverage of catastrophic illiness. The president noted that demographic changes in the American labor force indicate that the majority of new job-seekers in the years ahead will be females, minorities and immigrants. To keep abreast of the rapidly changing technologies and the change in the labor markets, he said, businesses must have incentives to make the kinds of investments that will create new jobs _ and he suggested that many of these new jobs will come in the high-technology area. `` Lower capital gains taxes will create jobs for those who do n't have jobs, and help build a better <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' he said `` So let us act to lift revenue, help savings, and free American businesses, without distorting world markets.'' `` My friends, I want to give the high five to high-tech. And I want to do it by investing in competitiveness,'' he said. The president was coupling his <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> economic speech today with a pep talk downstate to officers at a narcotics-enforcement training institute in Rancho del Rio. The disparate themes of the four-day <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> trip, which will conclude Thursday in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, seemed aimed at projecting an active president in the final seven days of the first 100 _ a milestone that has been used to report first impressions of the president's stewardship of national affairs <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has sought to minimize the importance of the 100-day marker for presidential performance. But during a speech Monday to the annual luncheon of <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> newspaper publishers in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, he went ahead anyway. `` We've made a good start these first three months,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` So while I'm pleased with all we've accomplished in these three months, there's a long road ahead of us.'' Meanwhile, in a letter made public Monday, the president came out against any quick moves to reduce the surtax for <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> coverage of catastrophic illness. In the letter, released by Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said it would be `` imprudent to tinker'' with the program even in light of a congressionally projected surplus in its reserves Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, last week raised the possibility of a reduction of up to 16 percent in the surtax. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, however, said in the letter that financial reserves for the program `` are not excessive'' and may actually be `` too thin.'' He said the surplus projections are based on uncertainties in a program that is only a few months old. The president set aside the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> plant speech today to laud the more than 75-month recovery from the 1981-82 recession and the nation's 5 percent unemployment rate, which is at the lowest level in 15 years. But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also wanted to warn anew of an <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> that is declining competitively in the global economy. The merchandise trade deficit fell from $ 152.1 billion in 1987 to $ 118.7 billion last year _ a 22 percent reduction which represented the first annual improvement since 1980. But the deficit has been on an upward trend more recently, with the red-ink figure at $ 10.5 billion in February, which was more than 20 percent above the January figure. `` We had a tremendous improvement in the trade figure last year, but we're now seeing a pause,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON>, chairman of the president's <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisers </ORGANIZATION>. `` When you go through a very substantial growth in exports, as we did last year, you often see such a pause and an adjustment.'' Speaking to reporters en route here on Air Force One, <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON> said that many businesses and industries are still trying to build up to capacity production. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will travel to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> on Wednesday to be reunited with the president he served as vice president for eight years, <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. Later in the week, the president will address the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> and make drug-related appearances in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Clearwater </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, before returning to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> late Thursday.
