<HEAD>Hundreds Arrested, Setting Off Rally That Shuts Down Town</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs, picking up 3rd graf pvs, and SUBS 9th graf,
``UMW District 28,'' with 5 grafs to recast and UPDATE with high school
students rallying in support of miners.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLINTWOOD, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 High school students walked out of class and rallied today in support of miners on strike against <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a day after the walkout turned nasty with the arrests of at least 200 miners. Seven striking members of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> said they were injured in Monday's arrests. Many strikers accused <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> state troopers of being unnecessarily rough. Most of the town's businesses closed for Monday's daylong rally in support of the strike, now in its 20th day. `` It's not criminal to stand up for what you believe in,'' <PERSON> Marty </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON>, executive assistant to the union vice president, told about 300 people at the rally in this western <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> town of about 1,400 people. `` There's going to be a lot more people in jail because it ai n't over.'' State Police Sgt. B.I. <PERSON> Sparks </PERSON> said about 200 miners and their supporters were arrested and charged with obstructing a free passage, Route 773, and were being released on their recognizance. Union members estimated the number arrested at closer to 300. An exact count was not immediately available because the numbers overwhelmed local officials, forcing them to turn a courtroom into an impromptu holding cell. `` There's not enough cells to hold us,'' <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> said. The 1,400 <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> employees in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and 300 in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> went on strike April 5, accusing the company of unfair practices during contract talks. The miners had been working without a contract since February 1988. About 200 union members gathered today at the <PERSON> McClure </PERSON> mine but did not block the road or mine entrances. No one was arrested. However, `` I think all of them here were prepared to go to jail if necessary,'' <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> 28 President <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Stump </PERSON> said today. Also, about 150 <ORGANIZATION> Clintwood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> students walked out of class today and rallied at the <ORGANIZATION> Dickenson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Courthouse </ORGANIZATION> in support of the miners, officials said. `` They're sort of walking around in the street in front of the courthouse,'' waving signs and chanting, said deputy county clerk <PERSON> Lula </PERSON> <PERSON> Large </PERSON>. She said a single police officer watched the students for a while, then left. `` The principal came down and talked to the children and asked them to go back to class,'' but the students refused, Large said. A secretary at <PERSON> Clintwood </PERSON> <PERSON> High </PERSON> said she was instructed to tell callers that school officials had no comment. Monday's arrests capped a day of civil disobedience by the union, which used more than 1,000 members to block entrances to <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION>'s Moss No. 3 preparation plant and 200 others to block the <LOCATION> Lambert </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fork </LOCATION> mine, both in <LOCATION> Russell </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, in addition to the <PERSON> McClure </PERSON> mine. Also Monday, the union expanded its strike against <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> to temporarily include <ORGANIZATION> Westmoreland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which it accused of plotting to provide <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> with 200,000 to 300,000 tons of coal to fulfill contracts. <PERSON> Westmoreland </PERSON> has denied that charge. The <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> employees on strike in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> were joined on the picket lines by about 750 <LOCATION> Westmoreland </LOCATION> employees who are taking off three of the 10 `` memorial days'' _ or personal days _ allowed by their contract. State police treatment of those arrested infuriated some union members and supporters, some of whom displayed signs that said `` Welcome To <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'' and `` Cut State Police Pay and Benefits.'' <PERSON> Sparks </PERSON> said he was aware of some reports of injuries. `` They were just complaints of injuries,'' he said. `` We do n't know whether there were actually injuries.'' Six miners who said they received cuts and bruises while being arrested were treated and released at <ORGANIZATION> Dickenson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Clintwood </LOCATION>. A seventh was admitted with reports of blurred vision, and was held for observation. <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Odom </PERSON> and company spokeswoman <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON> did not return phone calls from The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Monday.
