<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Lower On Forecasts For More Rain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly lower this morning on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> on forecasts for more rain in key crop-growing areas during the next week to 10 days. `` There's more agreement right now than there's been,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Frazier </PERSON>, a grain-market analyst in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Balfour </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maclaine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, referring to the wide disparity in forecasts last week. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> predicted normal temperatures and normal rainfall for the Corn Belt in a six-to-10-day forecast issued late Monday. Meteorologists also predicted increased precipitation in the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, where the winter wheat crop has been severely damaged by dry weather. Early declines in the wheat market are also linked to reports that the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> rejected <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s bid for 300,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat. In early trading, wheat was 1 \ cents lower to \ cent higher with the contract for delivery in May at $ 4.14 -LCB- per bushel; corn was 1 \ cents to 3 cents lower with May at $ 2.67 \ per bushel; oats were 1 \ cents to 2 -LCB- cents lower with May at $ 1.94 -LCB- per bushel; soybeans were 7 -LCB- cents lower to 1 cent higher with July at $ Cattle futures were lower, while pork futures were mixed during early trading at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .25 cent to .62 cent lower with June at 70.15 cents per pound; feeder cattle were .05 cen