<HEAD>Auto Sales Up Slightly</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs version planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales of cars and light trucks made by the nation's Big Three automakers rose 4.7 percent in mid-April compared with last year, mainly because of a strong performance by <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the companies said Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> reported their vehicles sold at an average daily rate of 38,686 during the April 11-20 period this year, compared with a rate of 36,956 cars and trucks a day during the same time last year. Car sales rose a modest 2.1 percent and truck sales were up 9.3 percent during the period, in which each of the Big Three had new incentive packages in full force. The companies have been banking that incentives announced at the end of March and in early April would entice customers into showrooms and help pull the industry out of a lower-than-expected sales slump during the first three months of the year. Normally, March and April sales are robust, but they failed to live up to that billing last month, hence the incentives. For the first 20 days of April, Big Three car sales were up 12.1 percent and truck sales were running 15.6 percent ahead of last year's pace. Since Jan. 1, car sales by the Big Three were down 8.4 percent and truck sales were off 1.2 percent compared with last year. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said its mid-April car sales were running 14.5 percent ahead of last year's pace, going to a daily rate of 8,348 this year from 7,292 during the period last year. So far in 1989, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales were running 1.1 percent ahead of last year's pace. Truck sales by <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> were up 4.9 percent during the 10-day period this year, and were down 2.4 percent for the calendar year. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> reported a 1.5 percent decrease in its mid-April car sales, with a daily rate of 12,296 this year, compared with 12,483 last year. So far this year, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> has sold 11 percent fewer cars than last year. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s light truck sales were up 14.7 percent in mid-April and down 2.4 percent so far this year. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> said its average daily car sales rate fell to 3,374 during mid-April this year, a 10.3 percent decline from the 3,760 rate during the period last year. Car sales by the nation's No. 3 automaker for the year were running 18.2 percent behind last year's pace Truck sales by Chrysler during the period were 7.1 percent above the mid-April pace last year, and for the entire year were 2.6 percent ahead of last year.
</TEXT>
