 <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has ordered 18 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 jetliners and taken options on 36 more in a deal with a potential value of about $ 1.7 billion, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airplanes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. The announcement was the latest indication that the aerospace giant is continuing on a roll of large aircraft orders. It came just one day after <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s annual shareholders meeting, at which the plane manufacturer announced increased dividends and a stock split, and predicted record-breaking sales this year. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> considers a plane sold when it is delivered to the buyer. The <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> order includes flexibility for the airline to decide later whether it wants jets in the 737-300, -400 or -500 series. The -500 is the smallest, with capacity of 100 to 132 passengers, and the -400 is the largest, able to carry 145 to 170 passengers. Deliveries of the 18 firm orders will be one a month during 1991 and two monthly during the first quarter of 1992, with options possibly exercised in 1994 and 1995. The latest transaction brings <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>'s current <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 orders to 68 aircraft, which will be delivered between now and 1992, plus 96 options, which would be delivered between 1992 and 1995, <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> said. Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> currently operates a fleet of 56 737-300s, the most of any airline. <ORGANIZATION> Piedmont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, operates 39 737-300s and 14 737-400s and has six additional 737-400s on order. <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> will be merged with <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> on Aug 5. With the <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> order, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> has received orders this year for 319 jetliners valued at about $ 19.7 billion. Of those, 120 orders are for 737s. In all of last year, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> had orders for 636 planes, valued at $ 29.7 billion. Total 737 orders stand at 2,384, making it the most popular commercial jet of all time. <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> also has ordered 20 <ORGANIZATION> Fokker </ORGANIZATION> 100 jets and holds options on 20 more. First delivery is scheduled for June. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> recently decided to buy as many as 40 MD-82 aircraft from <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>.
