<SECOND>AM-Branstad-Drought,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iowa Governor Asks Federal Drought Help For Cattle Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Branstad </PERSON> asked federal officials Tuesday to help soften the effects of a spring drought by activating emergency feed programs and allowing cattle to graze on fragile acres normally held out of production. `` Our recent scattered rains may have helped in some areas, but certainly they were not dust-busters by any means,'' <PERSON> Branstad </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Branstad </PERSON> said up to 40 percent of the state's pasture has been destroyed by dry weather this spring. <PERSON> Cattlemen </PERSON> said farmers already have started selling off their herds and may speed up the liquidation within the next two weeks if they do not get help. `` It is appropriate to take action early,'' the governor said. `` These are difficult times for our cattle producers.'' <PERSON> Branstad </PERSON> asked <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> officials to activate emergency programs to give farmers financial aid in buying feed and to allow grazing on highly erodable acres taken out of production. <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiese </PERSON> of Manning, president-elect of the <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cattlemen </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said farmers are facing a bleak future because the prime months for growing pasture are April and May `` This is normally when we have lush growth in our pastures,'' he said. `` In many areas of our state, that's just not happening.'' Before any decision can be made on the assistance requests, a county-by-county survey must be completed, something <PERSON> Branstad </PERSON> said could take two weeks. Programs the governor requested include: _ Allowing grazing on Conservation Reserve Program acres, land for which farmers receive annual payments to hold out of production That grazing would be allowed initially for 30 days, but could be extended if dry weather continues. _ Activating an emergency feed program giving up to 5 cents per pound for assistance to farmers purchasing feed _ Activating another feed program, where farmers can purchase feed owned by the government for 75 percent of its loan value `` They do not require any outlay of cash,'' <PERSON> Branstad </PERSON> said, adding he was confident federal officials would approve the request. `` We're not asking for anything that's out of line or that will run into a wall of resistance.'' Government officials, however, have warned that farmers should not expect a massive federal bailout similar to one approved last year due to the drought that gripped much of the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Wiese </PERSON> said cattle farmers need some signal that government will help or many will begin to sell herds. `` We need some assurances to carry on,'' he said. <PERSON> Branstad </PERSON> said the immediate threat was to livestock producers. `` We wo n't really know the impact on crops until much later,'' <PERSON> Branstad </PERSON> said. He said he would seek drought aid for other farmers `` if the drought continues and worsens throughout the year.''
