<HEAD>Cray Posts Large Earnings Decline for First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Cray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the world's biggest supercomputer maker, on Tuesday reported a 94 percent decline in first-quarter earnings and said second-quarter earnings also could be down significantly. The company reported first-quarter net earnings of $ 1.5 million, or 5 cents a share, down from first-quarter earnings of $ 26.4 million, or 85 cents a share, for the same period in 1988. First-quarter revenue was $ 116.1 million, compared with $ 145.9 million for the 1988 quarter. `` We entered the year expecting the delivery of computer systems to be much higher in the second half of the year than the first,'' said <PERSON> Marcelo </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gumucio </PERSON>, president and chief operating officer. `` The revenue results for the first quarter are consistent with that outlook. `` Current delivery schedules indicate that more systems have shifted to the last half of the year and we now expect revenue for the second quarter to be similar to last year's second quarter,'' <PERSON> Gumucio </PERSON> said. But he added, `` We have not changed our objective of achieving a 10 percent revenue increase for the full year.'' <PERSON> Gumucio </PERSON> said all operating areas are exercising strong expense control in line with the company's revenue objective for the full year `` while we continue to invest fully in new product development projects to meet long-term objectives. Expenses will be spread more evenly through the year than revenues. `` This affected earnings in the first quarter and earnings in the second quarter could be down significantly from the same period a year ago for the same reason,'' he said. `` Earnings for the full year will depend primarily on our ability to meet the aggressive delivery schedules for the third and fourth quarters.'' During the first quarter, 13 systems were installed at customer sites, including seven new systems and six used systems. Three of the new systems were leased, as were four of the used systems, <ORGANIZATION> Cray </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Cray </ORGANIZATION> posted a 6 percent increase in net earnings in 1988. It reported $ 756.3 million in revenues and $ 156.6 million in net profit for that year. <ORGANIZATION> Cray </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, employs more than 5,200 people and has manufacturing and development facilities in <LOCATION> Chippewa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Rice </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Colo </PERSON>.
