<SECOND>AM-School TV,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cable Industry Group Plans Programming for Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cable industry leaders are teaming up to encourage use of cable TV programming in the classroom, including a new daily news program that could rival a similar show for schools from <ORGANIZATION> Whittle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> LP </ORGANIZATION>, cable industry and education sources said Tuesday. The effort, which is expected to be announced at a news conference Wednesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, comes on the heels of Whittle's completion of a 25-show test in school classrooms of its commercially-sponsored news program, Channel One. The cable group includes some of the nation's biggest cable programmers and operators led by <ORGANIZATION> Turner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which operates <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> and reportedly will produce the daily news show. The Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> Turner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> scheduled a news conference for Wednesday at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> to announce `` a new venture to benefit American schools.'' Also scheduled to attend were top officials of the cable <ORGANIZATION> networks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Entertainment, C-Span and The Discovery Channel, along with cable operators <ORGANIZATION> Tele-Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cablevision </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> <PERSON> Intercable </PERSON>. Turner spokesmen refused to elaborate on the topic of the news conference and the other participants either declined comment or failed to return calls. But one education industry source, requesting anonymity, said he had been told <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> will disclose plans for a daily news show for use in schools. In addition to <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>'s news show, the other networks either would create new programming or more heavily promote the availability of their existing shows for use in schools, cable industry sources said. `` It will be a mix of programming of current events and some cultural and educational type programming _ a nice mix,'' said one cable executive familiar with the group's plans, discussing it provided he was not identified. It was not clear whether the programming would contain commercials as Whittle's Channel One service does or whether the cable group would donate equipment on the scale of that envisioned in the Channel One project. Whittle launched Channel One, a daily 12-minute news show with two minutes of paid advertising, in six test schools March 6. The schools were each given about $ 50,000 in video equipment, TV monitors and satellite dishes in exchange for agreeing to run the program every school day. The cable industry effort was being viewed in part as a way for the cable industry to show it is being a good citizen at a time when calls have arisen for greater regulation of the industry. It also reflects an effort to protect cable's turf against the entry of an outsider, the <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION>, Tenn.-based Whittle. Turner has been involved for two years in a joint venture with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> called `` News Access'' that has made available <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION>'s `` The Week in Review'' program and a detailed classroom guide with suggestions on how to use portions of the show in schools. The News Access program, which is being used in about 220 schools, relies on schools to use their own equipment to record and show the program. C-Span, the Discovery Channel and the <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Entertainment each have their own arrangements for sharing programs and course guides with schools. But none of those efforts has drawn the attention that Whittle's Channel One test did Whittle is reviewing the results of the seven-week test ended last week and hopes to decide by mid-summer whether to make the program available nationally in the fall of 1990.
