<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesProbe-Survey Bjt   04-25 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Probe-Survey, Bjt,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey: Traders Doing Business as Usual, Resist More Federal Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Traders surveyed by one of the country's largest brokerage firms say they have not changed the way they do business despite the government's investigation of activities at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Eighty percent of more than 1,100 private speculators who responded to the <ORGANIZATION> Lind-Waldock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> survey said disclosure of the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> probe on Jan. 23 had not affected their trading methods, the brokerage firm reported Tuesday. Sixty-nine percent said they believed trading pits at the nation's commodity futures exchanges operate honestly and efficiently _ but 63 percent thought the exchanges could do a better job of policing themselves. `` We wanted to know how our customers felt about the industry,'' said <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lind </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Lind-Waldock </ORGANIZATION>, a Chicago-based futures discount brokerage. With futures trading in the headlines, he said, `` we thought it would be a good time to get information.'' The federal probe of suspected trading fraud at the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION>, the world's two largest futures exchanges, has not yet produced any official charges or indictments. Of those who said they had changed the way they traded, 12 people _ or 1 percent _ said they had stopped trading as a result of the investigation. Others said they changed the type of orders they placed or said they were trading less than before. The survey was of active clients as of March. The brokerage said it did not have an unusual number of clients drop out in January and March as the investigation became known. `` I tend to think we have a image problem,'' <PERSON> Lins </PERSON> said, referring to those who had curtailed their trading. `` It's our fault because of our esoteric business. We have to explain why we are here and the importance of futures trading to the economy.'' Most of those expressing dissatisfaction in the survey opposed more federal regulation of futures trading, saying they feared it would reduce liquidity and volume on the trading floors, increasing the cost of transactions. `` I think the response to that question indicates the public wants reform,'' <PERSON> Lind </PERSON> said. The exchanges understood that when they created committees to recommend changes, he added. The ongoing investigation, in which undercover <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents have posed as traders, reportedly centers on allegations that as many as 100 brokers and traders cheated customers out of millions of dollars. A survey of traders conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> shortly after the federal investigation was revealed indicated that trading violations were numerous at the Mercantile Exchange. The 130 <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> traders responding to the Journal's survey blamed the violations on the way exchange rules are written and enforced. But they said cheating of customers was not common. Last week, a <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> panel recommended that most forms of `` dual trading'' be banned and floor surveillance of trading doubled to prevent wrongdoing. Dual trading, which is legal, enables traders to trade for their own accounts at the same time that they handle customers' orders. The Merc panel also recommended more extensive screening of applicants for membership, reform of the exchange's disciplinary committees and daily computerized trade information on the previous day's trades for members. <ORGANIZATION> Lind-Waldock </ORGANIZATION> conducted its survey in March. It mailed forms to 4,353 of its 13,000 customers and 1,142 replied. `` We were happy at the very high positive response we received and surprised at the extraordinarily high rate of return of our questionnaires,'' <PERSON> Lind </PERSON> said. `` People actually thanked us for the opportunity to voice their opinions.'' Seventy-eight percent said they were well served by the current open outcry system of filling orders. One respondent said attempts to automate trading would decrease confidence in the futures markets because it would take trading out of the public view.
</TEXT>
