<FIRST>u f AM-Exxon Bjt   04-25 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon, Bjt,0723</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Spill Has Generated Wave Of Lawsuits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it has been hit with 31 lawsuits and 1,300 claims ranging from $ 500 to $ 4 million in connection with last month's Alaskan oil spill and expects further suits as well as government fines. At a meeting of securities analysts, top executives of the nation's biggest oil company said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> already had paid $ 400,000 to settle smaller claims brought mainly by fishermen and cannery workers whose jobs were disrupted because of the March 24 spill that fouled hundreds of miles of coastline. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> executives declined to put a dollar value on the existing lawsuits or the claims. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON>, who has been criticized for staying out of sight in the crucial days following the disaster, said that in retrospect he would have responded differently. However, he said he did not understand the public anger against the company, especially because it had accepted the blame and apologized for the spill and was cleaning it up. `` I'm angry with myself,'' <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> said. `` It's not really clear to me as to why everyone is so angry _ once we get past the point of admitting it was our ship that went on the rocks.'' <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> said all but two of the lawsuits were class actions against the company. All but one were filed in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> state and federal courts, he said, with the remaining suit filed in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> has four separate insurance policies totaling $ 599.8 million in cleanup and liability coverage, including a $ 400 million policy that would pay off even in cases of company negligence. But <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> said the various policies ca n't necessarily be added together. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> said the insurance would cover most, if not all, of the cleanup costs and that `` therefore it's impossible for us at this point to make any provision for our earnings for any reserves.'' On Monday, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> announced that it had charged $ 30 million against first-quarter earnings for expenses associated with the salvage and repair of the broken tanker but not for the cleanup itself. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> also said the company probably was subject to fines but did not yet know what fines various government agencies might impose. <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> said the company did not anticipate any punitive damages due to the spill, in which an Exxon tanker ran onto a reef and spewed more than 11 million gallons of crude oil into Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. `` There obviously was no intent on our part _ to put a very expensive ship on <PERSON> Bligh </PERSON> reef, to put expensive oil in the water and then a very, very, very expensive cleanup,'' <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> said. In response to criticism that <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> did not have enough people working on the cleanup, <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> would increase the number to about 4,000 by next month. He also reiterated his optimism that, despite concerns by <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> officials, the major part of the spill would be cleaned up by September. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> told a news conference Monday that the cleanup was ahead of the pace calculated in the oil company's federally-approved plan, which estimates cleanup completion by Sept. 15. When questioned about the impact of a possible boycott against <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> said that with anticipated tight supplies and high demand during the summer season, `` it's hard to see this summer how we would n't be able to sell all the gasoline we can make.'' A number of consumer activists have called for a boycott of <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> to punish the company for what they claim is its poor response to the disaster and alleged negligence leading to the spill. `` The boycott will damage the dealers who are independent business people,'' <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> said the spill has n't changed <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s outlook or spending plans. He also declined to specify when the company would declare its next dividend, which generally is issued quarterly. As to changing <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s tarnished image, he said, `` It's pretty clear there's a better way to do that job, but we have n't had time to sort that out. We're going to have to do a hell of a lot better job than we have done.''
