<HEAD>Bush: High Five To High Tech</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> quoted several sports figures _ <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lasorda </PERSON>, <PERSON> Satchel </PERSON> <PERSON> Paige </PERSON> and <PERSON> Woody </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> _ and gave a `` high five to high tech'' during a pep talk on competitiveness Tuesday in <LOCATION> Silicon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. Critics complained, however, that he did n't say enough about unfair trade by foreign competitors in his speech before business leaders and workers at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION>'s Space Systems Division. After <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> received boos for his reference to <PERSON> Lasorda </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dodgers </ORGANIZATION> manager who is an enemy to <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Giants </ORGANIZATION> fans, the president won applause for advocating a cut in the capital gains tax and a boost in spending for <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> and other science and technology. He praised <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION>, which recently delivered the first of two communications Superbird satellites to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in a $ 209 million contract, as a good example of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s ability to compete internationally. `` Today, American satellites are among the most competitive spacecraft for customers who want affordable, high-powered communications satellites,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. He quoted former pitcher <PERSON> Satchel </PERSON> <PERSON> Paige </PERSON> _ `` Do n't look back. Somebody might be gaining on you.'' _ and said <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> must invest in the future by developing new programs to accommodate a changing workforce. As an example, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> cited <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s Employee Assistance Program, which helps workers find child-care help. Though <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> offered no new strategies for increasing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> productivity or improving <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s ability to compete abroad, his appearance in the nation's high-technology capital early in his term showed an eagerness to stimulate business. `` I think it fires up the people to want to be competitive, to realize they're making progress, and to want to be in the forefront of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s success for exports and products for our own use,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Berry </PERSON>, vice president and general manager of <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s Space Systems Division <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoeber </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s commercial space programs operations, led <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on a tour of the facility's space environmental chamber, which duplicates temperatures in space, and showed him the next Superbird satellite. `` This is a case study to show American businessmen what is possible if they're willing to take the time and make the investment in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and other countries,'' said <PERSON> Hoeber </PERSON>. `` There's no reason why Americans ca n't be as competitive as anyone else. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON>, mayor of <LOCATION> Sunnyvale </LOCATION> in the heart of <LOCATION> Silicon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, criticized <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for saying very little about fair, free trade and the restrictive policies of other countries. But Stone commended <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for returning to an area that he lost `` fairly handily'' in the November election. `` He came back within the first 100 days and gave a message that I think will be widely accepted by the corporations here _ the capital gains tax and the extension on research and development tax credits.'' Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, the first-term <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> congressman and <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> professor who represents much of <LOCATION> Silicon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, accompanied <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on his first domestic speaking tour since entering office. `` The R & amp; D tax credit is so important and the capital gains tax is critical,'' <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> said. `` He's hitting it in every speech.'' <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> said he talked with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aboard Air Force One about other ways to boost competitiveness, including improving access to foreign markets, ending excessive litigation and guarding against transferring technology to other countries that could hurt <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> business. `` We talked explicitly about access to foreign markets in connection with the semiconductor agreement to sell to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did not mention the semiconductor problem in his speech.
