<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar finished higher against most major currencies Tuesday, recovering from an early selloff. Gold prices declined slightly in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dealings after edging a bit higher on foreign markets. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted a bid of $ 384.75 for a troy ounce of gold at 4 p.m. EDT, $ 2 lower than Monday's late bid. <PERSON> Zlatko </PERSON> <PERSON> Glamuzina </PERSON>, chief currency dealer at <ORGANIZATION> Banco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> di </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sicilia </ORGANIZATION>, said dealers sold dollars after the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> released a report on `` big ticket'' durable goods orders. The reported said orders rose 0.8 percent in March. But, excluding the increase in the volatile transportation category, orders were off 2.8 percent and analysts interpreted the figure as evidence of slower economic growth. A report from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> said sales of existing homes dropped for the third straight month in March to the slowest pace in more than a year, an indication that rising mortgage interest rates are discouraging home buyers. On the inflation front, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said wages and salaries paid American workers in private industry rose 4.2 percent in the last 12 months, the biggest jump in 3 -LCB- years. The Employment Cost Index reading was consistent with recent reports pointing to a buildup in inflationary pressures in a tight job market. <PERSON> Glamuzina </PERSON> said the dollar slowly recovered amid mainly institutional buying. Trading was fairly subdued, he said. The markets were quiet ahead of the first-quarter <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> gross national product report due on Wednesday, foreign exchange dealers said. The announcement that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> will resign focused attention on the yen. The Japanese currency was firmer as a result. The dollar closed at 131.17 yen, down from Monday's late 131.38. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> late Tuesday, the dollar traded higher at 131.28 yen, and at 131.475 yen in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, down from 131.55 yen Monday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> one British pound cost $ 1.7030 late Tuesday, cheaper for buyers than Monday's late level of $ 1.7050. Sterling stood at $ 1.69945 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> compared to $ 1.70625 Monday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Monday's levels, included: 1.86655 West German marks, up from 1.86075; 1.64625 Swiss francs, up from 1.6420; 1.18925 Canadian dollars, unchanged; 6.3175 French francs, up from 6.3070; and 1,367.20 Italian lire, up from 1,364.625 Other late rates for the dollar in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> compared with Monday's late rates included: 1.8625 West German marks, up from 1.8575; 1.6435 Swiss francs, up from 1.6395; 6.3065 French francs, up from 6.2975; 2.1000 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0960; and, 1.1910 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1890 Italian markets were closed for a holiday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar closed at 1,366.00 Italian lire, up from 1,362.50 in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> on Monday. Gold bullion prices rose by less than $ 1 an ounce on markets abroad and then fell in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trading. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery fell to $ 385.70 a troy ounce from 