<HEAD>USX Profits Rise; Bethlehem Profits Fall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s profits shot up 88 percent while <ORGANIZATION> Bethlehem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s profits fell 24 percent, the nation's biggest and second-biggest steelmakers said Tuesday in first-quarter reports. Pittsburgh-based <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> said its net income surged 88 percent to $ 296 million, or $ 1.09 per share, led by a near three-fold increase in operating income at <ORGANIZATION> Marathon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Operating income from steel sagged 40 percent to $ 99 million on sales of $ 1.5 billion Income from continuing operations at <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> shrank from $ 7 million to $ 3 million even though sales grew 42 percent from $ 276 million to $ 393 million. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Gas eported operating income of $ 147 million, but $ 144 million of that came from the settlement of lawsuits concerning take-or-pay supply contracts, said company spokesman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryder </PERSON>. Overall sales grew by 12.5 percent to $ 4.5 billion from $ 4.0 billion in the 1988 first quarter, when profits were $ 157 million, or 52 cents per share. Marathon contributed operating income of $ 241 million on $ 2.4 billion in first-quarter sales compared with $ 84 million on $ 2.1 billion in sales a year earlier. `` Second-quarter operating results should be even stronger'' in energy, <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roderick </PERSON> said in a printed statement. Marathon's improvement was the result of higher profit margins on refined products, greater volume and higher prices for crude oil and natural gas and lower exploration costs. The company spent $ 31 million exploring for oil and gas in the first quarter, down from $ 50 million a year earlier. Operating income in steel declined from $ 167 million on sales of $ 1.4 billion. `` The decline ... was due primarily to continued weakness in the oil country tubular goods market and increased costs for raw materials,'' <PERSON> Roderick </PERSON> said. Income from the diversified group of <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> dropped from $ 98 million on $ 341 million in 1988 first-quarter sales to $ 30 million on $ 252 million in sales, reflecting the sale of businesses in the group and a $ 43 million on-time credit last year. <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> received $ 83 million in extraordinary income in the first quarter due primarily to the sale of assets, including the phosphate fertilizer business of the <ORGANIZATION> Agri-Chemicals </ORGANIZATION> dividion and the sale of 25 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Quebec </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cartier </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The company boosted capital spending by $ 143 million to $ 372 million. `` Even after this relatively heavy capital spending ... the corporation's cash balance continues over $ 2 billion,'' <PERSON> Roderick </PERSON> said. `` This cash flow for the first quarter is on track with our goal of generating more than $ 1 billion in 1989, permitting continuation of our program to strengthen our balance sheet and enhance shareholder value.'' <ORGANIZATION> Bethlehem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> said its 24 percent decline was the result of a one-time charge. The <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION>, Pa.-based steelmaker said its net income fell to $ 64.7 million, or 78 cents per share, from $ 85.4 million, or $ 1.23 per share, a year earlier. Sales rose 5.6 percent to $ 1.4 billion from $ 1.33 billion in the comparable period a year earlier. The nation's second-largest steelmaker said it charged $ 55 million against the first quarter as the cost of reorganizing its troubled <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> Division. The division could be hurt further by a strike that was begun March 17 by members of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> said. The 1988 first quarter results included a charge of $ 19 million over a coal mine fire and employee benefits and a $ 10 million credit as an investment tax credit refund. Shipments increased 2 percent from 2.6 million tons to 2.7 million tons. Production declined 1 percent to 3.2 million tons as the company operated at 82 percent of capacity, only 1 percentage point below the 1988 first quarter. Chairman <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said he expects shipments to remain about the same at least through the second quarter. He said second half industry shipments will decline from levels of the first half. <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION>'s future financial performance will be affected by its contract negotiations with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steelworkers </ORGANIZATION> and by the extent to which the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's renews steel import quotas due to expire in September, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said.
