<HEAD>Profits Off at Times Mirror, Washington Post in Absence of One-Time
Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Tops with 1 new graf to include Knight-Ridder. Adds 6 grafs
with Knight Ridder details.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday their first-quarter earnings fell from the levels of last year, when they had one-time gains on asset sales. Another media company, <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, also reported a decline in its first-quarter profit. Times Mirror, owner of the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Newsday </ORGANIZATION> and other papers, said it earned $ 68.8 million, or 53 cents a share, in the first quarter, down 8 percent from $ 75.1 million, or 58 cents a share, a year earlier. First-quarter sales rose 9.3 percent to $ 846.9 million from $ 774.6 million a year earlier. The Times Mirror results for the first quarter of 1988 included an after-tax gain of $ 15.3 million from sale of timberland and of Times-Mirror Press. If that gain were excluded, this year's profit would have risen 15 percent, the Los Angles-based media concern said. Newspaper publishing revenue, hurt in recent months by soft demand for advertising, rose 11 percent in the quarter because of higher advertising volume, cost-cutting and the fact the accounting period was five days longer than last year's. Advertising performance improved at the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> Sun papers, but continued slow in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Revenue rose 9 percent for book, magazine and other publishing and 17 percent for cable television. Broadcast TV revenue declined less than 1 percent. In addition to the Times, <ORGANIZATION> Newsday </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> Sun papers, <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> holdings include The <ORGANIZATION> Hartford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Courant </ORGANIZATION>, The -LRB- <LOCATION> Allentown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION> -RRB- Morning Call, The -LRB- <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION> -RRB- Advocate and <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION> -RRB- Time; <ORGANIZATION> KDFW-TV </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and other publishing, broadcast and cable TV operations. <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, which owns the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> newspaper and <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION> and has interests in TV stations and cable television, said its earnings tumbled 71 percent to $ 41.5 million, or $ 3.22 a share, in the first quarter from $ 144.8 million, or $ 11.25 a share, a year earlier. First-quarter revenue rose 6.5 percent to $ 341.9 million from $ 321.2 million a year earlier. The 1988 results had included a non-recurring gain of $ 115.7 million from the sale of cellular telephone interests. Excluding that gain, the company said its earnings would have risen 42 percent from a year earlier. Newspaper division revenue rose 7 percent in the latest quarter as advertising lineage at the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> edged up 3 percent. Revenue from the company's four television stations rose 5 percent and cable division revenue rose 13 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION>'s revenue rose 1 percent from a year ago Miami-based <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> said its profit fell 39.3 percent to $ 20.5 million, or 39 cents a share, from $ 33.8 million, or 59 cents a share, a year earlier. First-quarter revenue rose 10.4 percent to $ 540.7 million from $ 489.7 million a year earlier. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON>, senior vice president and chief financial officer, said, `` This was a difficult quarter, but the results were just about what we expected when we set our 1989 budget.'' He said more than half of the decline was due to acquisitions, including the purchase of <ORGANIZATION> Dialog </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> and an investment in a cable operation, while the rest reflected `` softness in operations and higher interest rates.'' He said he expected growth in earnings per share for the year, partly because of softening newsprint prices, stronger operating results from the newspaper division and growth in business information services. He said the company also expects to benefit from lower interest costs as the result of the previously-disclosed agreements to sell its eight television stations and two newspapers. <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> owns 30 newspapers, offers a variety of electronic business information services and has interests in cable television.
