<HEAD>Thousands to Receive Refund on Overcharge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> plans to give refunds to thousands of customers in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> after one man complained he was overcharged $ 60 by the long-distance telephone company. Sprint officials have acknowledged that thousands of their 22,000 Las Vegas customers were overcharged from April through August of 1988 because computers recorded the wrong time of day for the phone calls. The mistake also affected credit-card customers dialing from <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>. Sprint officials declined to estimate how much the refunds would be. The refunds were prompted by <PERSON> Lenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Frome </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> resident who complained about a billing error to the company last year. <PERSON> Frome </PERSON>, a retired aerospace engineer who teaches mathematics at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nevada-Las </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vegas </ORGANIZATION>, figured the company owed him about $ 60 in overcharges. When he felt the company was delaying in resolving the issue, <PERSON> Frome </PERSON> took his complaint to former Sen. Chic Hecht, R-Nev., who passed it along to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Furtney </PERSON>, a vice president of corporate relations for <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday the company was correcting the situation when the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> notified <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> about the complaint. <PERSON> Furtney </PERSON> defended any delays in dealing with <PERSON> Frome </PERSON>, saying erroneous charges are `` hard to find in a company that's generating billions of dollars in revenues.'' `` It's like looking for a needle in a haystack,'' he said. <PERSON> Furtney </PERSON> said the company plans to identify all overcharged customers within two weeks. He said customers should receive refunds within a month after that.
