<FIRST>r f AM-CropOutlook     04-25 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crop Outlook,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Yields Could Drop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A private analyst said Tuesday that poor moisture reserves in much of the nation's midsection have already taken a modest bite out of this year's crop yields and that the situation could worsen if the rains are n't abundant this spring. Economist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Schnittker </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> Schnittker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, a Washington-based agricultural consulting firm, said that the 1988 drought `` remains the leading force in world agriculture,'' at least until more is known about this year's crops of wheat and corn. Both <PERSON> Schnittker </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> project huge declines in world and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inventories as a result of last year's drought-shriveled yields in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> By July 1, he said, the global grain inventory going into the new 1989-90 season will be down to a 61-day supply, compared with an 87-day reserve last summer. That will be the smallest reserve since the early 1970s, when global grain stocks were drawn down to a 57-day supply. Speaking to a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journalists </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Schnittker </PERSON> said the supply situation puts the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` sort of on the razor's edge'' because of the uncertainties about 1989 crop conditions. Although many areas are dramatically improved from last year's summer drought, parts of the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> and Corn Belt are still woefully dry Even in some areas that have moderate surface moisture, the reserves deep in the subsoil are scant. `` And if we do have a second adverse crop-growing season, the effect will be substantially larger in the commodities markets and in the consumer food retail markets than they have been the past year,'' <PERSON> Schnittker </PERSON> said. The reduced 1988 harvests forced up market prices for the major crops as it became apparent that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> granary would be partially emptied. <PERSON> Schnittker </PERSON> said he finds himself `` disagreeing quite a lot'' with <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s chief meteorologist, <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> <PERSON> Strommen </PERSON>, who told the farm writers earlier that he was still optimistic that crop conditions will improve and that nationally the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can have a productive year. <PERSON> Strommen </PERSON> and others maintain the fate of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> winter wheat crop will not be known for another month or so and that farmers still have not planted spring wheat or made much of a dent in planting corn. `` If I seem a little on the optimistic side, it may be that I'm looking at changes that have occurred and the improvements that have taken place since the fall of 1988 and the real harshness of the 1988 drought,'' <PERSON> Strommen </PERSON> said Acknowledging there are pockets of drought problems still around _ <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, for example, where about 75 percent of the winter wheat is reported in very poor or poor condition _ <PERSON> Strommen </PERSON> said many other sections of the country have had good moisture last year in recent months. `` When you put all of the big parts together, the overall outlook for the country is much improved over what it was last year,'' <PERSON> Strommen </PERSON> said. `` But we are still deeply concerned about the pockets and the problems we have in the western <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> and the central part of the Corn Belt.'' <PERSON> Schnittker </PERSON> said <PERSON> Strommen </PERSON> `` may turn out to be right, but it seems to me, with the extreme ... subsoil drought concentrated on the central Corn Belt at the moment, that it is prudent for private forecasters, at least, to reduce the probable corn yield a little bit.'' Already, he said, the moisture problems have shaved this year's average corn yield If all had been normal, the yield trend pointed to an average of about 120 bushels per acre, but <PERSON> Schnittker </PERSON> says he thinks 115 bushels are more likely. That would mean a 1989 corn harvest of about 7.54 billion bushels, up from 5.1 billion bushels estimated for 1988. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> currently estimates last year's corn harvest at 4.92 billion bushels but has not projected the 1989 crop. Based on April 25 conditions, <PERSON> Schnittker </PERSON> forecast this year's total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat harvest at 2.15 billion bushels, about 300 million bushels less than the output would be if moisture conditions had been normal Last year's wheat harvest was 1.81 billion bushels.
</TEXT>
