 corresponding increase in product prices, the company said. However, domestic exploration and production results benefited from the higher crude prices. <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said its first-quarter earnings fell to $ 429 million, or $ 1.04 a share, from $ 549 million, or $ 1.33 a share, in the comparable 1988 quarter. Revenue totaled $ 14 billion, up slightly from $ 13.9 billion in last year's first quarter. <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> attributed the profit decline to volatile crude prices, which resulted in a 44 percent drop in the company's refining and marketing earnings. Exploration and production earnings were off 22 percent. However, <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> predicted that a continued rise in product prices, including gasoline, could produce a turnaround in the second quarter. San Francisco-based <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> reported net income of $ 313 million, or 91 cents a share, down from $ 653 million, or $ 1.91 a share, in the same period last year. Revenue totaled $ 7.7 billion, up from $ 7.5 billion. <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Derr </PERSON> noted that crude oil in November cost about $ 13 a barrel, but had risen to $ 20 a barrel by the end of the quarter. He said prices at the gas pump did not increase fast enough to make up the difference. <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> reported after-tax profit of $ 67 million, or 24 cents a share, down sharply from $ 113 million, or 52 cents a share. Sales were $ 5.1 billion, compared with $ 4.5 billion in 1988's first quarter. The Los Angeles-based company said the 1988 results included a net gain of $ 53 million from the issuance and sale of stock by one of its subsidiaries. <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> said the first-quarter results reflected the early pay