<HEAD>Report: United Airlines To Order 190 Boeing Jets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> plans to announce Wednesday that it is ordering 190 narrow-body jets worth $ 7.5 billion from <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, according to a published report. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said Tuesday it would hold a news conference in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> on Wednesday to make an important announcement, but it declined to disclose its purpose. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, quoting industry sources, reported in Wednesday's editions that the airline would announce it was buying 90 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 757s to be delivered starting in August 1989, and 100 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s, of which 35 are firm orders and the rest options. The carrier's management said previously that it intended to place a significant jet order. <PERSON> Julius </PERSON> <PERSON> Maldutis </PERSON>, an airline analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Solomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said the order was designed to counter recent major jet orders by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>. He added that he expected <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> to place another order in the summer for wide-body aircraft such as the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 or the <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. MD-11
